{"title_page": "Royal tours of Canada by the Canadian Royal Family", "text_new": "{{short description|Tours of Canada by the Canadian Royal Family}}\n[[File:His Majesty King George VI and Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth coming up the walkway with a view of the harbour of Victoria in the background.jpg|thumb|A crowd in [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], [[British Columbia]] watch [[King George VI]] and his [[List of royal consorts of Canada|royal consort]], [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]] coming up the walkway during their [[1939 royal tour of Canada]].]]\n'''Royal tours of Canada by the Canadian Royal Family''' have been [[List of royal tours of Canada (18th-20th centuries)|taking place since 1786]],<ref name=DCH>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/services/past-royal-tours/royal-visits-1786-1951.html|title=Royal Visits from 1786 to 1951|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=2 February 2019|date=24 October 2018}}</ref> and [[List of royal tours of Canada (21st century)|continue into the 21st century]], either as an official tour, a working tour, a vacation, or a period of military service by a member of the royal family. Originally, official tours were events predominantly for Canadians to see and possibly meet members of their [[Monarchy of Canada#Canada's royal family and house|Canadian Royal Family]], with the associated patriotic pomp and spectacle. However, nearing the end of the 20th century, such occasions took on the added dimension of a theme; for instance, the 2005 tour of [[Saskatchewan]] and [[Alberta]] by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], was deemed to be a vehicle for the Queen and Canadians to honour \"The Spirit of Nation Builders.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.ab.ca/premier/royalvisit/index_the_visit.cfm |last=Office of the Premier of Alberta |authorlink=Premier of Alberta |title=Premier Ralph Klein > Royal Visit > The Visit > Theme |publisher=Queen's Printer for Alberta |accessdate=3 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007233437/http://www.gov.ab.ca/premier/royalvisit/index_the_visit.cfm |archivedate=7 October 2008 }}</ref> The couple's tour in 2010 was themed \"Honouring the Canadian Record of Service{{mdash}} Past, Present and Future.\"<ref>{{Citation| last=Kennedy| first=Mark| title=A constitutional crisis likely looms for Canada's next governor general| newspaper=Vancouver Sun| date=28 September 2010| url=https://vancouversun.com/news/constitutional+crisis+likely+looms+Canada+next+governor+general/3592493/story.html| accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref> Official royal tours have always been vested with civic importance, providing a regionalised country with a common thread of loyalty.<ref>{{Cite book| last=Coates| first=Colin MacMillan| title=Majesty in Canada: essays on the role of royalty| publisher=Dundurn Press Ltd.| year=2006| location=Toronto| page=11| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FhFyvhpPx8MC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false| isbn=978-1-55002-586-6}}</ref>\n\nThe first member of the royal family to visit [[Canada]] was the future [[William IV of the United Kingdom|King William IV]], who arrived on the country's east coast in 1786 while an officer in the [[Royal Navy]]. His niece, [[Queen Victoria]], never came to Canada, but during her reign her son, the future [[Edward VII|King Edward VII]], made the first modern Canadian royal tour: partaking in official engagements, meeting politicians and the public, and reviewing troops.<ref>{{Cite book| last=Pigott| first=Peter| title=Royal Transport: An Inside Look at the History of Royal Travel| publisher=Dundurn Press| year=2005| location=Toronto| page=14| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8WSLImiMDhAC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=&f=false| isbn=978-1-55002-572-9| ref=CITEREF_Pigott_2005}}</ref> There had been many invitations since 1858 for the reigning monarch to tour Canada,<ref>{{Cite book| last=Bousfield| first=Arthur|author2=Toffoli, Gary|  title=Royal Spring: The Royal Tour of 1939 and the Queen Mother in Canada| publisher=Dundurn Press| year=1989| location=Toronto| page=5| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Go5p_CN8UQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_navlinks_s#v=onepage&q=&f=false| isbn=1-55002-065-X}}</ref> but in 1939 [[King George VI]] was the first to do so. During that trip, the King's wife, [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]], initiated the tradition of the \"royal walkabout\",<ref>{{Harvnb| Pigott| 2005| p=21}}</ref> though her brother-in-law, the former [[Edward VIII|King Edward VIII]], had often met ordinary Canadian people in 1919; as he said: \"Getting off the train to stretch my legs, I would start up conversations with farmers, section hands, miners, small town editors or newly arrived immigrants from Europe.\"<ref>{{Citation| last=Edward, Prince of Wales| author-link=Edward VIII| year=1919| publication-date=2005| contribution=Diary| editor-last=Pigott| editor-first=Peter| title=Royal Transport: An Inside Look at the History of Royal Travel| page=33| publication-place=Toronto| publisher=Dundurn Press| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8WSLImiMDhAC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=&f=false| isbn=978-1-55002-572-9| accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nRoyal tours can take more than a year to organize. The planning is coordinated by the [[Canadian Secretary to the Queen]].<ref name=Globe>{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/behind-the-royal-tour-a-businesslike-usher-of-the-black-rod/article615591/| last=Paperny| first=Anna Mehler| title=Behind the royal tour, a businesslike Usher of the Black Rod| date=26 June 2011| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> The regions to be visited are decided by a rotational formula.<ref name=Globe/> Modern tours have run with a theme; for instance the visit of Elizabeth II and the Duke of Edinburgh in 2010 was intended to highlight \"the Canadian record of service\u2014past, present and future\";<ref>{{Cite journal| last=Treble| first=Patricia| title=The Queen's man on the ground| journal=Maclean's| issue=July 2010| publisher=Rogers Communications| location=Toronto| date=8 July 2010| url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2010/07/08/the-queens-man-on-the-ground/| issn=0024-9262| accessdate=10 July 2010}}</ref> themes are decided upon by the Queen's secretary together with the [[Minister of Canadian Heritage]] and the [[Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)|Office of the Prime Minister]].<ref name=Globe/>\n{{toc limit|3}}\n\n==18th century==\n===1780s===\n[[File:HMS Pegasus.jpg|thumb|{{HMS|Pegasus|1779|6}} in the harbour of [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's]], [[Newfoundland Colony|Newfoundland]]. Commanding ''Pegasus'' from 1786 to 1787, [[William IV of the United Kingdom|Prince William Henry]] was the first member of the Royal Family to visit Canada.]]\nAs an officer in the [[Royal Navy]], Prince William Henry (later [[William IV of the United Kingdom|William IV]]) was the first member of the Royal Family to visit [[Newfoundland Colony]], the colony of [[Nova Scotia]], and the [[Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)|Province of Quebec]] (later [[Lower Canada|Lower]] and [[Upper Canada]]). William's first visit to the colonies was during his command of {{HMS|Pegasus|1779|6}}, a command he was given on 10 April 1786.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=24}} Arriving in Newfoundland, William found himself involved in the civil and naval affairs of Newfoundland, with no permanent civil authorities, and the newly arrived Prince being the senior naval officer in the colony.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=26}} During his time in Newfoundland, he presided over a court, and commissioned the construction of St. Luke's Anglican Church in [[New-Wes-Valley]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=26}} On 21 August 1786, he celebrated his 21st birthday on his ship in the waters off Newfoundland.<ref name=heritage />\n\nHe eventually proceeded to the main base of the Royal Navy's [[North America and West Indies Station|North American Station]], based at the [[Royal Naval Dockyard, Halifax|Royal Naval Dockyards]] in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=26}} Although he received a royal reception upon his arrival to Halifax, it was later made clear he would receive no further special treatment, not already accorded to an officer of his rank in the Royal Navy.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=26}} William visited the Quebec in 1787, travelling as far inland as [[Cornwall, Ontario|Cornwall]]. While there, he encouraged the [[United Empire Loyalist]]s to settle the region that later made up Upper Canada.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=27}} Near Cornwall, he also received a reception from members of the [[First Nations]] communities.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Secret of the Crown: Canada's Affair with Royalty|publisher=House of Anansi|chapter=2|isbn=1-7708-9055-6|year=2012|last=Fraser|first=John}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his visit to Quebec, William was stationed in the West Indies. Depressed over the departure of [[Horatio Nelson]], who he befriended during his time in the Caribbean, he took HMS ''Pegasus'' to Halifax, without permission from the Royal Navy.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=27}} William was ordered to winter in Quebec, although he would take his ship back to Britain, arriving in [[Portsmouth]] in December 1787.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=28}}\n\nWilliam received his second posting to [[British North America]] in July 1788, as the commander of {{HMS|Andromeda|1784|6}}. He served in North America for another year, stationed in cities including Halifax.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=27}}\n\n===1790s===\n[[File:Prince Edward By William J Weaver.png|upright|thumb|left|[[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn|Prince Edward]] with the [[Order of the Garter|Star of the Garter]], voted to him by the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]] in 1798.]]\n[[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn]] became the second member of the Royal Family to tour the Canadian colonies, and the first to live there for an extended period of time. Stationed at [[Gibraltar]] in 1790, he requested to be transferred to the Canadian colonies, in an effort to avoid the extreme Mediterranean heat.<ref>{{cite book|title=Prince Edward, Duke of Kent: Father of the Canadian Crown|page=56|year=2013|last=Tidridge|first=Nathan|publisher=Dundurn Press|isbn=1-4597-0790-7}}</ref> Arriving in [[Quebec City]] in 1791, he came as the colonel for the [[Royal Fusiliers|7th Regiment of Foot]], a military unit garrisoned in Quebec.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=30}} Shortly after his arrival, Edward was called upon by the [[Guy Carleton, 1st Baron Dorchester|Lord Dorchester]], the [[List of Governors General of Canada#Governors-in-Chief/Governors General of the Canadas, 1786\u20131841|Governor-in-Chief of the Canadas]], as 40 First Nations chiefs travelled to Quebec City to complain about American border incursions. Taking advantage of Edward's princely status, the Governor-in-Chief presented the Prince to First Nations' chiefs proclaiming \"Brothers! Here is Prince Edward, son of our king, who has just arrived with a chosen band of his warriors to protect this country,\" and subsequently named Edward as second-in-command of British forces in [[the Canadas]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=30}}\n\nEdward began to tour the Canadas in August 1791, departing from Quebec City to [[Montreal]], [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]], the [[Thousand Islands]], and [[Niagara-on-the-Lake|Newark-on-the-Lake]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=32}} Edward returned to Quebec City in time to act as an observer for the election of the first [[Legislative Assembly of Lower Canada]], in [[Charlesbourg, Quebec City|Charlesbourg]] in June 1792.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=33}} Edward is credited with the first use of the term \"Canadian\" to mean both [[French Canadian|French]] and [[English Canadians|English]] settlers in the Canadas. Witnessing a riot breaking out between two groups at the polling station, he entreated the public in French, \"I urge you to unanimity and concord. Let me hear no more of the odious distinction of English and French. You are all His Britannick Majesty's beloved Canadian subjects.\"{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=33}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Prince Edward, Duke of Kent: Father of the Canadian Crown|page=90|year=2013|last=Tidridge|first=Nathan|publisher=Dundurn Press|isbn=1-4597-0790-7}}</ref>\n\nWith the outbreak of the [[French Revolutionary War]], Edward was promoted to Major-General, and ordered to proceed to the Caribbean in January 1794. As the [[St. Lawrence River]] was frozen over for the winter, he was to travel overland to [[Boston]], before boarding a ship bound for [[Battle of Martinique (1794)|Martinique]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Prince Edward, Duke of Kent: Father of the Canadian Crown|publisher=Dundurn|first=Nathan|last=Tidridge|year=2013|isbn=1-4597-0791-5}}</ref> In doing so, he became the first member of the Royal Family to enter the newly-formed [[United States]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=36}}\n\nFollowing the West Indies campaign in the spring of 1794, he sailed for Halifax aboard {{HMS|Blanche|1786|6}}. Arriving on 10 May 1794, he left the city in June to tour Nova Scotia, and the newly-established colony of [[New Brunswick]], visiting [[Annapolis Royal]], and [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=36}} He was later made the [[Commander-in-Chief, North America#Commanders-in-Chief, Maritime provinces 1783\u20131875|Commander-in-Chief of the Maritimes]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=36}} During his time in Nova Scotia, he presided over the expansion of Halifax, and improved the [[Halifax Citadel#Halifax Defence Complex|city's defences]], due in part to his ability to secure funds from [[London]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=37}} He also worked to improve communications between the Canadian colonies, creating the first telegraph signal system in North America, and improving mail service between Halifax and Lower Canada.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=37}}{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=39}} Edward departed for Britain in August 1800, although he formally maintained his position as Commander-in-Chief of the region until 1802.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=39}} In 1811, Edward sought to obtain the appointment as the Governor General of the Canadas, although failed to do so.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=41}}\n\n==19th century==\nThe 19th century saw the beginning of modern royal tours in the country, with travel becoming easier and faster due to technological innovations such as the [[steamship]], and [[rail transport]]s. The mid-19th century marked the final time a member of the royal family made a [[transatlantic crossing]] by [[sailing ship]]; as royal family members began to travel by steamship in the late-19th century. While travelling through Canada, multiple modes of transportation were used when touring within Canada, including rail, on foot, and various-sized water vessels.\n\n===1860 royal tour===\nOn the 14 May 1859, the [[Legislative Assembly of the Province of Canada]] petitioned [[Queen Victoria]], and other members of the royal family to visit [[Montreal]] for the opening of [[Victoria Bridge (Montreal)|Victoria Bridge]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=42}} Unwilling to leave London in the hands of rivaling politicians, Victoria instead accepted the Canadian invitation on behalf of her son, Albert Edward, the Prince of Wales (later [[Edward VII]]).{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=42}} The Prince of Wales undertook a two-month tour of Newfoundland, New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, [[Prince Edward Island]], and the [[Province of Canada]] in 1860. The Prince of Wales' royal tour was used as the standard model for future royal tours for the next century.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=42}}\n\n====Newfoundland, and Maritime colonies====\n[[File:Arrival of the Prince of Wales at St. John's, Newfoundland, July 23, 1860 (NYPL Hades-165489-EM11624).tiff|thumb|left|The arrival of [[Edward VII|Albert Edward, Prince of Wales]] aboard HMS ''Hero'', in St. John's harbour, July 1860.]]\nThe Prince of Wales reached St. John's, Newfoundland, on 24 July 1860, aboard HMS ''Hero''.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=44}} The welcome reception the Prince of Wales received set the pattern for other welcome receptions during the royal tour, which typically included an official address at a [[Levee (ceremony)|levee]], and a formal ball held in the Prince of Wales' honour.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=44}} During his time there, he attended the [[Royal St. John's Regatta|St. John's Regatta]], and was gifted a [[Newfoundland dog]] on behalf of Newfoundlanders.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=44}}<ref name=heritage>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/special/royalvisit2005/history_e.cfm |last=Department of Canadian Heritage |authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion > The Canadian Monarchy > The Royal Presence in Canada > A Historical Overview |publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada |accessdate=14 July 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704031521/http://www.pch.gc.ca/special/royalvisit2005/history_e.cfm |archivedate=4 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nTravelling from St. John's he arrived in Halifax on 2 August. While in Halifax, he visited the [[Prince's Lodge, Nova Scotia|Prince's Lodge]], the country home used by his grandfather, the Duke of Kent and Strathearn.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=45}} From Halifax, the royal party boarded a train and stopped in [[Windsor, Nova Scotia|Windsor]], and [[Hantsport]], where they boarded HMS ''Styx'' to cross the [[Bay of Fundy]] to Saint John.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=46}} On 4 August, the Prince travelled through the [[St John River (New Brunswick)|St John River]] on the steamer ''Forest Queen'' to [[Fredericton]]. During his time there, he attended a royal reception, and inaugurated a park. Following his visit to Fredericton, he travelled to [[Pictou]], Nova Scotia to board HMS ''Hero'', returning to several communities, including Saint John, and Windsor.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=46}}\n\nHe landed at Charlottetown, Prince Edward Island, on 10 August, where he was welcomed by [[George Dundas (colonial administrator)|George Dundas]], the Governor of Prince Edward Island, and proceeded to [[Government House (Prince Edward Island)|Government House]]. There, he held audience with the [[Executive Council of Prince Edward Island]]. Along with formal ball and levee, the Prince toured the countryside around Charlottetown, and visited [[Province House (Prince Edward Island)|Province House]], where he received an addresses from the Executive Council. Upon his departure, he left with the Governor [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]150 for charitable use.<ref>{{cite book| last=Campbell| first=Duncan| title=History of Prince Edward Island| publisher=Bremner Brothers| year=1875| location=Charlottetown| pages=128\u2013130| url=http://www.islandregister.com/campbell/ch1.html| accessdate=11 July 2009| ref=CITEREF_Campbell_1875}}</ref>\n\n====Province of Canada====\n[[File:Prince of Wales lays last stone of Victoria Bridge.jpg|thumb|The Prince of Wales dedicating [[Victoria Bridge (Montreal)|Victoria Bridge]] in Montreal, as a part of his tour of [[Newfoundland Colony|Newfoundland]], [[Prince Edward Island]], [[Nova Scotia]], and the [[Province of Canada]] in 1860.]]\nThe Prince of Wales was formally welcomed into the Province of Canada by a Canadian delegation, who came aboard HMS ''Hero'' near [[Perc\u00e9 Rock]]. The Canadian welcome delegation consisted of the [[Governor General of the Province of Canada]], [[Edmund Walker Head]], and [[Joint Premiers of the Province of Canada|Joint Premiers]], [[George-\u00c9tienne Cartier]], and [[John A. Macdonald]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=46}} Arriving in Quebec City on 17 August, the Prince knighted [[Narcisse-Fortunat Belleau|Narcisse Belleau]], Speaker of the Legislative Council, and [[Henry Smith (Canadian politician)|Henry Smith]], Speaker of the Legislative Assembly. During his time there, he also visited [[Montmorency Falls]], and made an address at the [[Universit\u00e9 Laval]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=47}}\n\nFollowing his visit to Quebec City, the Prince of Wales proceeded towards Montreal aboard HMS ''Hero'', joined by several members of the Legislative Assembly near [[Trois-Rivi\u00e8res]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=47}} Arriving in Montreal, he took a specially-built open railway car to the Victoria Bridge in [[Pointe-Saint-Charles]], and tapped in-place the final-laid stone for the bridge.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=47}} During his five-day stay in Montreal, he stayed at the viceregal residence [[Government House (Quebec)|Spencerwood]], and inaugurated the city's [[Crystal Palace (Montreal)|Crystal Palace]], recalling the favourable impression made by Canadians at the [[The Great Exhibition|Great Exhibition]] in an address to the crowd.<ref name=heritage/>{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=49}}\n\nAt Ottawa, the Prince laid the foundation stone of the [[Centre Block|parliament buildings]], canoed on the [[Ottawa River]], and rode a [[timber slide]] on the [[Chaudi\u00e8re Falls]].<ref>{{Cite book| last=Hubbard| first=R.H.| title=Rideau Hall| publisher=McGill-Queen's University Press| year=1977| location=Montreal and London| pages=[https://archive.org/details/rideauhallillust00hubb/page/8 8\u20139]| isbn=978-0-7735-0310-6| ref=CITEREF_Hubbard_1977| url=https://archive.org/details/rideauhallillust00hubb/page/8}}</ref>{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=50}} Travelling towards [[Toronto]] aboard the steamer ''Kingston'', visits were planned for [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]], and Kingston, although anti-Catholic demonstrators from the [[Orange Order]] prevented the Prince from disembarking. In an attempt to not embroil the Prince in a controversy, [[Henry Pelham-Clinton, 5th Duke of Newcastle|Henry Pelham-Clinton]], the [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State|Under-Secretary of State]] who joined the Prince on his tour, informed mayors that they would not disembark until the demonstrators were dispersed.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=51}} Sailing further west, the Prince visited [[Cobourg]], [[Rice Lake (Ontario)|Rice Lake]], and [[Peterborough]], where he received a reception from the [[Mississaugas]]. He then proceeded to [[Port Hope, Ontario|Port Hope]], re-boarding ''Kingston'' to sail on to Toronto.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=52}}\n\nDuring a levee in Toronto, the Prince received a delegation from Belleville and Kingston, tending apologies for the early incident.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=53}} On 10 September, he took a one-day excursion to [[Collingwood, Ontario|Collingwood]], before returning to Toronto the following day. On his way back, he visited and received addresses from [[Aurora, Ontario|Aurora]], [[Barrie]], [[Bradford, Ontario|Bradford]], and [[Newmarket, Ontario|Newmarket]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=53}} In Toronto, the Prince attended the [[Royal Canadian Yacht Club]]'s regatta, agreeing to become its [[patron]]; and opened [[Allan Gardens]], and [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]] to the public. He departed the city for [[London, Ontario]] on 12 September, visiting [[Guelph]] and [[Stratford, Ontario|Stratford]] on the way.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=53}} From London, he travelled to [[Sarnia, Ontario|Sarnia]], in order to attend a gathering of 150 First Nations representatives in the Province of Canada. Following this gathering, he briefly returned to London, before travelling by railway to the [[Niagara Peninsula]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=53}}\n[[File:H.R.H. Prince of Wales and Suite at Point View, Niagara.jpg|thumb|upright|left|The Prince of Wales touring [[Niagara Falls]], [[Canada West]], September 1860.]] \nIn the peninsula, he visited [[Brantford]], [[Chippewa, Ontario|Chippewa]], [[Fort Erie]], and [[Queenston, Ontario|Queenston]]. The [[Niagara Falls]] were illuminated for the first time during his tour of the falls.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ontariotravel.net/TcisCtrl?site=consumers&key1=experiences&key2=NaturalWonders&language=EN&linkType=I| last=Ontario Tourism Marketing Partnership| title=Things to Do > Natural Wonders > Did You Know?| publisher=Queen's Printer for Ontario| accessdate=2 July 2009}}</ref> There, he rode on the ''[[Maid of the Mist]]''. At Queenston, he met with 160 [[War of 1812]] veterans, dedicated a rebuilt [[Brock's Monument]], and visited [[Laura Secord]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=54}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Toffoli| first=Gary| title=CBC's Attack on Canadian Heritage| journal=Monarchy Canada| publisher=Monarchist League of Canada| location=Toronto| date=10 August 1998| url=http://www.monarchist.ca/mc/cbc.htm| accessdate=2 July 2009| ref=harv| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215171031/http://www.monarchist.ca/mc/cbc.htm| archivedate=15 February 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Morden| first=James Cochenaur| title=Historic Niagara Falls| publisher=Lindsay Press| year=1932| location=Niagara Falls| page=87| url=http://www.ourroots.ca/f/page.aspx?id=591290}}</ref> From Queenston, he moved towards Niagara-on-the-Lake, [[St. Catherines, Ontario|St. Catherines]], and [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=55}}\n\nCompleting his royal tour of the Province of Canada in late-September, the Prince of Wales departed for the United States from [[Windsor, Ontario]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=55}} Taking a month-long personal tour of the United States, he travelled under the pseudonym \"Lord Renfrew,\" in an attempt to not attract attention to himself.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=55}} The Canadian co-premieres saw-off the Prince's during his departure from Canada, and again from the United States, travelling to [[Portland, Maine]] on 20 October 1860 to see the Prince off.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=55}}\n\n===1861\u20131883===\nIn 1861, [[Alfred, Duke of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Alfred]] took a five-week tour of [[The Maritimes]], Newfoundland, and the Province of Canada. While escorting Prince Alfred through [[Canada West]], the Governor General of Canada used the opportunity to make sketches of American defences around the [[Great Lakes]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Civil War Years: Canada and the United States|url=https://archive.org/details/civilwaryearscan0000wink|url-access=registration|year=1998|page=[https://archive.org/details/civilwaryearscan0000wink/page/55 55]|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press|first=Robin W.|last=Winks|isbn=0-7735-6763-1}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1869 to 1870, [[Prince Arthur, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn|Prince Arthur]] was stationed in Canada as a British Army officer in the [[Rifle Brigade (The Prince Consort's Own)|Rifle Brigade's]] Montreal detachment. Arriving in Halifax, he undertook a two-month royal tour of the colony of Prince Edward Island, and the newly formed Dominion of Canada, before returning to military duty in Montreal.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=80\u201381}} In the same year, the [[Six Nations of the Grand River]] conferred the title of chief to Prince Arthur. In a formal ceremony, the chief of the three \"clans\" of the [[Mohawk people|Mohawks]] received The Prince, and conferred upon him the name \"Kavakoudge,\" meaning \"the sun flying from east to west under the guidance of the Great Spirit.\"{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=83}} Although the title of chief was bestowed as an honourary title to a number of individuals, Alfred underwent the necessary rituals to formalize the title in Mohawk society.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=83}}\n[[File:Prince Arthur Mohawk Chapel Canada 1869.jpg|thumb|During his 1869 royal tour, [[Prince Arthur, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn|Prince Arthur]] met with the Chiefs of the [[Six Nations of the Grand River|Six Nations]] at the [[Mohawk Chapel]].]]\nDuring his time in Canada, Prince Arthur became the first member of the royal family to attend the [[opening of the Canadian parliament]], in February 1870.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=81}} Prince Arthur, along with his regiment, was present at the [[Battle of Eccles Hill]], a raid conducted by the American-based [[Fenian Brotherhood]], on 25 May 1870.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=81}} The Prince was awarded the [[Canada General Service Medal]] for his participation in the [[Fenian raids]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=82}} Returning to the United Kingdom in 1870, Prince Arthur would return to Canada on two more occasions, the latter visit as the Governor General of Canada.\n\nOther members of the royal family were also in Canada as a part of their military service during the late-1870s and early-1880s. Prince Alfred was stationed at Royal Naval Dockyard, Halifax from time to time between 1878 and 1883, as Commander of the Royal Navy's North Atlantic Squadron.<ref name=heritage /> [[George V|Prince George of Wales]] (later George V) was stationed in the Maritimes in 1882 as a midshipman on [[HMS Cumberland (1842)|HMS ''Cumberland'']]. During his time there, he drove the last spike into Newfoundland's first railway, the [[Newfoundland Railway|Harbour Grace Railway]].<ref name=RT>{{cite web| url=http://www.railways.incanada.net/circle/Royal_Trains.html| last=Churcher| first=Colin| title=Colin Churcher's Railway Pages > Royal Trains and Royal Occasions| publisher=Colin Churcher| accessdate=12 July 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060217005948/http://www.railways.incanada.net/circle/Royal_Trains.html| archivedate=17 February 2006| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Princess as the viceregal consort (1878\u20131883)====\nIn 1878, [[Benjamin Disraeli]], the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], requested the [[John Campbell, 9th Duke of Argyll|Marquess of Lorne]] be appointed the next [[Governor General of Canada]], with his wife, [[Princess Louise, Duchess of Argyll]] serving as the [[viceregal consort of Canada]]. Disraeli's nomination of Lorne was largely motivated by his desire to see a member of the royal family reside in Canada for an extended period.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=57}} Prior to his appointment as the Canadian Governor General, Lorne was virtually unknown to the public, with little concrete record of public service. The attraction for appointing Lorne to the office was having his spouse, Princess Louise, reside in Canada.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=58}} \n[[File:Opening of Canadian Parliament 1879.gif|thumb|[[Princess Louise, Duchess of Argyll|Princess Louise]] accompanies the [[John Campbell, 9th Duke of Argyll|Marquess of Lorne]], the [[Governor General of Canada]] during the opening the [[4th Canadian Parliament]], 1879.]]\nArriving in Canada on 23 November 1878, the viceregal couple was greeted by Prince Alfred, who was serving as a Royal Navy officer, stationed in Halifax.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=57}} Lorne was formally sworn in as the Governor General in [[Province House (Nova Scotia)|Province House]], Halifax, before they proceeded towards the capital, in Ottawa.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=57}} Arriving in Ottawa on 2 December, the head of the Canadian ministry, [[John A. Macdonald]], was not present at the viceregal welcome reception. Macdonald's absence from the welcome reception was depicted as a purposeful insult to the princess by the [[Official Opposition (Canada)|opposition]] [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=59}} They proceeded to take a private trip to Niagara Falls in January 1879, before returning to Ottawa to open the [[4th Canadian Parliament]], on 13 February 1879.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=60}}\n\nThey undertook an official tour of [[Eastern Canada]] from mid-May 1879, touring Montreal during [[Victoria Day]], awarding prizes to [[officer cadets]] of the [[Royal Military College of Canada]] in Kingston.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=60}}  On 9 June, they opened [[Terrasse Dufferin]] in Quebec City, and later laid the [[cornerstone]] of [[Ramparts of Quebec City|Porte Kent]], gifted to the city from Queen Victoria.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=60}}  Following their tour of Quebec, they proceeded towards [[The Maritimes]] and [[Ontario]]. In Toronto, they opened the first [[Canadian National Exhibition]], and attended the [[Queen's Plate]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=61}}<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.woodbineentertainment.com/queensplate/History.aspx| title=History > History of Queen's Plate| publisher=Woodbine Entertainment Group| accessdate=2 July 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090614063730/http://www.woodbineentertainment.com/queensplate/history.aspx| archivedate=14 June 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> During their time in Ottawa, both Lorne and Louise worked towards the creation of a national arts association, establishing the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]] in 1880.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=66}}\n\nOn 14 February 1880 in Ottawa, Princess Louise was injured after her horse-drawn sleigh was turned over. Hitting her head on the metal frame of the sleigh, Louise suffered from [[neuralgia]] after the incident. The public was not made aware of the event, with the [[aide-de-camp]] to the Governor General downplaying the incident to the press. She did not make another public appearance until April 1880.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=62}} While recovering, she was visited by her brother [[Prince Leopold, Duke of Albany|Prince Leopold]]. Louise and Leopold privately toured Quebec, Ontario, and the American city of [[Chicago]] until 31 July 1880, when both returned to the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=62}} \n[[File:A street market at Christmas time; reindeer, pigs, fruit, tu Wellcome V0040157.jpg|thumb|left|Princess Louise and the Marquess of Lorne visiting a street market in [[Ottawa]] around [[Christmas]], c. 1880s.]]\nDuring Lorne's 1881 tour of the [[Northwest Territories]], he proposed a section of the territory take its Alberta after his wife (whose full name was Louise Caroline Alberta).{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=62}} Similarly, Princess Louise was the one who proposed the name for [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]], from the Latin word for Queen.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=62}}<ref name=Regina>{{cite journal| last=Archer| first=John H.| title=Regina: A Royal City| journal=Monarchy Canada Magazine| volume=Spring 1996| publisher=Monarchist League of Canada| location=Toronto| year=1996| url=http://www.monarchist.ca/mc/regina.htm| accessdate=30 June 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209220023/http://www.monarchist.ca/mc/regina.htm| archivedate=9 February 2008| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nLouise returned to Canada until 4 June 1882, although rumors of a [[Fenian]] plot against her forced her to remain in the [[Citadelle of Quebec]],{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=63}} a military installation used by the [[Canadian militia]], and the secondary residence for the Monarch, and the Governor General. On 30 August, Lorne and Louise set out for an official tour of [[British Columbia]], visiting [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], and meeting with a First Nations delegation in [[New Westminster]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=64}} Louise remained in Victoria as Lorne continued with the official tour into the [[British Columbia Interior]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=64}} They remained in the province until 7 December 1882, with their tour extended to counter secessionist sentiments in the province, a result of the federal government's failure to produce a transcontinental rail link by 1881.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=65}} [[Robert Beaven]], the [[Premier of British Columbia]] was said to have suggested the province secede from Canada, and establish an independent kingdom with Louise as its Queen. The resulting crisis had spurred Lorne to push the Canadian government to hasten the development of the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=65}}\n\nLouise was visited by another member of the royal family, Prince George of Wales, in April 1883.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=65}} Shortly before the end of his fifth year as Governor General, Lorne declined an option to serve the position for another year. His decision to turn down an additional year in office was questioned by some, with Queen Victoria suspecting that Lorne was jealous of Louise's popularity with Canadians, in contrast to his own.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=65}} The Marquess and Princess Louise concluded their term in Canada with a farewell tours in Montreal, and Toronto, leaving for the United Kingdom from Quebec City on 27 October 1883.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=66}}\n\n===1884\u20131900===\nIn 1890, Prince Arthur conducted another tour of Canada, arriving in British Columbia from his earlier service with the British Army in the [[British Raj]]. During this tour, he travelled east towards the Maritimes, primarily by railway, before continuing on to the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=83}}\n\n[[Princess Marie Louise of Schleswig-Holstein|Princess Marie Louise]] arrived in Canada in 1900 to tour the country, however controversy surrounding her spouse, [[Prince Aribert of Anhalt]] forced her to return to the United Kingdom shortly after her arrival. After Prince Aribert was found in bed with another man, his father, [[Frederick I, Duke of Anhalt]], accused Marie Louise of indecency, claiming that his son was denied his conjugal rights. Marie Louise was at [[Rideau Hall]] when the Governor General gave her two telegrams instructing her to return to the United Kingdom immediately.<ref>{{cite book|title=Now You Know \u2014 Heroes, Villains, and Visionaries|year=2013|publisher=Dundurn|last=Lennox|first=Doug|isbn=1-4597-2477-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Twilight of Splendor: The Court of Queen Victoria During Her Diamond Jubilee Year|page=58|last=King|first=Greg|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2007|isbn=0-4700-4439-X}}</ref> Her marriage with Prince Aribert was annulled in December 1900, with his father using his prerogative as a reigning Duke of [[Duchy of Anhalt|Anhalt]] to annul the marriage.\n\n==Early 20th century (1901\u20131950)==\n===1900s===\n====1901 royal tour====\n[[File:Duke of York at Montreal and Quebec 1901.ogv|thumb|alt=George in military dress uniform hands out medals to servicemen, rides in a carriage and inspects a guard of honour|[[George V|Prince George]] in [[Montreal]] and [[Quebec City]]. He visited most of the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|provinces]] during his 1901 royal tour.]]\nThe first royal tour to take place since the death of Queen Victoria was conducted by the second son of the reigning king, Prince George, Duke of Cornwall and York (later George V), his spouse, [[Mary of Teck|Mary, Duchess of Cornwall and York]] (later Queen Mary), and the Duchesses brother, [[Alexander Cambridge, 1st Earl of Athlone|Prince Alexander of Teck]] (later the Earl of Athlone). The tour in Canada formed a part of a larger eight-month royal tour of the [[British Empire]] that began on 16 March 1901, with the Duke and Duchess' departure from [[Portsmouth]], United Kingdom.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=69}}\n\nThe Canadian portion of the tour was originally planned to begin in British Columbia, proceeding eastward through the country. However, after [[South Africa]] was added onto the royal tour, the decision was made to begin to the royal tour in Quebec City, and conclude it in Halifax.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=69}} As the period of court mourning for Queen Victoria's death had not yet expired during their time in Canada, public balls, banquets, and levees planned for the royal tour were cancelled, with only official dinners, concerts, receptions, and reviews taking place.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=70}} During the tour, Prince George kept a methodical record of his activities, recording that he shook the hands of 24,855 people at official receptions; received 544 addresses; laid 21 cornerstones; gave 100 speeches; and presented 4,329 medals.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=75}}\n\nThe Canadian portion of the 1901 royal tour began 16 September 1901, when the {{RMS|Ophir||6}} arrived in Quebec City.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=69}} The royal party{{spaced ndash}}which consisted of 22 people, landed at Quebec City on 16 September. During his time in Quebec City, Prince George invested Lieutenant [[Richard Ernest William Turner]] with the [[Victoria Cross]] for his conduct during the [[Battle of Leliefontein]] in a ceremony at the [[Plains of Abraham]], and spoke to students at the Universit\u00e9 Laval.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=71}} Moving west of Quebec City by railway, the group made stops to Montreal, and Ottawa.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=74}} Throughout the royal tour, Prince George placed an emphasis on praising the creation, and expansion of the country during his own lifetime, giving a speech about the country's development and growth in Ottawa and Winnipeg.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=73\u201374}}\n[[File:Timber slide 1901.jpg|thumb|left|The royal party rides a [[timber slide]] near Ottawa during the 1901 royal tour.]]\nIn Ottawa, Prince George dedicated the [[Alexandra Bridge]] in Ottawa, rode a timber slide, and watched the [[lacrosse]] final for the [[Minto Cup]], a match he enjoyed so much he kept the ball that was used.<ref name=RT /> Departing from Ottawa, they passed through Ontario, creating \"incredible excitement seldom seen since the visit of his father in 1860.\"<ref name=heritage /> The Duke and Duchess arrived in [[Manitoba]] where the former opened the new science building at the [[University of Manitoba]], and then to Regina in the Northwest Territories.<ref name=\"Regina\"/> In [[Calgary]], they met with First Nations chiefs and viewed exhibitions, before concluding their western-leg of their tour in [[Vancouver]] and [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]]. They group then turned back again towards [[Banff, Alberta|Banff]], where the Duchess went to [[Tunnel Mountain]] and [[Lake Louise (Alberta)|Lake Louise]], while the Duke went to Poplar Point.\n\nAfter passing back through Regina,<ref name=Regina /> they reunited in Toronto, welcomed by the [[Toronto Mendelssohn Choir]], and attended concerts at [[Massey Hall]]. They proceeded to tour throughout [[Southern Ontario]], before returning to Montreal, where the Duke opened the newly rebuilt Victoria Bridge. The Canadian tour ended with a trip through Saint John, and their departure from Halifax.<ref>{{Harvnb| Hubbard| 1977| pp=101\u2013106}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Nicolson, Harold|chapter=''Ophir'' itinerary|title= King George V: His Life and Reign|year=1959|page=68|location=NY|publisher=Doubleday|url=https://archive.org/stream/kinggeorgethefif006892mbp#page/n105/mode/2up/search/canada}}</ref> Following their departure from Halifax, the global royal tour proceeded towards Newfoundland, a separate colony not associated with Canada at the time. In Newfoundland, they received nine-month old Newfoundland dog, which was later given their son, [[Edward VIII|Prince Edward]] (later Edward VIII).{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=75}}\n\n====Tercentenary of Quebec City (1908)====\n[[File:(Quebec Tercentenary) Prince of Wales, attended by Earl Grey Col. S.A. Denison, Lord Lovat, Gen. Pole-Carew and Gen. Lake at the Military Review Quebec.jpg|upright|thumb|George, Prince of Wales attending a military review for the [[Canadian militia]], 1908.]]\nIn 1908 the Canadian government asked King Edward VII to preside over the [[tercentenary]] celebrations for the founding of Quebec City. Edward VII would accept the invitation on behalf of his son, George, Prince of Wales (later George V). The Prince of Wales arrived at Quebec City aboard the Royal Navy cruiser, {{HMS|Indomitable|1907|6}}. Unlike his earlier tour in 1901, his royal tour in 1908 was limited to the ceremony in Quebec City, as well as a military review of the Canadian militia on the Plains of Abraham.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=76}}\n\n===1910s===\nFrom 1911 to 1916, Prince Arthur, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn served as Canada's Governor General, with the [[Princess Louise Margaret of Prussia|Duchess of Connaught and Strathearn]] serving as his viceregal consort. The Duke was the first member of the royal family to serve the office of Governor General of Canada. Originally his appointment was for only two-years, although at the request of [[Robert Borden]], the [[Prime Minister of Canada]], his tenure would later be extended to five-years.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=88}}  The Duke, Duchess, and their daughter, [[Princess Patricia of Connaught]], arrived in Quebec City on 13 October 1911 and was later sworn into office at the [[Parliament of Quebec]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=85}} Several weeks after being sworn in, he presided over the opening of the [[Parliament of Canada]] in Ottawa.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=85}} \n\nThe Duke and Duchess conducted his first tour as Governor General in 1911, proceeding to Toronto, Hamilton, Kingston, and finally Montreal on 27 November 1911. Further tours with the Duke, and Princess Patricia, were undertaken in May 1912, to Winnipeg, and the Maritimes.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=85}}  On 28 August 1912, the Duke, Duchess, and their daughter conducted a tour of the west, visiting [[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario|Sault Ste. Marie]], [[Saskatoon]], [[Prince Albert, Saskatchewan|Prince Albert]], [[Edmonton]], Calgary, Banff, Vancouver, [[Prince Rupert, British Columbia|Prince Rupert]], and Victoria, where they inspected personnel of the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] at [[Esquimalt Royal Navy Dockyard]]. They then proceeded towards [[Medicine Hat]], Regina, and [[Brandon, Manitoba|Brandon]], before concluding their tour in Toronto and Ottawa.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=85\u201386}}\n[[File:Postcard of Vice-Regal Visit to Valcartier Military Base 1914.jpg|left|thumb|Prince Arthur visits [[CFB Valcartier|Valcartier base]] as the Governor General in 1914. He served the position from 1911 to 1916.]]\nWhile serving as the Governor General, the Duke inaugurated the [[Saskatchewan Legislative Building]], and laid the cornerstone for the [[Cathedral of St. John the Evangelist (Saskatoon)|Cathedral of St. John the Evangelist]] in Regina,<ref name=UoS>{{Cite book| last=Jackson| first=Michael D.| contribution=Royal Visits| year=1990| title=The Encyclopedia of Saskatchewan| editor-last=Cottrell| editor-first=Michael| place=Regina| publisher=Canadian Plains Research Centre| url=http://esask.uregina.ca/entry/royal_visits.html| accessdate=30 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://scaa.sk.ca/gallery/aerial/landmark_key.html#45| title=Departments > City Clerk's Office > City Archives > Image Galleries > A View From Above > Downtown III: Spadina Crescent to the Bessborough > Note 45| publisher=City of Saskatoon| accessdate=30 June 2009}}</ref> and for the new Provincial Library at the [[British Columbia Parliament Buildings]].<ref name=VanHist>{{cite web| url=http://www.vancouverhistory.ca/chronology1919.htm| last=Davis| first=Chuck| title=History of Metropolitan Vancouver > 1919| publisher=Chuck Davis| accessdate=24 June 2009}}</ref> The Duke returned to Banff on two occasions, in August 1914, and May 1916.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=86}}   In addition to Canada, he also visited [[Dominion of Newfoundland|Newfoundland]], a separate [[dominion]] of the [[British Empire]] in 1914.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=86}}\n\nIn 1913, [[George VI|The Prince Albert]] (later George VI) conducted his first royal tour of the Canada, as well as Newfoundland, while serving aboard the Royal Navy cruiser {{HMS|Cumberland|1902|6}}.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=107}}\n\nIn January 1913, the Duchess was hospitalized as a result of her declining health, with the viceregal family returning to London, UK, in March 1913. During this period, the Duke, continuing to serve as Governor General, received regular correspondences from Borden through [[electrical telegraph|telegraph]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=88}} After the Duchess recovered, the family returned to Canada in October 1913.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=88}} During [[World War I]], the Duke was involved in recruitment, and raising the morale of soldiers.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=89}} Princess Patricia worked for the [[Canadian Red Cross]], and continued working for a Canadian hospital in [[Orpington]], UK, after her father's term as Governor General ended in 1916.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=88}} Several months after Centre Block on Parliament Hill was ravaged by a fire, the Duke laid the memorial cornerstone for its replacement on 1 September 1916. The Duke's tenure as Governor General ended on 16 October 1916.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=90}}\n\n====1919 royal tour====\n[[File:PrinceOfWalesCanoeing.jpg|thumb|[[Edward VIII|Edward, Prince of Wales]] with two [[Ojibwe]] guides, canoe on the [[Nipigon River]] during his 1919 royal tour.]]\nAfter the end of World War I in November 1918, Edward, Prince of Wales (later Edward VIII) set out to develop his role as the [[Prince of Wales]] through a tour of the Empire, with his first tour occurring in the dominions of Newfoundland and Canada in 1919.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=91}} Organization for the tour was undertaken by [[Joseph Pope (public servant)|Joseph Pope]], the Assistant Clerk to the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|Privy Council for Canada]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=93}} Unlike earlier tours, the 1919 royal tour dropped the rigid formalities of earlier tours, partly due to authorities' inability to control the crowds who came to see the Prince.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=93}} The informality of the tour was matched by the Prince of Wales, whose informal dress, and mannerisms had struck the right note with Canadians.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=97}}\n\nBoarding {{HMS|Renown|1916|6}} on 5 August 1919, Edward proceeded towards St. John's, Newfoundland, and Charlottetown, before proceeding towards Quebec City on 21 August 1919. Proceeding towards Ontario, he laid the foundation stone of the [[Peace Tower]] on Parliament Hill, met with the League of Canadian Indians at Sault Ste. Marie, and took a three-day canoe trip down the [[Nipigon River]] to fish and hunt with two [[Ojibwa]] guides.<ref>{{cite journal| last=Whalen| first=James| title=Royalty on the Nipigon| journal=The Archivist| issue=117| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| location=Ottawa| year=1998| url=http://members.shaw.ca/amuir/royally.htm| accessdate=3 July 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070217124035/http://members.shaw.ca/amuir/royally.htm| archivedate=17 February 2007| url-status=dead}}</ref> On the 26 August, he inaugurated Warriors' Day at the Canadian National Exhibition.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=93}}\n\nHe then travelled to Regina, where he renamed a library the ''Prince of Wales Library''. He then proceeded towards [[Vancouver]], toured the area, attended a civic reception and military ball, as well as opening the New Westminster Exhibition.<ref name=VanHist /> While in Alberta, he was named Chief Morning Star by the Chiefs of the [[Nakoda (Stoney)|Nakoda]] First Nations.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=104}} The Prince also went on to Victoria, where he laid the foundation stone of a statue of Queen Victoria on the grounds of the British Columbia Parliament Buildings.<ref name=Legacy>{{cite web| url=http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/legacy.htm| last=British Columbia Archives| title=The Legacy| publisher=Queen's Printer for British Columbia| accessdate=25 June 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228171614/http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/legacy.htm| archivedate=28 February 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===1920s and 1930s===\n[[File:KingRoyals1927.jpg|thumb|Edward, Prince of Wales and [[Prince George, Duke of Kent|Prince George]] at [[Rideau Hall]] (seated, fifth and sixth from the left, respectively), during their 1927 royal tour.]]\nIn 1923, the Prince of Wales was in Canada on a visit, and work on his privately owned ranch, E. P. Ranch. Arriving at Quebec City on 12 September, he made stops in Ottawa and Winnipeg before reaching his private ranch near Calgary, known as E. P. Ranch.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=98}} He made another private visit to his ranch in 1924, as well as touring as well various towns and cities; in the latter year, he stopped at Rideau Hall for various official functions and again frustrated his staff by disappearing for dancing and golf.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hubbard|1977|p=157}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926, the brother to the Prince of Wales, [[Prince George, Duke of Kent|The Prince George]] (later Duke of Kent), arrived in Canada and actively took part in squash, badminton, and tennis games played in Rideau Hall's Tent Room;<ref>{{Harvnb| Hubbard| 1977| p=162}}</ref> the Governor General, [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|The Marquess of Willingdon]], said of the Prince: \"Such a nice boy, but shy, & as mad ib exercise as the P. of W.\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Freeman-Thomas|first=Freeman|author-link=Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|date=29 October 1926|editor-last=Hubbard|editor-first=R.H.|title=Rideau Hall|periodical=1977|publication-place=Montreal and London|publisher=McGill-Queen's University Press|isbn=978-0-7735-0310-6|url=https://archive.org/details/rideauhallillust00hubb}}</ref> Prince George, along with the Prince of Wales, conducted another royal tour of Canada in 1927. During the tour, the Prince of Wales and Prince George opened [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]] and the [[Princes' Gates]] in Toronto.<ref>{{Cite news | authorlink = Mike Filey | last =Filey | first = Mike | title=Union Station turns 80| newspaper=Toronto Sun| date=5 August 2007| url=http://www.torontosun.com/Lifestyle/Columnists/Filey_Mike/2007/08/05/4395354-sun.html| archive-url=https://archive.is/20070930210244/http://www.torontosun.com/Lifestyle/Columnists/Filey_Mike/2007/08/05/4395354-sun.html| url-status=dead| archive-date=30 September 2007| accessdate=6 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n====1939 royal tour====\n{{main|1939 royal tour of Canada}}\n[[File:George VI visits Woodbine Race Track.jpg|thumb|King George VI and Queen Elizabeth visit the [[Queen's Plate|King's Plate]] in [[Toronto]], during the 1939 royal tour.]]\nThe 1939 royal tour of Canada was a cross-Canada royal tour by [[King George VI]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]]. It was one of the first visits of a reigning monarch to Canada (in 1926, [[Queen Marie of Romania]] also visited the country<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19380719&id=1JEjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dqgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6052,2123265 |title=Ovation Given by Montreal |work=Montreal Gazette |via=Google News |date=19 July 1938 |page=12 |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>). This tour marked the first time that the sovereign's official Canadian birthday was marked with the monarch himself present in the country; the occasion was marked on Parliament Hill with a celebration and a [[Trooping the Colour|Trooping of the Colour]].\n\nLater, during a tour of Canada, Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother stated in a speech: \"It is now some 46 years since I first came to this country with the King, in those anxious days shortly before the outbreak of the Second World War. I shall always look back upon that visit with feelings of affection and happiness. I think I lost my heart to Canada and Canadians, and my feelings have not changed with the passage of time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/interactive/royalvisits/52.html| title=CBC: Royal Visits to Canada| publisher=CBC| location=Canada | accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n===1940s===\nThe [[Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone]] resided in Canada from June 1940 to April 1946 as the viceregal consort of Canada; accompanying her spouse, Alexander, Earl of Athlone, who was sworn in as the Governor General of Canada on 21 June.<ref name=Athl>{{cite book|title=Canada's Prime Ministers, Governors General and Fathers of Confederation|last=Coucill|first=Irma|page=[https://archive.org/details/canadasprimemini0000couc/page/84 84]|publisher=Pembrooke Publisher Limited|year=2005|isbn=1-5513-8185-0|url=https://archive.org/details/canadasprimemini0000couc/page/84}}</ref> In addition to the Princess Alice, [[Alastair Windsor, 2nd Duke of Connaught and Strathearn|Alastair, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn]] has also been residing in Canada from 1940, as the aide-de-camp to Alexander in his capacity as Governor General. On 23 April 1943, Alastair was found dead on the floor of his room at Rideau Hall. He had died from hypothermia.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Aronson|first1=Theo|title=Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone|date=1981|publisher=Cassell|location=London|isbn=978-0304307579|page=211}}</ref> Newspapers at the time cited the cause of death as \"natural causes.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11349086 |title=DEATH OF DUKE OF CONNAUGHT IN CANADA |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)]] |issue=30,162 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=28 April 1943 |accessdate=17 April 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n[[File:KingCheersForAthlone.jpg|thumb|[[Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone]] with the [[Alexander Cambridge, 1st Earl of Athlone|Earl of Athlone]] and [[William Lyon Mackenzie King]], March 1946]]\nIn 1941, [[Prince George, Duke of Kent]] visited several [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] bases in Canada.<ref name=DCH/> In the same year, Edward, the Duke of Windsor (formerly Edward VIII) visited Canada to stay at his private ranch in Alberta. He entered Canada at [[North Portal]], before proceeding towards Calgary the next day. As the visit was only few years removed from the [[Edward VIII abdication crisis|1936 abdication crisis]], he was initially discouraged from visiting by the Canadian Prime Minister, [[William Lyon Mackenzie King]]. However, King would later send Edward a telegram welcoming him shortly after he entered the country.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=104}} Edward departed Canada after spending nine days there, summoned back to [[the Bahamas]] as its [[List of governors of the Bahamas|Governor]], after a hurricane struck the islands. Edward would visit Canada on two more occasions, visiting New Brunswick in 1945, and Alberta in 1950. During his time in Alberta, Edward slept at the viceregal suite of the [[Fairmont Palliser Hotel|Palliser Hotel]] in Calgary; as the state of his ranch had deteriorated in the years since his last visit. In 1945, Edward sought the appointment as the Governor General of Canada, although failed to obtain it.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=104}}\n\nBy 1945, [[Alan Lascelles]], the [[Private Secretary to the Sovereign|private secretary of George VI]], and Shuldham Redfern, [[Secretary to the Governor General of Canada]], were discussing the idea of the King making regular flights to Canada to open parliament and perform other constitutional and ceremonial duties. The notion was eventually forgotten.<ref>{{citation| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZcIf46DzpfUC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false| last=Jackson| first=Michael D.| title=The Crown and Canadian Federalism| year=2013| publisher=Dundurn Press| isbn=9781459709898| accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Late 20th century (1951\u20132000)==\n===Elizabeth II===\n[[Elizabeth II]] conducted 20 official tours of Canada from 1951 to 2000. She first toured Canada in 1951, as Princess Elizabeth, Duchess of Edinburgh.<ref name=BCArchives>{{cite web| url=http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm| last=British Columbia Archives| title=Chronology of Principal Royal Visits to British Columbia| publisher=Queen's Printer for British Columbia| accessdate=25 June 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228124243/http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm| archivedate=28 February 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> In her subsequent tours of the country, she toured it as the Queen of Canada. In addition to official tours, in the 20th century, the Queen had made nine stopovers in Canada, in order to refuel the aircraft she was travelling on.<ref name=pastt>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/services/past-royal-tours.html|title=Past Royal Tours|publisher=Government of Canada|date=24 October 2018|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n====1950s====\n[[File:Princess Elizabeth holding flowers on stage with Prince Philip and several people. Royal Visit 1951, Ontario.jpg|thumb|[[Elizabeth II|Princess Elizabeth]] along with [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] during their 1951 royal tour.]]\n[[Elizabeth II|Princess Elizabeth, Duchess of Edinburgh]], and her husband, the [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]], made their first appearance in Newfoundland, Prince Edward Island, Nova Scotia, Quebec, Ontario, Saskatchewan, British Columbia, and Alberta in 1951, on behalf of her ailing father.<ref name=BCArchives/> The [[National Film Board of Canada]] produced a documentary film ''[[Royal Journey]]'', chronicling the 1951 royal tour.\n\nThe couple toured New Brunswick; after the Princess and Duke arrived at Fredericton's Union Station on 6 November, they were there greeted by both Lieutenant Governor [[David Laurence MacLaren]] and hundreds of well-wishers,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=1| last=Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| title=Exhibits and Education Tools > Royal Visits to New Brunswick > The Golden Jubilee: A New Brunswick Tribute > 1951 > Welcome to New Brunswick > November 6, 1951| year=2009| publisher=Queen's Printer for New Brunswick| accessdate=9 July 2009| ref=CITEREF_Provincial_Archives_of_New_Brunswick_2009}}</ref> and moved on to tour the [[University of New Brunswick]], [[Christ Church Cathedral (Fredericton)|Christ Church Cathedral]], and the [[New Brunswick Legislative Building|Legislative Assembly Building]].<ref>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=1 Visiting Provincial Landmarks]}}</ref> It was then on to [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]], where the royal couple travelled in a motorcade watched by some 60,000 people, visited a veterans' hospital, and attended a civic dinner at the Admiral Beatty Hotel, where the silver flatware designed specifically for the 1939 visit of the King was used. After an overnight on the royal train, Princess Elizabeth and the Duke of Edinburgh made whistle-stops in [[Moncton]] and [[Sackville, New Brunswick|Sackville]] before departing the province.<ref name=\"StJ\"/> In Toronto, she took in a [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] game at [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] and greeted Ontarians at numerous official functions.\n\nAside from a brief stop-over for refuelling in [[Gander, Newfoundland and Labrador|Gander, Newfoundland]] in 1953{{mdash}} during which the Queen decided, after being roused from sleep at 3:20&nbsp;am by their singing of \"[[For He's a Jolly Good Fellow|For She's a Jolly Good Fellow]]\", to address the crowd gathered outside,<ref>{{Harvnb| Bousfield| 2002| p=87}}</ref>\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Phillip sit on thrones before a full Parliament.jpg|upright|thumb|left|Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip at the [[Opening of the Canadian parliament|opening of]] the [[23rd Canadian Parliament]], 14 October 1957.]]\nElizabeth returned to Canada in 1957, there giving her first ever live television address, appointing her husband to [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|her Canadian Privy Council]] at a meeting which she chaired, and on 14 October, opening the first session of the [[23rd Canadian Parliament|23rd parliament]].<ref name=Bousfield>{{Harvnb| Bousfield| 2002| pp=11\u201316}}</ref> About 50,000 people descended on Parliament Hill to witness the arrival of the monarch.<ref>{{Harvnb| Trepanier| 1989| p=30}}</ref> Due to the financial austerity of the times,<ref>{{Cite journal| last=Callwood| first=June| authorlink=June Callwood| title=June Callwood's Story of the Queen's Visit| journal=Maclean's| volume=70| page=16| publisher=Maclean-Hunter| location=Toronto| date=December 1957| issn =0024-9262}}</ref> the pageantry was muted in comparison to what would be seen at a similar event in the United Kingdom. [[June Callwood]] said in her coverage of the tour for ''[[Maclean's]]'': \"The Queen's role in Canada, it appeared to some observers, hinged on calculated pageantry, just enough to warm the pride of Canadians who revere tradition and stateliness above state but not so much as to antagonize those who consider royalty a blindingly off-colour bauble in an age of lean fear.\"<ref>Callwood, June; ''Maclean's Magazine'': June Callwood's Story of the Queen's Visit; Vol. 70; December 1957; p. 16</ref> In Saskatchewan, the Queen inaugurated the natural gas-fired [[Queen Elizabeth Power Station]] on the [[South Saskatchewan River]].<ref name=\"Regina\"/>\n\nTwo years later, in 1959 the Queen returned and toured every province and territory of the country; Buckingham Palace officials and the Canadian government opted to dub this a \"royal tour\", as opposed to a \"royal visit\", to dispel any notion that the Queen was a visiting foreigner.<ref>{{Citation| last=Buckner| first=Phillip| publication-date=2005| contribution=The Last Great Royal Tour: Queen Elizabeth's 1959 Tour to Canada| editor-last=Buckner| editor-first=Phillip| title=Canada and the End of Empire| page=66| publication-place=Vancouver| publisher=UBC Press| isbn=0-7748-0915-9| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=27IggObUC9kC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=&f=false| accessdate=24 October 2009| ref=CITEREF_Buckner_2005}}</ref> Controversy arose in the run-up to the visit when [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] personality [[Joyce Davidson]], while being interviewed by [[Dave Garroway]] on [[NBC]]'s ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today Show]]'', said that as an \"average Canadian\" she was \"pretty indifferent\" to the Queen's forthcoming visit. Davidson was lambasted in the Canadian press and by many indignant Canadians for her comment.<ref name=\"Buckner 2005 85\">{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| p=85}}</ref> Regardless, the Queen toured the entire country, specifically directing that events she attended should be public, rather than closed luncheons or receptions;<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| p=75}}</ref> further, popular Canadian athletic stars were invited to royal events for the first time, so that during her tour the Queen met with [[Jean B\u00e9liveau]], [[Sam Etcheverry]], [[Maurice Richard]], [[Punch Imlach]], and [[Bud Grant]].<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| pp=78\u201379}}</ref>\n\nOne of the most important events of this trip was the official opening of the [[St. Lawrence Seaway]], along with President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], where, in [[Prescott, Ontario]], the Queen made her first [[Live television|live appearance]] on Canadian television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/special/royalvisit/royal-quiz-answers.htm| title=Department of Canadian Heritage: Test your royal skills| publisher=Pch.gc.ca| date=9 January 2009| accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> During this tour, the Queen paid numerous visits to Canadian industries,<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| p=68}}</ref> and again made a visit to the United States as Canada's head of state, stopping in Chicago and Washington, D.C., with Diefenbaker as her attending minister. The Prime Minister insisted that the Queen be accompanied at all times by a [[Cabinet of Canada|Canadian Cabinet]] minister, being determined to make it clear to Americans that the Queen was visiting the United States as the Canadian monarch, and that \"it is the Canadian embassy and not the British Embassy officials who are in charge\" of the Queen's itinerary.<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| p=69}}</ref> Her speeches in Chicago, written by her Canadian ministers, stressed steadily the fact that she had come to call as Queen of Canada.<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| p=76}}</ref> In this vein, the Queen hosted the return dinner for Eisenhower at the [[Embassy of Canada in Washington|Canadian Embassy in Washington]].<ref name=\"Buckner 2005 85\"/>\n[[File:O'Keefe Centre and royal motorcade 1959 Toronto Canada.jpg|thumb|Motorcade of The Queen at the intersection of [[Yonge Street|Yonge]] and [[Front Street (Toronto)|Front Street]], Toronto, during her 1959 royal tour.]]\nThe Queen returned to New Brunswick, at the end of her pan-Canada tour. The sovereign presided over a [[Queen's Scout]] recognition ceremony in Fredericton, visited the veterans' hospital in [[Lancaster, New Brunswick|Lancaster]], and undertook a walkabout in Victoria Park, Moncton. At [[Pointe-du-Chene, New Brunswick|Pointe-du-Ch\u00eane]], the royal couple visited briefly with the families of fishermen who had died the previous month in a storm off [[Escuminac, New Brunswick|Escuminac]], making a donation to the New Brunswick Fisherman's Disaster Fund that was established in honour of the deceased.<ref>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=3 Introduction]}}</ref>\n\nUnknown to all involved, the Queen was pregnant with [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|her third child]]. Prime Minister Diefenbaker urged her to cut the tour short after her disclosure to him at [[Kingston, Ontario]], but the Queen swore him to secrecy and continued the journey, leaving the public announcement of the upcoming birth until she returned to London.<ref name=\"Buckner 2005 85\"/>\n\nOnce the news was released, criticism of the tour that had simmered during its progress unleashed in full: Diefenbaker was blamed for pushing the Queen to carry on a grueling continent-wide trip, and the brevity of stops necessary to complete such a journey, combined with the formality and inaccessibility of events, led to calls for a cease to that format of royal tour. The ''Albertan'' stated: \"The fact is that royalty has no roots in Canada. And if roots must be put down, they certainly should be of a different kind than those which are historically proper for Britain.\"<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| pp=85\u201386}}</ref> Prior to the tour, the President of the [[Saint-Jean-Baptiste Society]], with the support of the Mayor of Quebec City, requested of the tour officials that, on the evening of [[National Holiday (Quebec)|Saint-Jean-Baptiste Day]], Her Majesty light the main [[bonfire]] in celebration. Though the Queen did lay a wreath at the [[James Wolfe#Legacy|James Wolfe Monument]] on the Plains of Abraham, the [[Canadian Secretary to the Queen|Queen's Canadian Secretary]] at the time, [[Howard Graham (Canadian Army officer)|Howard Graham]], left the bonfire off the itinerary, leading to complaints.<ref>{{Cite book| last=Buckner| first=Phillip| publication-date=2005| contribution=The Last Great Royal Tour: Queen Elizabeth's 1959 Tour to Canada| editor-last=Buckner| editor-first=Phillip| title=Canada and the End of Empire| page=76| publication-place=Vancouver| publisher=UBC Press| isbn=978-0-7748-0915-3| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=27IggObUC9kC&printsec=frontcover&q=| accessdate=24 October 2009| ref=harv| year=2005}}</ref>\n\nSuccesses were also noted, especially in the Crown's assistance in entrenching the newly emerging Canadian identity; the Queen ensured that the [[Canadian Red Ensign|Red Ensign]] (then Canada's ''de facto'' national flag) was flown on the [[HMY Britannia|royal yacht]], and she stood to attention for the duration of each playing of \"[[O Canada]]\", the country's then still unofficial national anthem, sometimes even joining in the singing.<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| 87}}</ref>\n\n====1960 to 2000====\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II, Royal tour of Canada 1983-Mar-09, UBC, Vancouver BC.jpg|thumb|upright|The Queen walks with [[John Clyne]], the Chancellor of the [[University of British Columbia]] during her 1983 royal tour of Canada.]]\nQueen Elizabeth II also celebrated the centennial of the [[Canadian Confederation|Confederation Conferences]] in Charlottetown on 6 October 1964.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |year=2010 |title=Confederation Centre of the Arts  |encyclopedia= The Canadian Encyclopedia |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/confederation-centre-of-the-arts-emc |language=en}}</ref> On 10 October, as she was touring the streets of [[Quebec City]], a turbulent riot occurred and opposed anti-monarchist [[Quebec nationalism|Quebec nationalists]] with the police. Since then, the event has been known as [[:fr:Samedi de la matraque|''Samedi de la matraque'']] (\"[[Baton (law enforcement)|Truncheon]] Saturday\").<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/quebec-and-the-royals-a-rocky-history-risks-another-bump/article585297/ |title=Quebec and the royals: A rocky history risks another bump |last=Blatchford |first=Andy |date=2 July 2011 |website=The Globe and Mail |access-date=2018-10-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, the Queen was in British Columbia to celebrate the centennial of the province's entry into Confederation.<ref name=BCArchives /> She toured Alberta and Saskatchewan in July 1973, to celebrate the centennial of the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], opening the new RCMP museum building in Regina,<ref name=Regina /> and in 1978, to open the [[1978 Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]] in Edmonton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://premier.alberta.ca/royalvisit/index_past_visits.cfm |last=Government of Alberta |title=Premier Ralph Klein > Royal Visit > Past Visits |publisher=Alberta Queen's Printer |accessdate=28 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422032851/http://premier.alberta.ca/royalvisit/index_past_visits.cfm |archivedate=22 April 2009 }}</ref> In Saskatchewan, she dedicated Queen Elizabeth Court, in front of Regina's city hall.<ref name=Regina />\n\n28 June \u2013 6 July 1976: Prince Charles, Prince Andrew and Prince Edward joined the Queen and Prince Philip for the 1976 Olympic Games in Montreal. Princess Anne was a member of the British equestrian team competing in the Olympics in Montreal. The royal family also stopped by Nova Scotia and New Brunswick during the visit. The Queen arrived at Fredericton, New Brunswick, on 15 July, after which she travelled to Woolastook Provincial Park to visit the [[Scouts Canada|Boy Scout]] Jamboree campsite, [[picnic]]ked with 3,500 schoolchildren, toured the [[Kings Landing Historical Settlement]],<ref>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=4 Woolastook and King's Landing]}}</ref> and attended a provincial dinner with fireworks following.<ref>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=4 First Stop \u2013 Fredericton]}}</ref> The Queen's second day in New Brunswick brought her to the [[Miramichi Valley|Miramichi]] area, where she attended a provincial lunch, visited [[Chatham, New Brunswick|Chatham]] and [[Newcastle, New Brunswick|Newcastle]], and toured the Burchill Laminating Plant in [[Nelson-Miramichi, New Brunswick|Nelson-Miramichi]].<ref name=StJ>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Image=1951-4-06&Panel=6&Years=1951 Saint John]}}</ref>\n\nThe Queen also journeyed to New Brunswick to celebrate the province's bicentennial in 1984, touching down, along with Prince Philip, at Moncton airport on 24 September, from where the royal party travelled to [[Shediac, New Brunswick|Shediac]], Sackville, [[Riverview, New Brunswick|Riverview]], and Fredericton over the course of three days. While at the Legislative Building, the Queen issued a [[Royal warrant (document)|Royal Warrant]] augmenting the [[Coat of arms of New Brunswick|province's coat of arms]] with its present crest, supporters, compartment, motto.<ref name=NBarch>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=5 Fredericton]}}</ref> She also, when in Fredericton, unveiled a plaque in Wilmot Park that honoured Edward Wilmot and recounted the dedication of the park by the Queen's great-grandfather.<ref name=NBarch />\n\nThe Queen opened the [[University of Northern British Columbia]] in 1994.<ref>[http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm British Columbia Archives: Chronology of Principal Royal Visits to British Columbia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228124243/http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm |date=28 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Philip, Duke of Edinburgh===\n[[File:QueenPhillip21976.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip at [[Scouts Canada]]'s Fourth Pentathlon Jamboree in 1976.]]\nPhilip, Duke of Edinburgh, [[Prince consort|consort]] to Queen Elizabeth II, participated in 28 official tours of Canada from 1951 to 2000, with his first in 1951, accompanying his spouse, Princess Elizabeth.<ref name=BCArchives/> During the same period of time, he has also taken 13 private working tours of the country, participating in events such as the [[Commonwealth Study Conference]], or the presentation of the [[Duke of Edinburgh Awards]]. Cumulatively, he has made more than 70 visits to Canada, including 19 royal tours with Queen Elizabeth II.<ref name=PPDE />\n\nThe Duke of Edinburgh visited the realm on two occasions to open two [[multi-sport event]], the [[1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]], and the [[1967 Pan American Games]]. The trip was one of many visits to Canada the Duke has made without the Queen. Other visits without the Queen occurred in 1960, 1962, 1978, 1979, 1980, and 1998, as he was chairing the [[Commonwealth Study Conference]], hosted in Canada during those years. He has also made 11 trips to Canada in relation to [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]].<ref name=PPDE>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-philip-s-love-affair-with-canada-1.1305785|title=Prince Philip's love affair with Canada|last=Davison|first=Janet|date=26 April 2013|accessdate=8 January 2018|work=CBCNews.ca|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> The Duke has also made several visits relating to his [[The Canadian Crown and the Canadian Armed Forces|role with the Armed Forces]]. He was appointed the [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of the [[Royal Canadian Regiment]] on 8 December 1953, he presented the 3rd Battalion's first colours on [[Parliament Hill]] in 1973.\n\n===Charles, Prince of Wales===\n[[Charles, Prince of Wales]] made 12 official tours of Canada from 1970 to 2000.<ref name=pastt/> His first official tour of Canada was in July 1970, touring Ottawa,<ref name=pastt/> prior to joining The Queen, the Duke of Edinburgh, and [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]]'s official tour of Manitoba, to celebrate of the centennial of Manitoba's entry into Confederation.<ref name=Mancent>{{cite web|url=http://lg.gov.mb.ca/history/house/second/bed.html| last=Office of the Lieutenant Governor of Manitoba| title=History > Government House > The Royal Bedroom| publisher=Queen's Printer for Manitoba| accessdate=2 July 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213160834/http://lg.gov.mb.ca/history/house/second/bed.html| archivedate=13 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe Prince and his first wife, the [[Diana, Princess of Wales|Princess of Wales]] attended the bicentennial in 1983 of the arrival of the first Empire Loyalists in Nova Scotia,<ref name=CBCVisits /> and also visited Newfoundland to mark the 400th anniversary of the island becoming a British colony.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://archives.cbc.ca/on_this_day/06/24/| title=On This Day > June 24, 1983 > Charles and Diana charm Newfoundlanders| date=23 June 1983| publisher=CBC| accessdate=12 July 2009}}</ref> In 1986, the Prince and Princess of Wales toured British Columbia, visiting Vancouver to open [[Expo 86]] (on 2 May 1986), as well as Victoria, Prince George, Kamloops and Nanaimo.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm| title=Chronology of Principal Royal Visits to British Columbia| accessdate=10 August 2014| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228124243/http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm| archivedate=28 February 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, the Prince and Princess of Wales toured Ontario; in Toronto, the princess was joined on board the [[HMY Britannia|Royal Yacht ''Britannia'']] by her two sons, Princes [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|William]] and [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex|Harry]], and caused some controversy{{cn|date=November 2019}} when she broke from established protocol by enthusiastically hugging the two boys after they ran up the gangplank to meet her. After performing official duties in the city, including a formal dinner at the Royal York hotel, the royal family then went on to visit [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]], [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]], Ottawa, and Niagara Falls, where the princes, as their great-great-great-grandfather had done, rode on ''Maid of the Mist''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.niagaraparks.com/nfgg/famous_visitors.php| last=Niagara Parks| title=Niagara Falls & Great Gorge > More Niagara Falls and Great Gorge > Falls Facts > Famous Visitors| publisher=Queen's Printer for Ontario| accessdate=4 July 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120904074848/http://www.niagaraparks.com/nfgg/famous_visitors.php| archivedate=4 September 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Other royal family members===\n[[File:Royal motorcade (8075978363).jpg|thumb|Four members of the Royal Family\u2014The Queen; Prince Philip; [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|Prince Andrew]]; and [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Prince Edward]]\u2014at the opening of the [[1978 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]].]]\nQueen Elizabeth The Queen Mother, [[queen-consort]] to King George VI, and mother of Elizabeth II, has conducted nine official tours of Canada from 1951 to 2000.<ref name=pastt/> In 1967, she returned to Nova Scotia and Prince Edward Island to celebrate [[Canadian Centennial|Canada's centennial]] in 1967.<ref name=CBCVisits /> On a visit in 1985 to Toronto and Saskatchewan she noted, \"It is now some 46 years since I first came to this country with the King, in those anxious days shortly before the outbreak of the Second World War. I shall always look back upon that visit with feelings of affection and happiness. I think I lost my heart to Canada and Canadians, and my feelings have not changed with the passage of time.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/interactive/royalvisits/52.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106091148/http://www.cbc.ca/news/interactive/royalvisits/52.html |archivedate=6 November 2012 |title=Royal Visits to Canada |work=CBC News |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> In addition to her nine official tours, she conducted one private working tour in 1965, touring Toronto to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the [[The Toronto Scottish Regiment (Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother's Own)|Toronto Scottish Regiment]], a regiment where she holds the position of colonel-in-chief.<ref name=pastt/>\n\nElizabeth II's sister, [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon]] conducted seven official tours of Canada, as well as three private working tours of Canada from 1951 to 2000<ref name=pastt/> Two of her private working tours were conducted in relation to her role as patron of the [[Princess Margaret Cancer Centre|Princess Margaret Hospital]].<ref name=pastt/> Official tours include tours of Nova Scotia and British Columbia in 1958.<ref name=CBCVisits>{{Citation| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/interactive/royalvisits/51.html| title=Royal Visits to Canada| publisher=CBC| accessdate=10 July 2009}}</ref> In BC, the princess opened the new [[Pontoon bridge|floating bridge]] in Kelowna, with two plaques marking the ceremony.<ref name=Legacy /> She also presided over the celebrations of the 75th anniversary of Saskatchewan's entry into Confederation.<ref name=Regina />\n\n[[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy]] conducted three official tours of Canada, as well as four private working tours of the country from 1951 to 2000.<ref name=pastt/>  She toured Canada for its centenary in 1967, and also arrived in Halifax in 1973 to mark the bicentennial of the arrival of {{ship||Hector|ship|2}}, the first ship to land at Nova Scotia with Scottish colonists.<ref name=CBCVisits />\n\n[[Anne, Princess Royal]] conducted over six official tours of Canada, as well as seven private working tours from 1951 to 2000.<ref name=pastt/> Princess Anne presided over the 1970 celebrations of the centennial of Manitoba's entry into Confederation alongside her brother, the Prince of Wales.<ref name=Mancent />\n\n[[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]] conducted five official tours of Canada, as well as 10 private working tours from 1951 to 2000.<ref name=pastt/> His first official tour was conducted in 1976, whereas his first private working tour was conducted in the following year,<ref name=pastt/> after attending a semester of [[secondary school]] at [[Lakefield College School]], in [[Selwyn, Ontario|Selwyn]], Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thedukeofyork.org/about-the-duke/early-life-and-education/|title=Early Life & Education|publisher=The Duke of York|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> He undertook his first official tour of Nova Scotia in 1985, during which, amongst other activities, he visited Halifax and skippered [[Bluenose#Bluenose II|''Bluenose II'']].<ref name=CBCVisits />\n\nOther members of the royal family that conducted either official, or private working tours of Canada in the second half of the 20th century include [[Princess Marina of Greece and Denmark|Princess Marina, Duchess of Kent]], [[Princess Alice, Duchess of Gloucester]], [[Mary, Princess Royal and Countess of Harewood|Mary, Princess Royal]], [[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent]], [[Katharine, Duchess of Kent]], the [[Prince Michael of Kent|Prince]] and [[Princess Michael of Kent]], and the [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Earl]] and [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|Countess of Wessex]].<ref name=pastt/>\n\n==21st century==\n{{main|List of royal tours of Canada (21st century)}}\n===Elizabeth II===\n[[File:Royal Visit Toronto 2010 6.JPG|thumb|The Queen in [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]], Toronto, during her 2010 royal tour.]]\nElizabeth II has conducted three official tours of Canada in the 21st century. In 2002, Elizabeth II toured the Canadian provinces of British Columbia, New Brunswick, Manitoba, Ontario, Quebec, and the territory of Nunavut, for her [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Golden Jubilee]].\n\nIn 2005, the Queen was in Alberta again to mark the province's 100th anniversary of entry into Confederation, where she attended, along with an audience of 25,000, a kick-off concert at [[Commonwealth Stadium (Edmonton)|Commonwealth Stadium]], re-designated the Provincial Museum of Alberta as the [[Royal Alberta Museum]], and addressed the Legislative Assembly, becoming the first reigning monarch to do so.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.albertacentennial.ca/events/kickoff.html| last=Government of Alberta| title=Alberta Centennial Home > Official Events > Celebrate Alberta Kick-Off Party| publisher=Alberta Queen's Printer| accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref> The [[Education in Alberta|Alberta Ministry of Learning]] encouraged teachers to focus education on the monarchy and to organize field trips for their students to see the Queen and her consort, or to watch the events on television.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.education.gov.ab.ca/centennial/RoyalVisit/bulletin.asp| last=Government of Alberta| title=Education Home > Centennial Projects > Alberta students encouraged to join the festivities the Royal Visit 2005| publisher=Alberta Queen's Printer| accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref> In Saskatchewan, the Queen presided over the main events for the centennial of Saskatchewan's creation, as well as touring the [[Canadian Light Source Synchrotron]] and the University of Saskatchewan,<ref>{{cite news| title=Royal couple touches down in Saskatchewan| publisher=CTV| date=18 May 2005| url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1116361103300_111770303/?hub=TopStories| accessdate=30 June 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051001053156/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1116361103300_111770303/?hub=TopStories| archivedate=1 October 2005| df=dmy-all}}</ref> where, in the Diefenbaker Canada Centre, is stored correspondence between former Prime Minister [[John Diefenbaker]] and the Queen.\n\nIn 2010, Elizabeth II visited Ontario and Manitoba as part of the 2010 royal tour of Canada. Arriving in Ottawa 30 June 2010, she toured the Canadian Museum of Nature and met with Prime Minister Stephen Harper. The following day, the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh joined the festivities for Canada Day on Parliament Hill. The Royal Tour of Canada ended as the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh departed for New York on 6 July 2010, following visits to Toronto and Waterloo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/the-royal-visit-of-2010-1.892553|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|title=The Royal Visit of 2010|date=25 June 2010|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Charles, Prince of Wales===\n[[File:Royal Tour 2014 (14040125577).jpg|thumb|left|[[Charles, Prince of Wales]] visiting [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]] during his 2014 royal tour of Canada.]]\nSince 2001, the Prince of Wales has conducted five official tours in Canada, in April 2001, November 2009, May 2012, May 2014, and June\u2013July 2017. He was accompanied by his spouse, [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] on the latter four tours.<ref name=pastt/>\n\nIn 2001 he toured through Ottawa, where his interactions with the crowds kept Prime Minister [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] waiting for twenty minutes. He also toured Regina, Moose Jaw, [[Assiniboia, Saskatchewan|Assiniboia]], Saskatoon, [[Whitehorse, Yukon|Whitehorse]], and [[Mayo, Yukon|Mayo]]. In Saskatchewan, he turned the sod for the Prince of Wales Cultural and Recreation Centre in Assiniboia and dedicated the Anniversary Arch outside Regina's YMCA.<ref name=Regina />\n\nOn 14 December, it was announced that Camilla and Charles would visit several provinces in Canada, including New Brunswick, Ontario, and Saskatchewan. This trip is in honour of the Queen's Diamond Jubilee in February 2012. In 2017, the Prince of Wales and Duchess of Cornwall were in Canada from 29 June to 1 July for [[Canada Day]] celebration and for the country's sesquicentennial celebrations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2017/04/18/prince-charles-camilla-to-visit-for-canada-150-celebration.html|title=Prince Charles, Camilla to visit for Canada 150 celebration|date=18 April 2017|accessdate=20 May 2017|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\n===William, Duke of Cambridge===\n[[File:Canada Ottawa William Kate 2011 (2).jpg|thumb|[[William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] and the [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Duchess of Cambridge]] at an inspection for the [[Governor General's Foot Guards]] during their [[2011 royal tour of Canada]].]]\n[[William, Duke of Cambridge]] has conducted two official tours in Canada in the 21st century. The [[2011 royal tour of Canada]] was the first time Prince William, and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]], visited Canada as the Duke and Duchess of Cambridge. The tour saw the newlywed couple tour Ottawa, Montreal, Quebec City, Charlottetown, [[Summerside, Prince Edward Island|Summerside]], [[Yellowknife]], Calgary, as well as the fire-ravaged community of [[Slave Lake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/services/past-royal-tours/2011-royal-tour-duke-duchess-cambridge.html|title=2011 Royal Tour of Canada by Their Royal Highnesses The Duke and Duchess of Cambridge|publisher=Government of Canada|date=4 August 2017|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref> It was the first such tour undertaken by the Duke and Duchess since their marriage two months prior.<ref>{{cite press release |title=HRH Prince William of Wales and Miss Catherine Middleton to undertake a Royal tour of Canada |url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/media/press-releases/hrh-prince-william-of-wales-and-miss-catherine-middleton-undertake-royal-tour |publisher=Clarence House |via=www.princeofwales.gov.uk |date=16 February 2011 |access-date=30 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=cbc-tour-it-an>{{cite news| last=Yelaja| first=Prithi| title=William and Kate's royal tour itinerary released| publisher=CBC| date=21 June 2011| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/williamandkate/story/2011/06/21/royal-tour.html| accessdate=2 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the Duke and Duchess of Cambridge, along with their children, [[Prince George of Cambridge]], and [[Princess Charlotte of Cambridge]], conducted an official tour of British Columbia and [[Yukon]], visiting Victoria, Vancouver, [[Bella Bella, British Columbia|Bella Bella]], [[Kelowna]], Whitehorse, [[Carcross]], and [[Haida Gwaii]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/services/past-royal-tours/2016-royal-tour-duke-duchess-cambridge.html|title=The 2016 Royal Tour of The Duke and Duchess of Cambridge|publisher=Government of Canada|date=24 October 2018|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Anne, Princess Royal===\nAnne, Princess Royal has conducted seven private working tours, and one official working tour of Canada since 2001. She conducted private working tours in August\u2013September 2003, June 2004, June 2007, February 2010, April 2010, October 2013, and February 2015; and one official tour in November 2014.<ref name=pastt/>\n\nThe Princess Royal's private tours to Canada are typically conducted in association with her honorary role as the colonel in chief of six units in the Canadian Forces. In April 2010, she visited St. John's to celebrate the anniversary of the [[Royal Newfoundland Regiment]], as well as Regina, to celebrate its centennial.<ref name=Regina /> The Princess Royal also a visit to Barrie on 22 October 2013 to commemorate the opening of park with military significance and to visit the [[Grey and Simcoe Foresters]], for which she their current colonel-in-chief.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.simcoe.com/news-story/4168372-princess-anne-s-royal-visit-commemorated-in-new-barrie-park/ |title=Princess Anne's royal visit commemorated in new Barrie park |work=simcoe.com |date=22 October 2013 |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Princess Royal and her husband [[Vice admiral (Royal Navy)|Vice-Admiral]] [[Tim Laurence]] arrived in Canada on 10 November 2014 in Ottawa for a two-day official tour, with focus on [[Remembrance Day]] ceremonies in Ottawa, such as the re-dedication of the [[National War Memorial (Canada)|National War Memorial]].<ref name=pastt/>\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/princess-anne-s-ottawa-tour-will-honour-everyday-heroes-1.2826736 |title=Princess Anne's Ottawa tour will honour 'everyday heroes' |work=CBC News |date=7 November 2014 |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Edward, Earl of Wessex===\n[[File:Wessex-MLC.jpg|thumb|[[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]] with members of the [[Monarchist League of Canada]] in Toronto, 2005.]]\nSince 2001, [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]] has conducted 17 private working tours in Canada. His first visit to Canada in the 21st century occurred in October 2001, with his latest tour occurring in October\u2013November 2015. Most of these visits were conducted for ceremonies relating to the [[Duke of Edinburgh Award]].<ref name=pastt/>\n\nIn 2003, Prince Edward opened two parks in Saskatchewan, the Prince Edward Park in Melfort and the Queen's Golden Jubilee Rose Garden in Moose Jaw.<ref name=Regina /> In 2005, the Earl and Countess of Wessex toured Ontario; the Earl visited Peterborough, [[Prince Edward County, Ontario|Prince Edward County]], and Toronto, while his spouse, [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex]], went to [[Welland, Ontario|Welland]] to be installed as Colonel-in-Chief of [[the Lincoln and Welland Regiment]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.heritagefdn.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/nts_1_8218_1.html| publisher=Ontario Heritage Trust| title=HRH The Earl of Wessex unveils provincial plaque celebrating the Toronto-Dominion Centre| date=14 August 2006| accessdate=15 September 2007| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927091304/http://www.heritagefdn.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/nts_1_8218_1.html| archivedate=27 September 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Countess has accompanied her husband, Prince Edward on a number of tours to Canada. Their tour of Canada in 2002 marked the Countess' first tour outside of the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite press release| title=Their Royal Highnesses The Earl and Countess of Wessex to Visit the Province| publisher=Queen's Printer for Prince Edward Island| date=4 May 2000| url=http://www.gov.pe.ca/news/getrelease.php3?number=1591| accessdate=11 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Burke |first=Scott |author2=Aimers, John |title=Wessexs' Tour a Triumph |journal=Canadian Monarchist News |publisher=Monarchist League of Canada |location=Toronto |year=2001 |url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2001/wessex.htm |accessdate=11 July 2009 |ref=harv |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708015252/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2001/wessex.htm |archivedate=8 July 2009 }}</ref> In 2009, Countess of Wessex opened the Air Force Museum of Alberta in Calgary, spending some hours visiting its displays.<ref>{{Cite book| last=Stepaniuk| first=Violette| title=New museum in Calgary tells story of Canada\u2019s Air Force| publisher=Skytech Dynamics Corporation| date=2 July 2009| url=http://www.aviation.ca/content/view/7566/117/| accessdate=3 July 2009}}</ref> The Countess of Wessex has also conducted private working tours of her own, as was the case in November 2015.<ref name=pastt/>\n\n===Other royal family members===\n[[File:Prince Philip as Colonel-in-Chief of the Royal Canadian Regiment.jpg|thumb|Prince Philip with members of [[The Royal Canadian Regiment]] in 2013.]]\nIn the 21st century, Prince Philip has conducted three official tours alongside Queen Elizabeth, in October 2002, May 2005, and June 2010. In addition to official tours, he has conducted three private working tours, in October 2001, April 2004, and April 2013.<ref name=pastt/> In 2001, he visited Toronto in order to present the Duke of Edinburgh Award to recipients, and participate in activities relating to the [[World Wildlife Foundation]].<ref name=pastt/> In April 2013, [[David Johnston]], the Governor General of Canada, presented Philip with the [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|Order of Military Merit]], and inducted him as a Companion of the [[Order of Canada]].<ref name=pastt/> On the 27 April 2013, Prince Philip, the Colonel-in-Chief of the Royal Canadian Regiment, visited Toronto in order to present the 3rd battalion its second colours.<ref name=PPDE/>\n\nThe Prince Andrew, Duke of York has conducted 17 of private working tours in Canada since 2001. His first tour in the 21st century was in January 2001, whereas his latest tour in Canada occurred in May 2019.<ref name=pastt/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thechronicleherald.ca/opinion/columnists/john-demont-prince-andrew-honours-halifaxs-princess-louise-fusiliers-315122/|title=Prince Andrew honours Halifax\u2019s Princess Louise Fusiliers|last=DeMont|first=Josh|publisher=SaltWire Network|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=24 May 2019|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> In 2003, he came twice, at one point going into the field in full [[CADPAT|combat uniform]] to observe tactical exercises and address the troops of the [[Queen's York Rangers (1st American Regiment) (RCAC)|Queen's York Rangers]], of which he is colonel-in-chief.<ref>{{cite journal| last=Roberts| first=Stephen| title=HRH Duke of York visits the Monarchist League| journal=Canadian Monarchist News| volume=7| issue=4| page=4| publisher=Monarchist League of Canada| location=Toronto| year=2003| url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmnews/CMN_summer_2003_Update-2.pdf| accessdate=4 July 2009| ref=harv|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071006170218/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmnews/CMN_summer_2003_Update-2.pdf| archivedate = 6 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nPrincess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy, has conducted two private working tours of Canada, in April 2010, and October 2012. During her 2010, she visited Toronto and Victoria to attend the 150th anniversary ceremonies for the establishment of [[The Queen's Own Rifles of Canada]], of which she is the colonel-in-chief.<ref name=pastt/> In 2012, she returned to Victoria to attend the 100th anniversary for [[The Canadian Scottish Regiment (Princess Mary's)]].<ref name=pastt/>\n\nSince 2001, Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex has visited Canada on two private working tours, on the 26 June 2007, and from September\u2013October 2008. Both visits were conducted for military exercises at [[CFB Suffield]] in Alberta.<ref name=pastt/> In addition to private working tours, Harry has made informal visits to the country, such as the opening for the [[2017 Invictus Games]] in Toronto. It was during these games that Prince Harry, and his future spouse, [[Meghan, Duchess of Sussex]] made their first public appearance together.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/invictus-games/2017/09/25/prince-harry-meghan-markle-make-first-public-appearance-together-at-invictus-games.html|title=Prince Harry, Meghan Markle make first public appearance together at Invictus Games|publisher=Torstar Corporation|work=The Toronto Star|last=Loriggio|first=Paolo|accessdate=23 January 2019|date=25 September 2017}}</ref> Prior to their first public appearance, reports had surfaced in 2016 that Harry visited Meghan at her home in Toronto; who was residing in the city from 2011 to 2017 in order to film the television series ''[[Suits (U.S. TV series)|Suits]]''.<ref name=Megh>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2017/11/27/how-meghan-markle-and-prince-harry-fell-in-love-in-toronto-the-timeline-of-a-royal-romance.html|title=How Meghan Markle and Prince Harry fell in love in Toronto: The timeline of a royal romance|publisher=Torstar Corporation|work=The Toronto Star|accessdate=23 January 2019|date=27 November 2017|last=Jones|first=Alexandra}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of royal tours of Canada (18th\u201320th centuries)]]\n*[[List of royal tours of Canada (21st century)]]\n*[[List of royal visits to Hamilton, Ontario]]\n*[[List of royal visits to London, Ontario]]\n*[[Royal visits to Saskatchewan]]\n*[[Royal and viceroyal transport in Canada]]\n**[[Royal Canadian Air Force VIP aircraft]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book| last=Bousfield| first=Arthur|author2=Toffoli, Garry|  title=Royal Spring: The Royal Tour of 1939 and the Queen Mother in Canada| publisher=Dundurn Press| year=1989| location=Toronto| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Go5p_CN8UQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=&f=false| isbn=1-55002-065-X}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bousfuield|first1=Arthur|first2=Garry|last2=Toffoli|title=Royal Tours 1786-2010: Home to Canada|publisher=Dundurn Press|isbn=1-4597-1165-3 |year=2010|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last=Cartwright| first=Thelma|author2=Clay, John| author3=Hall, Edna|  title=The Silver Jubilee: Royal Visit to Canada| publisher=Deneau & Greenburg| year=1977| location=Ottawa| isbn=0-88879-002-3}}\n*{{Cite book| last=Fleming| first=Rae| title=The Royal Tour of Canada: The 1939 Visit of King George VI and Queen Elizabeth| publisher=Lynx Images| year=2002| isbn=1-894073-37-1| url=https://archive.org/details/royaltourofcanad0000flem}}\n*{{Cite book| last=Lanctot| first=Gustave| authorlink=Gustave Lanctot| title=The Royal Tour of King George VI and Queen Elizabeth in Canada and the United States of America 1939| publisher=E.P. Taylor Foundation| year=1964| location=Toronto}}\n*{{Cite book| last=MacDonnell| first=Tom| title=Daylight Upon Magic: The Royal Tour of Canada, 1939| publisher=Macmillan| year=1989| location=Toronto| isbn=0-7715-9229-9}}\n*{{Cite book| last=Radforth| first=Ian| title=Royal Spectacle: The 1860 Visit of the Prince of Wales to Canada and the United States| publisher=University of Toronto Press| year=2005| location=Toronto| isbn=0-8020-8699-3}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Royal visits by the Monarchy of the Commonwealth to Canada|Royal tours of Canada}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.canada.ca/en/services/culture/canadian-identity-society/monarchy-crown/royal-tours.html}} - Government of Canada\n* [https://www.nfb.ca/subjects/politics-and-government-canada/royal-family/ Royal Family] - National Film Board of Canada\n* [https://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/society/the-monarchy/ The Monarchy] - CBC Digital Archive\n\n{{Canadian monarchy}}\n{{Elizabeth II}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Royal Tours Of Canada}}\n[[Category:Elizabeth II]]\n[[Category:Monarchy in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal tours of Canada| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tours of Canada by the Canadian Royal Family}}\n[[File:His Majesty King George VI and Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth coming up the walkway with a view of the harbour of Victoria in the background.jpg|thumb|A crowd in [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], [[British Columbia]] watch [[King George VI]] and his [[List of royal consorts of Canada|royal consort]], [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]] coming up the walkway during their [[1939 royal tour of Canada]].]]\n'''Royal tours of Canada by the Canadian Royal Family''' have been [[List of royal tours of Canada (18th-20th centuries)|taking place since 1786]],<ref name=DCH>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/services/past-royal-tours/royal-visits-1786-1951.html|title=Royal Visits from 1786 to 1951|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=2 February 2019|date=24 October 2018}}</ref> and [[List of royal tours of Canada (21st century)|continue into the 21st century]], either as an official tour, a working tour, a vacation, or a period of military service by a member of the royal family. Originally, official tours were events predominantly for Canadians to see and possibly meet members of their [[Monarchy of Canada#Canada's royal family and house|Canadian Royal Family]], with the associated patriotic pomp and spectacle. However, nearing the end of the 20th century, such occasions took on the added dimension of a theme; for instance, the 2005 tour of [[Saskatchewan]] and [[Alberta]] by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], was deemed to be a vehicle for the Queen and Canadians to honour \"The Spirit of Nation Builders.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.ab.ca/premier/royalvisit/index_the_visit.cfm |last=Office of the Premier of Alberta |authorlink=Premier of Alberta |title=Premier Ralph Klein > Royal Visit > The Visit > Theme |publisher=Queen's Printer for Alberta |accessdate=3 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007233437/http://www.gov.ab.ca/premier/royalvisit/index_the_visit.cfm |archivedate=7 October 2008 }}</ref> The couple's tour in 2010 was themed \"Honouring the Canadian Record of Service{{mdash}} Past, Present and Future.\"<ref>{{Citation| last=Kennedy| first=Mark| title=A constitutional crisis likely looms for Canada's next governor general| newspaper=Vancouver Sun| date=28 September 2010| url=https://vancouversun.com/news/constitutional+crisis+likely+looms+Canada+next+governor+general/3592493/story.html| accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref> Official royal tours have always been vested with civic importance, providing a regionalised country with a common thread of loyalty.<ref>{{Cite book| last=Coates| first=Colin MacMillan| title=Majesty in Canada: essays on the role of royalty| publisher=Dundurn Press Ltd.| year=2006| location=Toronto| page=11| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FhFyvhpPx8MC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false| isbn=978-1-55002-586-6}}</ref>\n\nThe first member of the royal family to visit [[Canada]] was the future [[William IV of the United Kingdom|King William IV]], who arrived on the country's east coast in 1786 while an officer in the [[Royal Navy]]. His niece, [[Queen Victoria]], never came to Canada, but during her reign her son, the future [[Edward VII|King Edward VII]], made the first modern Canadian royal tour: partaking in official engagements, meeting politicians and the public, and reviewing troops.<ref>{{Cite book| last=Pigott| first=Peter| title=Royal Transport: An Inside Look at the History of Royal Travel| publisher=Dundurn Press| year=2005| location=Toronto| page=14| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8WSLImiMDhAC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=&f=false| isbn=978-1-55002-572-9| ref=CITEREF_Pigott_2005}}</ref> There had been many invitations since 1858 for the reigning monarch to tour Canada,<ref>{{Cite book| last=Bousfield| first=Arthur|author2=Toffoli, Gary|  title=Royal Spring: The Royal Tour of 1939 and the Queen Mother in Canada| publisher=Dundurn Press| year=1989| location=Toronto| page=5| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Go5p_CN8UQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_navlinks_s#v=onepage&q=&f=false| isbn=1-55002-065-X}}</ref> but in 1939 [[King George VI]] was the first to do so. During that trip, the King's wife, [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]], initiated the tradition of the \"royal walkabout\",<ref>{{Harvnb| Pigott| 2005| p=21}}</ref> though her brother-in-law, the former [[Edward VIII|King Edward VIII]], had often met ordinary Canadian people in 1919; as he said: \"Getting off the train to stretch my legs, I would start up conversations with farmers, section hands, miners, small town editors or newly arrived immigrants from Europe.\"<ref>{{Citation| last=Edward, Prince of Wales| author-link=Edward VIII| year=1919| publication-date=2005| contribution=Diary| editor-last=Pigott| editor-first=Peter| title=Royal Transport: An Inside Look at the History of Royal Travel| page=33| publication-place=Toronto| publisher=Dundurn Press| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8WSLImiMDhAC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=&f=false| isbn=978-1-55002-572-9| accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nRoyal tours can take more than a year to organize. The planning is coordinated by the [[Canadian Secretary to the Queen]].<ref name=Globe>{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/behind-the-royal-tour-a-businesslike-usher-of-the-black-rod/article615591/| last=Paperny| first=Anna Mehler| title=Behind the royal tour, a businesslike Usher of the Black Rod| date=26 June 2011| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> The regions to be visited are decided by a rotational formula.<ref name=Globe/> Modern tours have run with a theme; for instance the visit of Elizabeth II and the Duke of Edinburgh in 2010 was intended to highlight \"the Canadian record of service\u2014past, present and future\";<ref>{{Cite journal| last=Treble| first=Patricia| title=The Queen's man on the ground| journal=Maclean's| issue=July 2010| publisher=Rogers Communications| location=Toronto| date=8 July 2010| url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2010/07/08/the-queens-man-on-the-ground/| issn=0024-9262| accessdate=10 July 2010}}</ref> themes are decided upon by the Queen's secretary together with the [[Minister of Canadian Heritage]] and the [[Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)|Office of the Prime Minister]].<ref name=Globe/>\n{{toc limit|3}}\n\n==18th century==\n===1780s===\n[[File:HMS Pegasus.jpg|thumb|{{HMS|Pegasus|1779|6}} in the harbour of [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's]], [[Newfoundland Colony|Newfoundland]]. Commanding ''Pegasus'' from 1786 to 1787, [[William IV of the United Kingdom|Prince William Henry]] was the first member of the Royal Family to visit Canada.]]\nAs an officer in the [[Royal Navy]], Prince William Henry (later [[William IV of the United Kingdom|William IV]]) was the first member of the Royal Family to visit [[Newfoundland Colony]], the colony of [[Nova Scotia]], and the [[Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)|Province of Quebec]] (later [[Lower Canada|Lower]] and [[Upper Canada]]). William's first visit to the colonies was during his command of {{HMS|Pegasus|1779|6}}, a command he was given on 10 April 1786.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=24}} Arriving in Newfoundland, William found himself involved in the civil and naval affairs of Newfoundland, with no permanent civil authorities, and the newly arrived Prince being the senior naval officer in the colony.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=26}} During his time in Newfoundland, he presided over a court, and commissioned the construction of St. Luke's Anglican Church in [[New-Wes-Valley]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=26}} On 21 August 1786, he celebrated his 21st birthday on his ship in the waters off Newfoundland.<ref name=heritage />\n\nHe eventually proceeded to the main base of the Royal Navy's [[North America and West Indies Station|North American Station]], based at the [[Royal Naval Dockyard, Halifax|Royal Naval Dockyards]] in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=26}} Although he received a royal reception upon his arrival to Halifax, it was later made clear he would receive no further special treatment, not already accorded to an officer of his rank in the Royal Navy.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=26}} William visited the Quebec in 1787, travelling as far inland as [[Cornwall, Ontario|Cornwall]]. While there, he encouraged the [[United Empire Loyalist]]s to settle the region that later made up Upper Canada.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=27}} Near Cornwall, he also received a reception from members of the [[First Nations]] communities.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Secret of the Crown: Canada's Affair with Royalty|publisher=House of Anansi|chapter=2|isbn=1-7708-9055-6|year=2012|last=Fraser|first=John}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his visit to Quebec, William was stationed in the West Indies. Depressed over the departure of [[Horatio Nelson]], who he befriended during his time in the Caribbean, he took HMS ''Pegasus'' to Halifax, without permission from the Royal Navy.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=27}} William was ordered to winter in Quebec, although he would take his ship back to Britain, arriving in [[Portsmouth]] in December 1787.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=28}}\n\nWilliam received his second posting to [[British North America]] in July 1788, as the commander of {{HMS|Andromeda|1784|6}}. He served in North America for another year, stationed in cities including Halifax.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=27}}\n\n===1790s===\n[[File:Prince Edward By William J Weaver.png|upright|thumb|left|[[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn|Prince Edward]] with the [[Order of the Garter|Star of the Garter]], voted to him by the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]] in 1798.]]\n[[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn]] became the second member of the Royal Family to tour the Canadian colonies, and the first to live there for an extended period of time. Stationed at [[Gibraltar]] in 1790, he requested to be transferred to the Canadian colonies, in an effort to avoid the extreme Mediterranean heat.<ref>{{cite book|title=Prince Edward, Duke of Kent: Father of the Canadian Crown|page=56|year=2013|last=Tidridge|first=Nathan|publisher=Dundurn Press|isbn=1-4597-0790-7}}</ref> Arriving in [[Quebec City]] in 1791, he came as the colonel for the [[Royal Fusiliers|7th Regiment of Foot]], a military unit garrisoned in Quebec.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=30}} Shortly after his arrival, Edward was called upon by the [[Guy Carleton, 1st Baron Dorchester|Lord Dorchester]], the [[List of Governors General of Canada#Governors-in-Chief/Governors General of the Canadas, 1786\u20131841|Governor-in-Chief of the Canadas]], as 40 First Nations chiefs travelled to Quebec City to complain about American border incursions. Taking advantage of Edward's princely status, the Governor-in-Chief presented the Prince to First Nations' chiefs proclaiming \"Brothers! Here is Prince Edward, son of our king, who has just arrived with a chosen band of his warriors to protect this country,\" and subsequently named Edward as second-in-command of British forces in [[the Canadas]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=30}}\n\nEdward began to tour the Canadas in August 1791, departing from Quebec City to [[Montreal]], [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]], the [[Thousand Islands]], and [[Niagara-on-the-Lake|Newark-on-the-Lake]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=32}} Edward returned to Quebec City in time to act as an observer for the election of the first [[Legislative Assembly of Lower Canada]], in [[Charlesbourg, Quebec City|Charlesbourg]] in June 1792.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=33}} Edward is credited with the first use of the term \"Canadian\" to mean both [[French Canadian|French]] and [[English Canadians|English]] settlers in the Canadas. Witnessing a riot breaking out between two groups at the polling station, he entreated the public in French, \"I urge you to unanimity and concord. Let me hear no more of the odious distinction of English and French. You are all His Britannick Majesty's beloved Canadian subjects.\"{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=33}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Prince Edward, Duke of Kent: Father of the Canadian Crown|page=90|year=2013|last=Tidridge|first=Nathan|publisher=Dundurn Press|isbn=1-4597-0790-7}}</ref>\n\nWith the outbreak of the [[French Revolutionary War]], Edward was promoted to Major-General, and ordered to proceed to the Caribbean in January 1794. As the [[St. Lawrence River]] was frozen over for the winter, he was to travel overland to [[Boston]], before boarding a ship bound for [[Battle of Martinique (1794)|Martinique]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Prince Edward, Duke of Kent: Father of the Canadian Crown|publisher=Dundurn|first=Nathan|last=Tidridge|year=2013|isbn=1-4597-0791-5}}</ref> In doing so, he became the first member of the Royal Family to enter the newly-formed [[United States]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=36}}\n\nFollowing the West Indies campaign in the spring of 1794, he sailed for Halifax aboard {{HMS|Blanche|1786|6}}. Arriving on 10 May 1794, he left the city in June to tour Nova Scotia, and the newly-established colony of [[New Brunswick]], visiting [[Annapolis Royal]], and [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=36}} He was later made the [[Commander-in-Chief, North America#Commanders-in-Chief, Maritime provinces 1783\u20131875|Commander-in-Chief of the Maritimes]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=36}} During his time in Nova Scotia, he presided over the expansion of Halifax, and improved the [[Halifax Citadel#Halifax Defence Complex|city's defences]], due in part to his ability to secure funds from [[London]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=37}} He also worked to improve communications between the Canadian colonies, creating the first telegraph signal system in North America, and improving mail service between Halifax and Lower Canada.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=37}}{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=39}} Edward departed for Britain in August 1800, although he formally maintained his position as Commander-in-Chief of the region until 1802.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=39}} In 1811, Edward sought to obtain the appointment as the Governor General of the Canadas, although failed to do so.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=41}}\n\n==19th century==\nThe 19th century saw the beginning of modern royal tours in the country, with travel becoming easier and faster due to technological innovations such as the [[steamship]], and [[rail transport]]s. The mid-19th century marked the final time a member of the royal family made a [[transatlantic crossing]] by [[sailing ship]]; as royal family members began to travel by steamship in the late-19th century. While travelling through Canada, multiple modes of transportation were used when touring within Canada, including rail, on foot, and various-sized water vessels.\n\n===1860 royal tour===\nOn the 14 May 1859, the [[Legislative Assembly of the Province of Canada]] petitioned [[Queen Victoria]], and other members of the royal family to visit [[Montreal]] for the opening of [[Victoria Bridge (Montreal)|Victoria Bridge]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=42}} Unwilling to leave London in the hands of rivaling politicians, Victoria instead accepted the Canadian invitation on behalf of her son, Albert Edward, the Prince of Wales (later [[Edward VII]]).{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=42}} The Prince of Wales undertook a two-month tour of Newfoundland, New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, [[Prince Edward Island]], and the [[Province of Canada]] in 1860. The Prince of Wales' royal tour was used as the standard model for future royal tours for the next century.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=42}}\n\n====Newfoundland, and Maritime colonies====\n[[File:Arrival of the Prince of Wales at St. John's, Newfoundland, July 23, 1860 (NYPL Hades-165489-EM11624).tiff|thumb|left|The arrival of [[Edward VII|Albert Edward, Prince of Wales]] aboard HMS ''Hero'', in St. John's harbour, July 1860.]]\nThe Prince of Wales reached St. John's, Newfoundland, on 24 July 1860, aboard HMS ''Hero''.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=44}} The welcome reception the Prince of Wales received set the pattern for other welcome receptions during the royal tour, which typically included an official address at a [[Levee (ceremony)|levee]], and a formal ball held in the Prince of Wales' honour.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=44}} During his time there, he attended the [[Royal St. John's Regatta|St. John's Regatta]], and was gifted a [[Newfoundland dog]] on behalf of Newfoundlanders.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=44}}<ref name=heritage>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/special/royalvisit2005/history_e.cfm |last=Department of Canadian Heritage |authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion > The Canadian Monarchy > The Royal Presence in Canada > A Historical Overview |publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada |accessdate=14 July 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704031521/http://www.pch.gc.ca/special/royalvisit2005/history_e.cfm |archivedate=4 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nTravelling from St. John's he arrived in Halifax on 2 August. While in Halifax, he visited the [[Prince's Lodge, Nova Scotia|Prince's Lodge]], the country home used by his grandfather, the Duke of Kent and Strathearn.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=45}} From Halifax, the royal party boarded a train and stopped in [[Windsor, Nova Scotia|Windsor]], and [[Hantsport]], where they boarded HMS ''Styx'' to cross the [[Bay of Fundy]] to Saint John.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=46}} On 4 August, the Prince travelled through the [[St John River (New Brunswick)|St John River]] on the steamer ''Forest Queen'' to [[Fredericton]]. During his time there, he attended a royal reception, and inaugurated a park. Following his visit to Fredericton, he travelled to [[Pictou]], Nova Scotia to board HMS ''Hero'', returning to several communities, including Saint John, and Windsor.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=46}}\n\nHe landed at Charlottetown, Prince Edward Island, on 10 August, where he was welcomed by [[George Dundas (colonial administrator)|George Dundas]], the Governor of Prince Edward Island, and proceeded to [[Government House (Prince Edward Island)|Government House]]. There, he held audience with the [[Executive Council of Prince Edward Island]]. Along with formal ball and levee, the Prince toured the countryside around Charlottetown, and visited [[Province House (Prince Edward Island)|Province House]], where he received an addresses from the Executive Council. Upon his departure, he left with the Governor [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]150 for charitable use.<ref>{{cite book| last=Campbell| first=Duncan| title=History of Prince Edward Island| publisher=Bremner Brothers| year=1875| location=Charlottetown| pages=128\u2013130| url=http://www.islandregister.com/campbell/ch1.html| accessdate=11 July 2009| ref=CITEREF_Campbell_1875}}</ref>\n\n====Province of Canada====\n[[File:Prince of Wales lays last stone of Victoria Bridge.jpg|thumb|The Prince of Wales dedicating [[Victoria Bridge (Montreal)|Victoria Bridge]] in Montreal, as a part of his tour of [[Newfoundland Colony|Newfoundland]], [[Prince Edward Island]], [[Nova Scotia]], and the [[Province of Canada]] in 1860.]]\nThe Prince of Wales was formally welcomed into the Province of Canada by a Canadian delegation, who came aboard HMS ''Hero'' near [[Perc\u00e9 Rock]]. The Canadian welcome delegation consisted of the [[Governor General of the Province of Canada]], [[Edmund Walker Head]], and [[Joint Premiers of the Province of Canada|Joint Premiers]], [[George-\u00c9tienne Cartier]], and [[John A. Macdonald]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=46}} Arriving in Quebec City on 17 August, the Prince knighted [[Narcisse-Fortunat Belleau|Narcisse Belleau]], Speaker of the Legislative Council, and [[Henry Smith (Canadian politician)|Henry Smith]], Speaker of the Legislative Assembly. During his time there, he also visited [[Montmorency Falls]], and made an address at the [[Universit\u00e9 Laval]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=47}}\n\nFollowing his visit to Quebec City, the Prince of Wales proceeded towards Montreal aboard HMS ''Hero'', joined by several members of the Legislative Assembly near [[Trois-Rivi\u00e8res]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=47}} Arriving in Montreal, he took a specially-built open railway car to the Victoria Bridge in [[Pointe-Saint-Charles]], and tapped in-place the final-laid stone for the bridge.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=47}} During his five-day stay in Montreal, he stayed at the viceregal residence [[Government House (Quebec)|Spencerwood]], and inaugurated the city's [[Crystal Palace (Montreal)|Crystal Palace]], recalling the favourable impression made by Canadians at the [[The Great Exhibition|Great Exhibition]] in an address to the crowd.<ref name=heritage/>{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=49}}\n\nAt Ottawa, the Prince laid the foundation stone of the [[Centre Block|parliament buildings]], canoed on the [[Ottawa River]], and rode a [[timber slide]] on the [[Chaudi\u00e8re Falls]].<ref>{{Cite book| last=Hubbard| first=R.H.| title=Rideau Hall| publisher=McGill-Queen's University Press| year=1977| location=Montreal and London| pages=[https://archive.org/details/rideauhallillust00hubb/page/8 8\u20139]| isbn=978-0-7735-0310-6| ref=CITEREF_Hubbard_1977| url=https://archive.org/details/rideauhallillust00hubb/page/8}}</ref>{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=50}} Travelling towards [[Toronto]] aboard the steamer ''Kingston'', visits were planned for [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]], and Kingston, although anti-Catholic demonstrators from the [[Orange Order]] prevented the Prince from disembarking. In an attempt to not embroil the Prince in a controversy, [[Henry Pelham-Clinton, 5th Duke of Newcastle|Henry Pelham-Clinton]], the [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State|Under-Secretary of State]] who joined the Prince on his tour, informed mayors that they would not disembark until the demonstrators were dispersed.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=51}} Sailing further west, the Prince visited [[Cobourg]], [[Rice Lake (Ontario)|Rice Lake]], and [[Peterborough]], where he received a reception from the [[Mississaugas]]. He then proceeded to [[Port Hope, Ontario|Port Hope]], re-boarding ''Kingston'' to sail on to Toronto.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=52}}\n\nDuring a levee in Toronto, the Prince received a delegation from Belleville and Kingston, tending apologies for the early incident.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=53}} On 10 September, he took a one-day excursion to [[Collingwood, Ontario|Collingwood]], before returning to Toronto the following day. On his way back, he visited and received addresses from [[Aurora, Ontario|Aurora]], [[Barrie]], [[Bradford, Ontario|Bradford]], and [[Newmarket, Ontario|Newmarket]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=53}} In Toronto, the Prince attended the [[Royal Canadian Yacht Club]]'s regatta, agreeing to become its [[patron]]; and opened [[Allan Gardens]], and [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]] to the public. He departed the city for [[London, Ontario]] on 12 September, visiting [[Guelph]] and [[Stratford, Ontario|Stratford]] on the way.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=53}} From London, he travelled to [[Sarnia, Ontario|Sarnia]], in order to attend a gathering of 150 First Nations representatives in the Province of Canada. Following this gathering, he briefly returned to London, before travelling by railway to the [[Niagara Peninsula]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=53}}\n[[File:H.R.H. Prince of Wales and Suite at Point View, Niagara.jpg|thumb|upright|left|The Prince of Wales touring [[Niagara Falls]], [[Canada West]], September 1860.]] \nIn the peninsula, he visited [[Brantford]], [[Chippewa, Ontario|Chippewa]], [[Fort Erie]], and [[Queenston, Ontario|Queenston]]. The [[Niagara Falls]] were illuminated for the first time during his tour of the falls.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ontariotravel.net/TcisCtrl?site=consumers&key1=experiences&key2=NaturalWonders&language=EN&linkType=I| last=Ontario Tourism Marketing Partnership| title=Things to Do > Natural Wonders > Did You Know?| publisher=Queen's Printer for Ontario| accessdate=2 July 2009}}</ref> There, he rode on the ''[[Maid of the Mist]]''. At Queenston, he met with 160 [[War of 1812]] veterans, dedicated a rebuilt [[Brock's Monument]], and visited [[Laura Secord]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=54}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Toffoli| first=Gary| title=CBC's Attack on Canadian Heritage| journal=Monarchy Canada| publisher=Monarchist League of Canada| location=Toronto| date=10 August 1998| url=http://www.monarchist.ca/mc/cbc.htm| accessdate=2 July 2009| ref=harv| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215171031/http://www.monarchist.ca/mc/cbc.htm| archivedate=15 February 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Morden| first=James Cochenaur| title=Historic Niagara Falls| publisher=Lindsay Press| year=1932| location=Niagara Falls| page=87| url=http://www.ourroots.ca/f/page.aspx?id=591290}}</ref> From Queenston, he moved towards Niagara-on-the-Lake, [[St. Catherines, Ontario|St. Catherines]], and [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=55}}\n\nCompleting his royal tour of the Province of Canada in late-September, the Prince of Wales departed for the United States from [[Windsor, Ontario]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=55}} Taking a month-long personal tour of the United States, he travelled under the pseudonym \"Lord Renfrew,\" in an attempt to not attract attention to himself.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=55}} The Canadian co-premieres saw-off the Prince's during his departure from Canada, and again from the United States, travelling to [[Portland, Maine]] on 20 October 1860 to see the Prince off.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=55}}\n\n===1861\u20131883===\nIn 1861, [[Alfred, Duke of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Alfred]] took a five-week tour of [[The Maritimes]], Newfoundland, and the Province of Canada. While escorting Prince Alfred through [[Canada West]], the Governor General of Canada used the opportunity to make sketches of American defences around the [[Great Lakes]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Civil War Years: Canada and the United States|url=https://archive.org/details/civilwaryearscan0000wink|url-access=registration|year=1998|page=[https://archive.org/details/civilwaryearscan0000wink/page/55 55]|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press|first=Robin W.|last=Winks|isbn=0-7735-6763-1}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1869 to 1870, [[Prince Arthur, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn|Prince Arthur]] was stationed in Canada as a British Army officer in the [[Rifle Brigade (The Prince Consort's Own)|Rifle Brigade's]] Montreal detachment. Arriving in Halifax, he undertook a two-month royal tour of the colony of Prince Edward Island, and the newly formed Dominion of Canada, before returning to military duty in Montreal.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=80\u201381}} In the same year, the [[Six Nations of the Grand River]] conferred the title of chief to Prince Arthur. In a formal ceremony, the chief of the three \"clans\" of the [[Mohawk people|Mohawks]] received The Prince, and conferred upon him the name \"Kavakoudge,\" meaning \"the sun flying from east to west under the guidance of the Great Spirit.\"{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=83}} Although the title of chief was bestowed as an honourary title to a number of individuals, Alfred underwent the necessary rituals to formalize the title in Mohawk society.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=83}}\n[[File:Prince Arthur Mohawk Chapel Canada 1869.jpg|thumb|During his 1869 royal tour, [[Prince Arthur, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn|Prince Arthur]] met with the Chiefs of the [[Six Nations of the Grand River|Six Nations]] at the [[Mohawk Chapel]].]]\nDuring his time in Canada, Prince Arthur became the first member of the royal family to attend the [[opening of the Canadian parliament]], in February 1870.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=81}} Prince Arthur, along with his regiment, was present at the [[Battle of Eccles Hill]], a raid conducted by the American-based [[Fenian Brotherhood]], on 25 May 1870.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=81}} The Prince was awarded the [[Canada General Service Medal]] for his participation in the [[Fenian raids]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=82}} Returning to the United Kingdom in 1870, Prince Arthur would return to Canada on two more occasions, the latter visit as the Governor General of Canada.\n\nOther members of the royal family were also in Canada as a part of their military service during the late-1870s and early-1880s. Prince Alfred was stationed at Royal Naval Dockyard, Halifax from time to time between 1878 and 1883, as Commander of the Royal Navy's North Atlantic Squadron.<ref name=heritage /> [[George V|Prince George of Wales]] (later George V) was stationed in the Maritimes in 1882 as a midshipman on [[HMS Cumberland (1842)|HMS ''Cumberland'']]. During his time there, he drove the last spike into Newfoundland's first railway, the [[Newfoundland Railway|Harbour Grace Railway]].<ref name=RT>{{cite web| url=http://www.railways.incanada.net/circle/Royal_Trains.html| last=Churcher| first=Colin| title=Colin Churcher's Railway Pages > Royal Trains and Royal Occasions| publisher=Colin Churcher| accessdate=12 July 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060217005948/http://www.railways.incanada.net/circle/Royal_Trains.html| archivedate=17 February 2006| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Princess as the viceregal consort (1878\u20131883)====\nIn 1878, [[Benjamin Disraeli]], the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], requested the [[John Campbell, 9th Duke of Argyll|Marquess of Lorne]] be appointed the next [[Governor General of Canada]], with his wife, [[Princess Louise, Duchess of Argyll]] serving as the [[viceregal consort of Canada]]. Disraeli's nomination of Lorne was largely motivated by his desire to see a member of the royal family reside in Canada for an extended period.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=57}} Prior to his appointment as the Canadian Governor General, Lorne was virtually unknown to the public, with little concrete record of public service. The attraction for appointing Lorne to the office was having his spouse, Princess Louise, reside in Canada.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=58}} \n[[File:Opening of Canadian Parliament 1879.gif|thumb|[[Princess Louise, Duchess of Argyll|Princess Louise]] accompanies the [[John Campbell, 9th Duke of Argyll|Marquess of Lorne]], the [[Governor General of Canada]] during the opening the [[4th Canadian Parliament]], 1879.]]\nArriving in Canada on 23 November 1878, the viceregal couple was greeted by Prince Alfred, who was serving as a Royal Navy officer, stationed in Halifax.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=57}} Lorne was formally sworn in as the Governor General in [[Province House (Nova Scotia)|Province House]], Halifax, before they proceeded towards the capital, in Ottawa.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=57}} Arriving in Ottawa on 2 December, the head of the Canadian ministry, [[John A. Macdonald]], was not present at the viceregal welcome reception. Macdonald's absence from the welcome reception was depicted as a purposeful insult to the princess by the [[Official Opposition (Canada)|opposition]] [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=59}} They proceeded to take a private trip to Niagara Falls in January 1879, before returning to Ottawa to open the [[4th Canadian Parliament]], on 13 February 1879.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=60}}\n\nThey undertook an official tour of [[Eastern Canada]] from mid-May 1879, touring Montreal during [[Victoria Day]], awarding prizes to [[officer cadets]] of the [[Royal Military College of Canada]] in Kingston.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=60}}  On 9 June, they opened [[Terrasse Dufferin]] in Quebec City, and later laid the [[cornerstone]] of [[Ramparts of Quebec City|Porte Kent]], gifted to the city from Queen Victoria.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=60}}  Following their tour of Quebec, they proceeded towards [[The Maritimes]] and [[Ontario]]. In Toronto, they opened the first [[Canadian National Exhibition]], and attended the [[Queen's Plate]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=61}}<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.woodbineentertainment.com/queensplate/History.aspx| title=History > History of Queen's Plate| publisher=Woodbine Entertainment Group| accessdate=2 July 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090614063730/http://www.woodbineentertainment.com/queensplate/history.aspx| archivedate=14 June 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> During their time in Ottawa, both Lorne and Louise worked towards the creation of a national arts association, establishing the [[Royal Canadian Academy of Arts]] in 1880.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=66}}\n\nOn 14 February 1880 in Ottawa, Princess Louise was injured after her horse-drawn sleigh was turned over. Hitting her head on the metal frame of the sleigh, Louise suffered from [[neuralgia]] after the incident. The public was not made aware of the event, with the [[aide-de-camp]] to the Governor General downplaying the incident to the press. She did not make another public appearance until April 1880.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=62}} While recovering, she was visited by her brother [[Prince Leopold, Duke of Albany|The Prince Leopold]]. Louise and Leopold privately toured Quebec, Ontario, and the American city of [[Chicago]] until 31 July 1880, when both returned to the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=62}} \n[[File:A street market at Christmas time; reindeer, pigs, fruit, tu Wellcome V0040157.jpg|thumb|left|Princess Louise and the Marquess of Lorne visiting a street market in [[Ottawa]] around [[Christmas]], c. 1880s.]]\nDuring Lorne's 1881 tour of the [[Northwest Territories]], he proposed a section of the territory take its Alberta after his wife (whose full name was Louise Caroline Alberta).{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=62}} Similarly, Princess Louise was the one who proposed the name for [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]], from the Latin word for Queen.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=62}}<ref name=Regina>{{cite journal| last=Archer| first=John H.| title=Regina: A Royal City| journal=Monarchy Canada Magazine| volume=Spring 1996| publisher=Monarchist League of Canada| location=Toronto| year=1996| url=http://www.monarchist.ca/mc/regina.htm| accessdate=30 June 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209220023/http://www.monarchist.ca/mc/regina.htm| archivedate=9 February 2008| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nLouise returned to Canada until 4 June 1882, although rumors of a [[Fenian]] plot against her forced her to remain in the [[Citadelle of Quebec]],{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=63}} a military installation used by the [[Canadian militia]], and the secondary residence for the Monarch, and the Governor General. On 30 August, Lorne and Louise set out for an official tour of [[British Columbia]], visiting [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], and meeting with a First Nations delegation in [[New Westminster]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=64}} Louise remained in Victoria as Lorne continued with the official tour into the [[British Columbia Interior]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=64}} They remained in the province until 7 December 1882, with their tour extended to counter secessionist sentiments in the province, a result of the federal government's failure to produce a transcontinental rail link by 1881.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=65}} [[Robert Beaven]], the [[Premier of British Columbia]] was said to have suggested the province secede from Canada, and establish an independent kingdom with Louise as its Queen. The resulting crisis had spurred Lorne to push the Canadian government to hasten the development of the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=65}}\n\nLouise was visited by another member of the royal family, Prince George of Wales, in April 1883.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=65}} Shortly before the end of his fifth year as Governor General, Lorne declined an option to serve the position for another year. His decision to turn down an additional year in office was questioned by some, with Queen Victoria suspecting that Lorne was jealous of Louise's popularity with Canadians, in contrast to his own.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=65}} The Marquess and Princess Louise concluded their term in Canada with a farewell tours in Montreal, and Toronto, leaving for the United Kingdom from Quebec City on 27 October 1883.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=66}}\n\n===1884\u20131900===\nIn 1890, Prince Arthur conducted another tour of Canada, arriving in British Columbia from his earlier service with the British Army in the [[British Raj]]. During this tour, he travelled east towards the Maritimes, primarily by railway, before continuing on to the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=83}}\n\n[[Princess Marie Louise of Schleswig-Holstein|Princess Marie Louise]] arrived in Canada in 1900 to tour the country, however controversy surrounding her spouse, [[Prince Aribert of Anhalt]] forced her to return to the United Kingdom shortly after her arrival. After Prince Aribert was found in bed with another man, his father, [[Frederick I, Duke of Anhalt]], accused Marie Louise of indecency, claiming that his son was denied his conjugal rights. Marie Louise was at [[Rideau Hall]] when the Governor General gave her two telegrams instructing her to return to the United Kingdom immediately.<ref>{{cite book|title=Now You Know \u2014 Heroes, Villains, and Visionaries|year=2013|publisher=Dundurn|last=Lennox|first=Doug|isbn=1-4597-2477-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Twilight of Splendor: The Court of Queen Victoria During Her Diamond Jubilee Year|page=58|last=King|first=Greg|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2007|isbn=0-4700-4439-X}}</ref> Her marriage with Prince Aribert was annulled in December 1900, with his father using his prerogative as a reigning Duke of [[Duchy of Anhalt|Anhalt]] to annul the marriage.\n\n==Early 20th century (1901\u20131950)==\n===1900s===\n====1901 royal tour====\n[[File:Duke of York at Montreal and Quebec 1901.ogv|thumb|alt=George in military dress uniform hands out medals to servicemen, rides in a carriage and inspects a guard of honour|[[George V|Prince George]] in [[Montreal]] and [[Quebec City]]. He visited most of the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|provinces]] during his 1901 royal tour.]]\nThe first royal tour to take place since the death of Queen Victoria was conducted by the second son of the reigning king, Prince George, Duke of Cornwall and York (later George V), his spouse, [[Mary of Teck|Mary, Duchess of Cornwall and York]] (later Queen Mary), and the Duchesses brother, [[Alexander Cambridge, 1st Earl of Athlone|Prince Alexander of Teck]] (later the Earl of Athlone). The tour in Canada formed a part of a larger eight-month royal tour of the [[British Empire]] that began on 16 March 1901, with the Duke and Duchess' departure from [[Portsmouth]], United Kingdom.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=69}}\n\nThe Canadian portion of the tour was originally planned to begin in British Columbia, proceeding eastward through the country. However, after [[South Africa]] was added onto the royal tour, the decision was made to begin to the royal tour in Quebec City, and conclude it in Halifax.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=69}} As the period of court mourning for Queen Victoria's death had not yet expired during their time in Canada, public balls, banquets, and levees planned for the royal tour were cancelled, with only official dinners, concerts, receptions, and reviews taking place.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=70}} During the tour, Prince George kept a methodical record of his activities, recording that he shook the hands of 24,855 people at official receptions; received 544 addresses; laid 21 cornerstones; gave 100 speeches; and presented 4,329 medals.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=75}}\n\nThe Canadian portion of the 1901 royal tour began 16 September 1901, when the {{RMS|Ophir||6}} arrived in Quebec City.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=69}} The royal party{{spaced ndash}}which consisted of 22 people, landed at Quebec City on 16 September. During his time in Quebec City, Prince George invested Lieutenant [[Richard Ernest William Turner]] with the [[Victoria Cross]] for his conduct during the [[Battle of Leliefontein]] in a ceremony at the [[Plains of Abraham]], and spoke to students at the Universit\u00e9 Laval.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=71}} Moving west of Quebec City by railway, the group made stops to Montreal, and Ottawa.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=74}} Throughout the royal tour, Prince George placed an emphasis on praising the creation, and expansion of the country during his own lifetime, giving a speech about the country's development and growth in Ottawa and Winnipeg.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=73\u201374}}\n[[File:Timber slide 1901.jpg|thumb|left|The royal party rides a [[timber slide]] near Ottawa during the 1901 royal tour.]]\nIn Ottawa, Prince George dedicated the [[Alexandra Bridge]] in Ottawa, rode a timber slide, and watched the [[lacrosse]] final for the [[Minto Cup]], a match he enjoyed so much he kept the ball that was used.<ref name=RT /> Departing from Ottawa, they passed through Ontario, creating \"incredible excitement seldom seen since the visit of his father in 1860.\"<ref name=heritage /> The Duke and Duchess arrived in [[Manitoba]] where the former opened the new science building at the [[University of Manitoba]], and then to Regina in the Northwest Territories.<ref name=\"Regina\"/> In [[Calgary]], they met with First Nations chiefs and viewed exhibitions, before concluding their western-leg of their tour in [[Vancouver]] and [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]]. They group then turned back again towards [[Banff, Alberta|Banff]], where the Duchess went to [[Tunnel Mountain]] and [[Lake Louise (Alberta)|Lake Louise]], while the Duke went to Poplar Point.\n\nAfter passing back through Regina,<ref name=Regina /> they reunited in Toronto, welcomed by the [[Toronto Mendelssohn Choir]], and attended concerts at [[Massey Hall]]. They proceeded to tour throughout [[Southern Ontario]], before returning to Montreal, where the Duke opened the newly rebuilt Victoria Bridge. The Canadian tour ended with a trip through Saint John, and their departure from Halifax.<ref>{{Harvnb| Hubbard| 1977| pp=101\u2013106}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Nicolson, Harold|chapter=''Ophir'' itinerary|title= King George V: His Life and Reign|year=1959|page=68|location=NY|publisher=Doubleday|url=https://archive.org/stream/kinggeorgethefif006892mbp#page/n105/mode/2up/search/canada}}</ref> Following their departure from Halifax, the global royal tour proceeded towards Newfoundland, a separate colony not associated with Canada at the time. In Newfoundland, they received nine-month old Newfoundland dog, which was later given their son, [[Edward VIII|Prince Edward]] (later Edward VIII).{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=75}}\n\n====Tercentenary of Quebec City (1908)====\n[[File:(Quebec Tercentenary) Prince of Wales, attended by Earl Grey Col. S.A. Denison, Lord Lovat, Gen. Pole-Carew and Gen. Lake at the Military Review Quebec.jpg|upright|thumb|George, Prince of Wales attending a military review for the [[Canadian militia]], 1908.]]\nIn 1908 the Canadian government asked King Edward VII to preside over the [[tercentenary]] celebrations for the founding of Quebec City. Edward VII would accept the invitation on behalf of his son, George, Prince of Wales (later George V). The Prince of Wales arrived at Quebec City aboard the Royal Navy cruiser, {{HMS|Indomitable|1907|6}}. Unlike his earlier tour in 1901, his royal tour in 1908 was limited to the ceremony in Quebec City, as well as a military review of the Canadian militia on the Plains of Abraham.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=76}}\n\n===1910s===\nFrom 1911 to 1916, Prince Arthur, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn served as Canada's Governor General, with the [[Princess Louise Margaret of Prussia|Duchess of Connaught and Strathearn]] serving as his viceregal consort. The Duke was the first member of the royal family to serve the office of Governor General of Canada. Originally his appointment was for only two-years, although at the request of [[Robert Borden]], the [[Prime Minister of Canada]], his tenure would later be extended to five-years.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=88}}  The Duke, Duchess, and their daughter, [[Princess Patricia of Connaught]], arrived in Quebec City on 13 October 1911 and was later sworn into office at the [[Parliament of Quebec]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=85}} Several weeks after being sworn in, he presided over the opening of the [[Parliament of Canada]] in Ottawa.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=85}} \n\nThe Duke and Duchess conducted his first tour as Governor General in 1911, proceeding to Toronto, Hamilton, Kingston, and finally Montreal on 27 November 1911. Further tours with the Duke, and Princess Patricia, were undertaken in May 1912, to Winnipeg, and the Maritimes.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=85}}  On 28 August 1912, the Duke, Duchess, and their daughter conducted a tour of the west, visiting [[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario|Sault Ste. Marie]], [[Saskatoon]], [[Prince Albert, Saskatchewan|Prince Albert]], [[Edmonton]], Calgary, Banff, Vancouver, [[Prince Rupert, British Columbia|Prince Rupert]], and Victoria, where they inspected personnel of the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] at [[Esquimalt Royal Navy Dockyard]]. They then proceeded towards [[Medicine Hat]], Regina, and [[Brandon, Manitoba|Brandon]], before concluding their tour in Toronto and Ottawa.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=85\u201386}}\n[[File:Postcard of Vice-Regal Visit to Valcartier Military Base 1914.jpg|left|thumb|Prince Arthur visits [[CFB Valcartier|Valcartier base]] as the Governor General in 1914. He served the position from 1911 to 1916.]]\nWhile serving as the Governor General, the Duke inaugurated the [[Saskatchewan Legislative Building]], and laid the cornerstone for the [[Cathedral of St. John the Evangelist (Saskatoon)|Cathedral of St. John the Evangelist]] in Regina,<ref name=UoS>{{Cite book| last=Jackson| first=Michael D.| contribution=Royal Visits| year=1990| title=The Encyclopedia of Saskatchewan| editor-last=Cottrell| editor-first=Michael| place=Regina| publisher=Canadian Plains Research Centre| url=http://esask.uregina.ca/entry/royal_visits.html| accessdate=30 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://scaa.sk.ca/gallery/aerial/landmark_key.html#45| title=Departments > City Clerk's Office > City Archives > Image Galleries > A View From Above > Downtown III: Spadina Crescent to the Bessborough > Note 45| publisher=City of Saskatoon| accessdate=30 June 2009}}</ref> and for the new Provincial Library at the [[British Columbia Parliament Buildings]].<ref name=VanHist>{{cite web| url=http://www.vancouverhistory.ca/chronology1919.htm| last=Davis| first=Chuck| title=History of Metropolitan Vancouver > 1919| publisher=Chuck Davis| accessdate=24 June 2009}}</ref> The Duke returned to Banff on two occasions, in August 1914, and May 1916.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=86}}   In addition to Canada, he also visited [[Dominion of Newfoundland|Newfoundland]], a separate [[dominion]] of the [[British Empire]] in 1914.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=86}}\n\nIn 1913, [[George VI|The Prince Albert]] (later George VI) conducted his first royal tour of the Canada, as well as Newfoundland, while serving aboard the Royal Navy cruiser {{HMS|Cumberland|1902|6}}.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=107}}\n\nIn January 1913, the Duchess was hospitalized as a result of her declining health, with the viceregal family returning to London, UK, in March 1913. During this period, the Duke, continuing to serve as Governor General, received regular correspondences from Borden through [[electrical telegraph|telegraph]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=88}} After the Duchess recovered, the family returned to Canada in October 1913.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=88}} During [[World War I]], the Duke was involved in recruitment, and raising the morale of soldiers.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=89}} Princess Patricia worked for the [[Canadian Red Cross]], and continued working for a Canadian hospital in [[Orpington]], UK, after her father's term as Governor General ended in 1916.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=88}} Several months after Centre Block on Parliament Hill was ravaged by a fire, the Duke laid the memorial cornerstone for its replacement on 1 September 1916. The Duke's tenure as Governor General ended on 16 October 1916.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=90}}\n\n====1919 royal tour====\n[[File:PrinceOfWalesCanoeing.jpg|thumb|[[Edward VIII|Edward, Prince of Wales]] with two [[Ojibwe]] guides, canoe on the [[Nipigon River]] during his 1919 royal tour.]]\nAfter the end of World War I in November 1918, Edward, Prince of Wales (later Edward VIII) set out to develop his role as the [[Prince of Wales]] through a tour of the Empire, with his first tour occurring in the dominions of Newfoundland and Canada in 1919.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=91}} Organization for the tour was undertaken by [[Joseph Pope (public servant)|Joseph Pope]], the Assistant Clerk to the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|Privy Council for Canada]].{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=93}} Unlike earlier tours, the 1919 royal tour dropped the rigid formalities of earlier tours, partly due to authorities' inability to control the crowds who came to see the Prince.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=93}} The informality of the tour was matched by the Prince of Wales, whose informal dress, and mannerisms had struck the right note with Canadians.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=97}}\n\nBoarding {{HMS|Renown|1916|6}} on 5 August 1919, Edward proceeded towards St. John's, Newfoundland, and Charlottetown, before proceeding towards Quebec City on 21 August 1919. Proceeding towards Ontario, he laid the foundation stone of the [[Peace Tower]] on Parliament Hill, met with the League of Canadian Indians at Sault Ste. Marie, and took a three-day canoe trip down the [[Nipigon River]] to fish and hunt with two [[Ojibwa]] guides.<ref>{{cite journal| last=Whalen| first=James| title=Royalty on the Nipigon| journal=The Archivist| issue=117| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| location=Ottawa| year=1998| url=http://members.shaw.ca/amuir/royally.htm| accessdate=3 July 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070217124035/http://members.shaw.ca/amuir/royally.htm| archivedate=17 February 2007| url-status=dead}}</ref> On the 26 August, he inaugurated Warriors' Day at the Canadian National Exhibition.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=93}}\n\nHe then travelled to Regina, where he renamed a library the ''Prince of Wales Library''. He then proceeded towards [[Vancouver]], toured the area, attended a civic reception and military ball, as well as opening the New Westminster Exhibition.<ref name=VanHist /> While in Alberta, he was named Chief Morning Star by the Chiefs of the [[Nakoda (Stoney)|Nakoda]] First Nations.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=104}} The Prince also went on to Victoria, where he laid the foundation stone of a statue of Queen Victoria on the grounds of the British Columbia Parliament Buildings.<ref name=Legacy>{{cite web| url=http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/legacy.htm| last=British Columbia Archives| title=The Legacy| publisher=Queen's Printer for British Columbia| accessdate=25 June 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228171614/http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/legacy.htm| archivedate=28 February 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===1920s and 1930s===\n[[File:KingRoyals1927.jpg|thumb|Edward, Prince of Wales and [[Prince George, Duke of Kent|Prince George]] at [[Rideau Hall]] (seated, fifth and sixth from the left, respectively), during their 1927 royal tour.]]\nIn 1923, the Prince of Wales was in Canada on a visit, and work on his privately owned ranch, E. P. Ranch. Arriving at Quebec City on 12 September, he made stops in Ottawa and Winnipeg before reaching his private ranch near Calgary, known as E. P. Ranch.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=98}} He made another private visit to his ranch in 1924, as well as touring as well various towns and cities; in the latter year, he stopped at Rideau Hall for various official functions and again frustrated his staff by disappearing for dancing and golf.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hubbard|1977|p=157}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926, the brother to the Prince of Wales, [[Prince George, Duke of Kent|The Prince George]] (later Duke of Kent), arrived in Canada and actively took part in squash, badminton, and tennis games played in Rideau Hall's Tent Room;<ref>{{Harvnb| Hubbard| 1977| p=162}}</ref> the Governor General, [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|The Marquess of Willingdon]], said of the Prince: \"Such a nice boy, but shy, & as mad ib exercise as the P. of W.\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Freeman-Thomas|first=Freeman|author-link=Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|date=29 October 1926|editor-last=Hubbard|editor-first=R.H.|title=Rideau Hall|periodical=1977|publication-place=Montreal and London|publisher=McGill-Queen's University Press|isbn=978-0-7735-0310-6|url=https://archive.org/details/rideauhallillust00hubb}}</ref> Prince George, along with the Prince of Wales, conducted another royal tour of Canada in 1927. During the tour, the Prince of Wales and Prince George opened [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]] and the [[Princes' Gates]] in Toronto.<ref>{{Cite news | authorlink = Mike Filey | last =Filey | first = Mike | title=Union Station turns 80| newspaper=Toronto Sun| date=5 August 2007| url=http://www.torontosun.com/Lifestyle/Columnists/Filey_Mike/2007/08/05/4395354-sun.html| archive-url=https://archive.is/20070930210244/http://www.torontosun.com/Lifestyle/Columnists/Filey_Mike/2007/08/05/4395354-sun.html| url-status=dead| archive-date=30 September 2007| accessdate=6 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n====1939 royal tour====\n{{main|1939 royal tour of Canada}}\n[[File:George VI visits Woodbine Race Track.jpg|thumb|King George VI and Queen Elizabeth visit the [[Queen's Plate|King's Plate]] in [[Toronto]], during the 1939 royal tour.]]\nThe 1939 royal tour of Canada was a cross-Canada royal tour by [[King George VI]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]]. It was one of the first visits of a reigning monarch to Canada (in 1926, [[Queen Marie of Romania]] also visited the country<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19380719&id=1JEjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dqgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6052,2123265 |title=Ovation Given by Montreal |work=Montreal Gazette |via=Google News |date=19 July 1938 |page=12 |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>). This tour marked the first time that the sovereign's official Canadian birthday was marked with the monarch himself present in the country; the occasion was marked on Parliament Hill with a celebration and a [[Trooping the Colour|Trooping of the Colour]].\n\nLater, during a tour of Canada, Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother stated in a speech: \"It is now some 46 years since I first came to this country with the King, in those anxious days shortly before the outbreak of the Second World War. I shall always look back upon that visit with feelings of affection and happiness. I think I lost my heart to Canada and Canadians, and my feelings have not changed with the passage of time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/interactive/royalvisits/52.html| title=CBC: Royal Visits to Canada| publisher=CBC| location=Canada | accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n===1940s===\nThe [[Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone]] resided in Canada from June 1940 to April 1946 as the viceregal consort of Canada; accompanying her spouse, Alexander, Earl of Athlone, who was sworn in as the Governor General of Canada on 21 June.<ref name=Athl>{{cite book|title=Canada's Prime Ministers, Governors General and Fathers of Confederation|last=Coucill|first=Irma|page=[https://archive.org/details/canadasprimemini0000couc/page/84 84]|publisher=Pembrooke Publisher Limited|year=2005|isbn=1-5513-8185-0|url=https://archive.org/details/canadasprimemini0000couc/page/84}}</ref> In addition to the Princess Alice, [[Alastair Windsor, 2nd Duke of Connaught and Strathearn|Alastair, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn]] has also been residing in Canada from 1940, as the aide-de-camp to Alexander in his capacity as Governor General. On 23 April 1943, Alastair was found dead on the floor of his room at Rideau Hall. He had died from hypothermia.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Aronson|first1=Theo|title=Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone|date=1981|publisher=Cassell|location=London|isbn=978-0304307579|page=211}}</ref> Newspapers at the time cited the cause of death as \"natural causes.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11349086 |title=DEATH OF DUKE OF CONNAUGHT IN CANADA |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)]] |issue=30,162 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=28 April 1943 |accessdate=17 April 2018 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n[[File:KingCheersForAthlone.jpg|thumb|[[Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone]] with the [[Alexander Cambridge, 1st Earl of Athlone|Earl of Athlone]] and [[William Lyon Mackenzie King]], March 1946]]\nIn 1941, [[Prince George, Duke of Kent]] visited several [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] bases in Canada.<ref name=DCH/> In the same year, Edward, the Duke of Windsor (formerly Edward VIII) visited Canada to stay at his private ranch in Alberta. He entered Canada at [[North Portal]], before proceeding towards Calgary the next day. As the visit was only few years removed from the [[Edward VIII abdication crisis|1936 abdication crisis]], he was initially discouraged from visiting by the Canadian Prime Minister, [[William Lyon Mackenzie King]]. However, King would later send Edward a telegram welcoming him shortly after he entered the country.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=104}} Edward departed Canada after spending nine days there, summoned back to [[the Bahamas]] as its [[List of governors of the Bahamas|Governor]], after a hurricane struck the islands. Edward would visit Canada on two more occasions, visiting New Brunswick in 1945, and Alberta in 1950. During his time in Alberta, Edward slept at the viceregal suite of the [[Fairmont Palliser Hotel|Palliser Hotel]] in Calgary; as the state of his ranch had deteriorated in the years since his last visit. In 1945, Edward sought the appointment as the Governor General of Canada, although failed to obtain it.{{sfn|Bousfuield|Toffoli|2010|p=104}}\n\nBy 1945, [[Alan Lascelles]], the [[Private Secretary to the Sovereign|private secretary of George VI]], and Shuldham Redfern, [[Secretary to the Governor General of Canada]], were discussing the idea of the King making regular flights to Canada to open parliament and perform other constitutional and ceremonial duties. The notion was eventually forgotten.<ref>{{citation| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZcIf46DzpfUC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false| last=Jackson| first=Michael D.| title=The Crown and Canadian Federalism| year=2013| publisher=Dundurn Press| isbn=9781459709898| accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Late 20th century (1951\u20132000)==\n===Elizabeth II===\n[[Elizabeth II]] conducted 20 official tours of Canada from 1951 to 2000. She first toured Canada in 1951, as Princess Elizabeth, Duchess of Edinburgh.<ref name=BCArchives>{{cite web| url=http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm| last=British Columbia Archives| title=Chronology of Principal Royal Visits to British Columbia| publisher=Queen's Printer for British Columbia| accessdate=25 June 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228124243/http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm| archivedate=28 February 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> In her subsequent tours of the country, she toured it as the Queen of Canada. In addition to official tours, in the 20th century, the Queen had made nine stopovers in Canada, in order to refuel the aircraft she was travelling on.<ref name=pastt>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/services/past-royal-tours.html|title=Past Royal Tours|publisher=Government of Canada|date=24 October 2018|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n====1950s====\n[[File:Princess Elizabeth holding flowers on stage with Prince Philip and several people. Royal Visit 1951, Ontario.jpg|thumb|[[Elizabeth II|Princess Elizabeth]] along with [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] during their 1951 royal tour.]]\n[[Elizabeth II|Princess Elizabeth, Duchess of Edinburgh]], and her husband, the [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]], made their first appearance in Newfoundland, Prince Edward Island, Nova Scotia, Quebec, Ontario, Saskatchewan, British Columbia, and Alberta in 1951, on behalf of her ailing father.<ref name=BCArchives/> The [[National Film Board of Canada]] produced a documentary film ''[[Royal Journey]]'', chronicling the 1951 royal tour.\n\nThe couple toured New Brunswick; after the Princess and Duke arrived at Fredericton's Union Station on 6 November, they were there greeted by both Lieutenant Governor [[David Laurence MacLaren]] and hundreds of well-wishers,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=1| last=Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| title=Exhibits and Education Tools > Royal Visits to New Brunswick > The Golden Jubilee: A New Brunswick Tribute > 1951 > Welcome to New Brunswick > November 6, 1951| year=2009| publisher=Queen's Printer for New Brunswick| accessdate=9 July 2009| ref=CITEREF_Provincial_Archives_of_New_Brunswick_2009}}</ref> and moved on to tour the [[University of New Brunswick]], [[Christ Church Cathedral (Fredericton)|Christ Church Cathedral]], and the [[New Brunswick Legislative Building|Legislative Assembly Building]].<ref>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=1 Visiting Provincial Landmarks]}}</ref> It was then on to [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]], where the royal couple travelled in a motorcade watched by some 60,000 people, visited a veterans' hospital, and attended a civic dinner at the Admiral Beatty Hotel, where the silver flatware designed specifically for the 1939 visit of the King was used. After an overnight on the royal train, Princess Elizabeth and the Duke of Edinburgh made whistle-stops in [[Moncton]] and [[Sackville, New Brunswick|Sackville]] before departing the province.<ref name=\"StJ\"/> In Toronto, she took in a [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] game at [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] and greeted Ontarians at numerous official functions.\n\nAside from a brief stop-over for refuelling in [[Gander, Newfoundland and Labrador|Gander, Newfoundland]] in 1953{{mdash}} during which the Queen decided, after being roused from sleep at 3:20&nbsp;am by their singing of \"[[For He's a Jolly Good Fellow|For She's a Jolly Good Fellow]]\", to address the crowd gathered outside,<ref>{{Harvnb| Bousfield| 2002| p=87}}</ref>\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Phillip sit on thrones before a full Parliament.jpg|upright|thumb|left|Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip at the [[Opening of the Canadian parliament|opening of]] the [[23rd Canadian Parliament]], 14 October 1957.]]\nElizabeth returned to Canada in 1957, there giving her first ever live television address, appointing her husband to [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|her Canadian Privy Council]] at a meeting which she chaired, and on 14 October, opening the first session of the [[23rd Canadian Parliament|23rd parliament]].<ref name=Bousfield>{{Harvnb| Bousfield| 2002| pp=11\u201316}}</ref> About 50,000 people descended on Parliament Hill to witness the arrival of the monarch.<ref>{{Harvnb| Trepanier| 1989| p=30}}</ref> Due to the financial austerity of the times,<ref>{{Cite journal| last=Callwood| first=June| authorlink=June Callwood| title=June Callwood's Story of the Queen's Visit| journal=Maclean's| volume=70| page=16| publisher=Maclean-Hunter| location=Toronto| date=December 1957| issn =0024-9262}}</ref> the pageantry was muted in comparison to what would be seen at a similar event in the United Kingdom. [[June Callwood]] said in her coverage of the tour for ''[[Maclean's]]'': \"The Queen's role in Canada, it appeared to some observers, hinged on calculated pageantry, just enough to warm the pride of Canadians who revere tradition and stateliness above state but not so much as to antagonize those who consider royalty a blindingly off-colour bauble in an age of lean fear.\"<ref>Callwood, June; ''Maclean's Magazine'': June Callwood's Story of the Queen's Visit; Vol. 70; December 1957; p. 16</ref> In Saskatchewan, the Queen inaugurated the natural gas-fired [[Queen Elizabeth Power Station]] on the [[South Saskatchewan River]].<ref name=\"Regina\"/>\n\nTwo years later, in 1959 the Queen returned and toured every province and territory of the country; Buckingham Palace officials and the Canadian government opted to dub this a \"royal tour\", as opposed to a \"royal visit\", to dispel any notion that the Queen was a visiting foreigner.<ref>{{Citation| last=Buckner| first=Phillip| publication-date=2005| contribution=The Last Great Royal Tour: Queen Elizabeth's 1959 Tour to Canada| editor-last=Buckner| editor-first=Phillip| title=Canada and the End of Empire| page=66| publication-place=Vancouver| publisher=UBC Press| isbn=0-7748-0915-9| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=27IggObUC9kC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=&f=false| accessdate=24 October 2009| ref=CITEREF_Buckner_2005}}</ref> Controversy arose in the run-up to the visit when [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] personality [[Joyce Davidson]], while being interviewed by [[Dave Garroway]] on [[NBC]]'s ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today Show]]'', said that as an \"average Canadian\" she was \"pretty indifferent\" to the Queen's forthcoming visit. Davidson was lambasted in the Canadian press and by many indignant Canadians for her comment.<ref name=\"Buckner 2005 85\">{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| p=85}}</ref> Regardless, the Queen toured the entire country, specifically directing that events she attended should be public, rather than closed luncheons or receptions;<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| p=75}}</ref> further, popular Canadian athletic stars were invited to royal events for the first time, so that during her tour the Queen met with [[Jean B\u00e9liveau]], [[Sam Etcheverry]], [[Maurice Richard]], [[Punch Imlach]], and [[Bud Grant]].<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| pp=78\u201379}}</ref>\n\nOne of the most important events of this trip was the official opening of the [[St. Lawrence Seaway]], along with President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], where, in [[Prescott, Ontario]], the Queen made her first [[Live television|live appearance]] on Canadian television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/special/royalvisit/royal-quiz-answers.htm| title=Department of Canadian Heritage: Test your royal skills| publisher=Pch.gc.ca| date=9 January 2009| accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> During this tour, the Queen paid numerous visits to Canadian industries,<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| p=68}}</ref> and again made a visit to the United States as Canada's head of state, stopping in Chicago and Washington, D.C., with Diefenbaker as her attending minister. The Prime Minister insisted that the Queen be accompanied at all times by a [[Cabinet of Canada|Canadian Cabinet]] minister, being determined to make it clear to Americans that the Queen was visiting the United States as the Canadian monarch, and that \"it is the Canadian embassy and not the British Embassy officials who are in charge\" of the Queen's itinerary.<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| p=69}}</ref> Her speeches in Chicago, written by her Canadian ministers, stressed steadily the fact that she had come to call as Queen of Canada.<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| p=76}}</ref> In this vein, the Queen hosted the return dinner for Eisenhower at the [[Embassy of Canada in Washington|Canadian Embassy in Washington]].<ref name=\"Buckner 2005 85\"/>\n[[File:O'Keefe Centre and royal motorcade 1959 Toronto Canada.jpg|thumb|Motorcade of The Queen at the intersection of [[Yonge Street|Yonge]] and [[Front Street (Toronto)|Front Street]], Toronto, during her 1959 royal tour.]]\nThe Queen returned to New Brunswick, at the end of her pan-Canada tour. The sovereign presided over a [[Queen's Scout]] recognition ceremony in Fredericton, visited the veterans' hospital in [[Lancaster, New Brunswick|Lancaster]], and undertook a walkabout in Victoria Park, Moncton. At [[Pointe-du-Chene, New Brunswick|Pointe-du-Ch\u00eane]], the royal couple visited briefly with the families of fishermen who had died the previous month in a storm off [[Escuminac, New Brunswick|Escuminac]], making a donation to the New Brunswick Fisherman's Disaster Fund that was established in honour of the deceased.<ref>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=3 Introduction]}}</ref>\n\nUnknown to all involved, the Queen was pregnant with [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|her third child]]. Prime Minister Diefenbaker urged her to cut the tour short after her disclosure to him at [[Kingston, Ontario]], but the Queen swore him to secrecy and continued the journey, leaving the public announcement of the upcoming birth until she returned to London.<ref name=\"Buckner 2005 85\"/>\n\nOnce the news was released, criticism of the tour that had simmered during its progress unleashed in full: Diefenbaker was blamed for pushing the Queen to carry on a grueling continent-wide trip, and the brevity of stops necessary to complete such a journey, combined with the formality and inaccessibility of events, led to calls for a cease to that format of royal tour. The ''Albertan'' stated: \"The fact is that royalty has no roots in Canada. And if roots must be put down, they certainly should be of a different kind than those which are historically proper for Britain.\"<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| pp=85\u201386}}</ref> Prior to the tour, the President of the [[Saint-Jean-Baptiste Society]], with the support of the Mayor of Quebec City, requested of the tour officials that, on the evening of [[National Holiday (Quebec)|Saint-Jean-Baptiste Day]], Her Majesty light the main [[bonfire]] in celebration. Though the Queen did lay a wreath at the [[James Wolfe#Legacy|James Wolfe Monument]] on the Plains of Abraham, the [[Canadian Secretary to the Queen|Queen's Canadian Secretary]] at the time, [[Howard Graham (Canadian Army officer)|Howard Graham]], left the bonfire off the itinerary, leading to complaints.<ref>{{Cite book| last=Buckner| first=Phillip| publication-date=2005| contribution=The Last Great Royal Tour: Queen Elizabeth's 1959 Tour to Canada| editor-last=Buckner| editor-first=Phillip| title=Canada and the End of Empire| page=76| publication-place=Vancouver| publisher=UBC Press| isbn=978-0-7748-0915-3| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=27IggObUC9kC&printsec=frontcover&q=| accessdate=24 October 2009| ref=harv| year=2005}}</ref>\n\nSuccesses were also noted, especially in the Crown's assistance in entrenching the newly emerging Canadian identity; the Queen ensured that the [[Canadian Red Ensign|Red Ensign]] (then Canada's ''de facto'' national flag) was flown on the [[HMY Britannia|royal yacht]], and she stood to attention for the duration of each playing of \"[[O Canada]]\", the country's then still unofficial national anthem, sometimes even joining in the singing.<ref>{{Harvnb| Buckner| 2005| 87}}</ref>\n\n====1960 to 2000====\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II, Royal tour of Canada 1983-Mar-09, UBC, Vancouver BC.jpg|thumb|upright|The Queen walks with [[John Clyne]], the Chancellor of the [[University of British Columbia]] during her 1983 royal tour of Canada.]]\nQueen Elizabeth II also celebrated the centennial of the [[Canadian Confederation|Confederation Conferences]] in Charlottetown on 6 October 1964.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |year=2010 |title=Confederation Centre of the Arts  |encyclopedia= The Canadian Encyclopedia |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/confederation-centre-of-the-arts-emc |language=en}}</ref> On 10 October, as she was touring the streets of [[Quebec City]], a turbulent riot occurred and opposed anti-monarchist [[Quebec nationalism|Quebec nationalists]] with the police. Since then, the event has been known as [[:fr:Samedi de la matraque|''Samedi de la matraque'']] (\"[[Baton (law enforcement)|Truncheon]] Saturday\").<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/quebec-and-the-royals-a-rocky-history-risks-another-bump/article585297/ |title=Quebec and the royals: A rocky history risks another bump |last=Blatchford |first=Andy |date=2 July 2011 |website=The Globe and Mail |access-date=2018-10-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, the Queen was in British Columbia to celebrate the centennial of the province's entry into Confederation.<ref name=BCArchives /> She toured Alberta and Saskatchewan in July 1973, to celebrate the centennial of the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], opening the new RCMP museum building in Regina,<ref name=Regina /> and in 1978, to open the [[1978 Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]] in Edmonton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://premier.alberta.ca/royalvisit/index_past_visits.cfm |last=Government of Alberta |title=Premier Ralph Klein > Royal Visit > Past Visits |publisher=Alberta Queen's Printer |accessdate=28 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422032851/http://premier.alberta.ca/royalvisit/index_past_visits.cfm |archivedate=22 April 2009 }}</ref> In Saskatchewan, she dedicated Queen Elizabeth Court, in front of Regina's city hall.<ref name=Regina />\n\n28 June \u2013 6 July 1976: Prince Charles, Prince Andrew and Prince Edward joined the Queen and Prince Philip for the 1976 Olympic Games in Montreal. Princess Anne was a member of the British equestrian team competing in the Olympics in Montreal. The royal family also stopped by Nova Scotia and New Brunswick during the visit. The Queen arrived at Fredericton, New Brunswick, on 15 July, after which she travelled to Woolastook Provincial Park to visit the [[Scouts Canada|Boy Scout]] Jamboree campsite, [[picnic]]ked with 3,500 schoolchildren, toured the [[Kings Landing Historical Settlement]],<ref>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=4 Woolastook and King's Landing]}}</ref> and attended a provincial dinner with fireworks following.<ref>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=4 First Stop \u2013 Fredericton]}}</ref> The Queen's second day in New Brunswick brought her to the [[Miramichi Valley|Miramichi]] area, where she attended a provincial lunch, visited [[Chatham, New Brunswick|Chatham]] and [[Newcastle, New Brunswick|Newcastle]], and toured the Burchill Laminating Plant in [[Nelson-Miramichi, New Brunswick|Nelson-Miramichi]].<ref name=StJ>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Image=1951-4-06&Panel=6&Years=1951 Saint John]}}</ref>\n\nThe Queen also journeyed to New Brunswick to celebrate the province's bicentennial in 1984, touching down, along with Prince Philip, at Moncton airport on 24 September, from where the royal party travelled to [[Shediac, New Brunswick|Shediac]], Sackville, [[Riverview, New Brunswick|Riverview]], and Fredericton over the course of three days. While at the Legislative Building, the Queen issued a [[Royal warrant (document)|Royal Warrant]] augmenting the [[Coat of arms of New Brunswick|province's coat of arms]] with its present crest, supporters, compartment, motto.<ref name=NBarch>{{Harvnb| Provincial Archives of New Brunswick| 2009| loc=[http://archives.gnb.ca/Exhibits/RoyalVisit/Default.aspx?culture=en-CA&Panel=5 Fredericton]}}</ref> She also, when in Fredericton, unveiled a plaque in Wilmot Park that honoured Edward Wilmot and recounted the dedication of the park by the Queen's great-grandfather.<ref name=NBarch />\n\nThe Queen opened the [[University of Northern British Columbia]] in 1994.<ref>[http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm British Columbia Archives: Chronology of Principal Royal Visits to British Columbia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228124243/http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm |date=28 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Philip, Duke of Edinburgh===\n[[File:QueenPhillip21976.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip at [[Scouts Canada]]'s Fourth Pentathlon Jamboree in 1976.]]\nPhilip, Duke of Edinburgh, [[Prince consort|consort]] to Queen Elizabeth II, participated in 28 official tours of Canada from 1951 to 2000, with his first in 1951, accompanying his spouse, Princess Elizabeth.<ref name=BCArchives/> During the same period of time, he has also taken 13 private working tours of the country, participating in events such as the [[Commonwealth Study Conference]], or the presentation of the [[Duke of Edinburgh Awards]]. Cumulatively, he has made more than 70 visits to Canada, including 19 royal tours with Queen Elizabeth II.<ref name=PPDE />\n\nThe Duke of Edinburgh visited the realm on two occasions to open two [[multi-sport event]], the [[1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]], and the [[1967 Pan American Games]]. The trip was one of many visits to Canada the Duke has made without the Queen. Other visits without the Queen occurred in 1960, 1962, 1978, 1979, 1980, and 1998, as he was chairing the [[Commonwealth Study Conference]], hosted in Canada during those years. He has also made 11 trips to Canada in relation to [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]].<ref name=PPDE>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-philip-s-love-affair-with-canada-1.1305785|title=Prince Philip's love affair with Canada|last=Davison|first=Janet|date=26 April 2013|accessdate=8 January 2018|work=CBCNews.ca|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> The Duke has also made several visits relating to his [[The Canadian Crown and the Canadian Armed Forces|role with the Armed Forces]]. He was appointed the [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of the [[Royal Canadian Regiment]] on 8 December 1953, he presented the 3rd Battalion's first colours on [[Parliament Hill]] in 1973.\n\n===Charles, Prince of Wales===\n[[Charles, Prince of Wales]] made 12 official tours of Canada from 1970 to 2000.<ref name=pastt/> His first official tour of Canada was in July 1970, touring Ottawa,<ref name=pastt/> prior to joining The Queen, the Duke of Edinburgh, and [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]]'s official tour of Manitoba, to celebrate of the centennial of Manitoba's entry into Confederation.<ref name=Mancent>{{cite web|url=http://lg.gov.mb.ca/history/house/second/bed.html| last=Office of the Lieutenant Governor of Manitoba| title=History > Government House > The Royal Bedroom| publisher=Queen's Printer for Manitoba| accessdate=2 July 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213160834/http://lg.gov.mb.ca/history/house/second/bed.html| archivedate=13 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe Prince and his first wife, the [[Diana, Princess of Wales|Princess of Wales]] attended the bicentennial in 1983 of the arrival of the first Empire Loyalists in Nova Scotia,<ref name=CBCVisits /> and also visited Newfoundland to mark the 400th anniversary of the island becoming a British colony.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://archives.cbc.ca/on_this_day/06/24/| title=On This Day > June 24, 1983 > Charles and Diana charm Newfoundlanders| date=23 June 1983| publisher=CBC| accessdate=12 July 2009}}</ref> In 1986, the Prince and Princess of Wales toured British Columbia, visiting Vancouver to open [[Expo 86]] (on 2 May 1986), as well as Victoria, Prince George, Kamloops and Nanaimo.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm| title=Chronology of Principal Royal Visits to British Columbia| accessdate=10 August 2014| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228124243/http://www.bcarchives.gov.bc.ca/exhibits/jubilee/chronvisit.htm| archivedate=28 February 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, the Prince and Princess of Wales toured Ontario; in Toronto, the princess was joined on board the [[HMY Britannia|Royal Yacht ''Britannia'']] by her two sons, Princes [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|William]] and [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex|Harry]], and caused some controversy{{cn|date=November 2019}} when she broke from established protocol by enthusiastically hugging the two boys after they ran up the gangplank to meet her. After performing official duties in the city, including a formal dinner at the Royal York hotel, the royal family then went on to visit [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]], [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]], Ottawa, and Niagara Falls, where the princes, as their great-great-great-grandfather had done, rode on ''Maid of the Mist''.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.niagaraparks.com/nfgg/famous_visitors.php| last=Niagara Parks| title=Niagara Falls & Great Gorge > More Niagara Falls and Great Gorge > Falls Facts > Famous Visitors| publisher=Queen's Printer for Ontario| accessdate=4 July 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120904074848/http://www.niagaraparks.com/nfgg/famous_visitors.php| archivedate=4 September 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Other royal family members===\n[[File:Royal motorcade (8075978363).jpg|thumb|Four members of the Royal Family\u2014The Queen; Prince Philip; [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|Prince Andrew]]; and [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Prince Edward]]\u2014at the opening of the [[1978 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]].]]\nQueen Elizabeth The Queen Mother, [[queen-consort]] to King George VI, and mother of Elizabeth II, has conducted nine official tours of Canada from 1951 to 2000.<ref name=pastt/> In 1967, she returned to Nova Scotia and Prince Edward Island to celebrate [[Canadian Centennial|Canada's centennial]] in 1967.<ref name=CBCVisits /> On a visit in 1985 to Toronto and Saskatchewan she noted, \"It is now some 46 years since I first came to this country with the King, in those anxious days shortly before the outbreak of the Second World War. I shall always look back upon that visit with feelings of affection and happiness. I think I lost my heart to Canada and Canadians, and my feelings have not changed with the passage of time.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/interactive/royalvisits/52.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106091148/http://www.cbc.ca/news/interactive/royalvisits/52.html |archivedate=6 November 2012 |title=Royal Visits to Canada |work=CBC News |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> In addition to her nine official tours, she conducted one private working tour in 1965, touring Toronto to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the [[The Toronto Scottish Regiment (Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother's Own)|Toronto Scottish Regiment]], a regiment where she holds the position of colonel-in-chief.<ref name=pastt/>\n\nElizabeth II's sister, [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon]] conducted seven official tours of Canada, as well as three private working tours of Canada from 1951 to 2000<ref name=pastt/> Two of her private working tours were conducted in relation to her role as patron of the [[Princess Margaret Cancer Centre|Princess Margaret Hospital]].<ref name=pastt/> Official tours include tours of Nova Scotia and British Columbia in 1958.<ref name=CBCVisits>{{Citation| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/interactive/royalvisits/51.html| title=Royal Visits to Canada| publisher=CBC| accessdate=10 July 2009}}</ref> In BC, the princess opened the new [[Pontoon bridge|floating bridge]] in Kelowna, with two plaques marking the ceremony.<ref name=Legacy /> She also presided over the celebrations of the 75th anniversary of Saskatchewan's entry into Confederation.<ref name=Regina />\n\n[[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy]] conducted three official tours of Canada, as well as four private working tours of the country from 1951 to 2000.<ref name=pastt/>  She toured Canada for its centenary in 1967, and also arrived in Halifax in 1973 to mark the bicentennial of the arrival of {{ship||Hector|ship|2}}, the first ship to land at Nova Scotia with Scottish colonists.<ref name=CBCVisits />\n\n[[Anne, Princess Royal]] conducted over six official tours of Canada, as well as seven private working tours from 1951 to 2000.<ref name=pastt/> Princess Anne presided over the 1970 celebrations of the centennial of Manitoba's entry into Confederation alongside her brother, the Prince of Wales.<ref name=Mancent />\n\n[[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]] conducted five official tours of Canada, as well as 10 private working tours from 1951 to 2000.<ref name=pastt/> His first official tour was conducted in 1976, whereas his first private working tour was conducted in the following year,<ref name=pastt/> after attending a semester of [[secondary school]] at [[Lakefield College School]], in [[Selwyn, Ontario|Selwyn]], Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thedukeofyork.org/about-the-duke/early-life-and-education/|title=Early Life & Education|publisher=The Duke of York|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> He undertook his first official tour of Nova Scotia in 1985, during which, amongst other activities, he visited Halifax and skippered [[Bluenose#Bluenose II|''Bluenose II'']].<ref name=CBCVisits />\n\nOther members of the royal family that conducted either official, or private working tours of Canada in the second half of the 20th century include [[Princess Marina of Greece and Denmark|Princess Marina, Duchess of Kent]], [[Princess Alice, Duchess of Gloucester]], [[Mary, Princess Royal and Countess of Harewood|Mary, Princess Royal]], [[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent]], [[Katharine, Duchess of Kent]], the [[Prince Michael of Kent|Prince]] and [[Princess Michael of Kent]], and the [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Earl]] and [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|Countess of Wessex]].<ref name=pastt/>\n\n==21st century==\n{{main|List of royal tours of Canada (21st century)}}\n===Elizabeth II===\n[[File:Royal Visit Toronto 2010 6.JPG|thumb|The Queen in [[Queen's Park (Toronto)|Queen's Park]], Toronto, during her 2010 royal tour.]]\nElizabeth II has conducted three official tours of Canada in the 21st century. In 2002, Elizabeth II toured the Canadian provinces of British Columbia, New Brunswick, Manitoba, Ontario, Quebec, and the territory of Nunavut, for her [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Golden Jubilee]].\n\nIn 2005, the Queen was in Alberta again to mark the province's 100th anniversary of entry into Confederation, where she attended, along with an audience of 25,000, a kick-off concert at [[Commonwealth Stadium (Edmonton)|Commonwealth Stadium]], re-designated the Provincial Museum of Alberta as the [[Royal Alberta Museum]], and addressed the Legislative Assembly, becoming the first reigning monarch to do so.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.albertacentennial.ca/events/kickoff.html| last=Government of Alberta| title=Alberta Centennial Home > Official Events > Celebrate Alberta Kick-Off Party| publisher=Alberta Queen's Printer| accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref> The [[Education in Alberta|Alberta Ministry of Learning]] encouraged teachers to focus education on the monarchy and to organize field trips for their students to see the Queen and her consort, or to watch the events on television.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.education.gov.ab.ca/centennial/RoyalVisit/bulletin.asp| last=Government of Alberta| title=Education Home > Centennial Projects > Alberta students encouraged to join the festivities the Royal Visit 2005| publisher=Alberta Queen's Printer| accessdate=28 June 2009}}</ref> In Saskatchewan, the Queen presided over the main events for the centennial of Saskatchewan's creation, as well as touring the [[Canadian Light Source Synchrotron]] and the University of Saskatchewan,<ref>{{cite news| title=Royal couple touches down in Saskatchewan| publisher=CTV| date=18 May 2005| url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1116361103300_111770303/?hub=TopStories| accessdate=30 June 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051001053156/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1116361103300_111770303/?hub=TopStories| archivedate=1 October 2005| df=dmy-all}}</ref> where, in the Diefenbaker Canada Centre, is stored correspondence between former Prime Minister [[John Diefenbaker]] and the Queen.\n\nIn 2010, Elizabeth II visited Ontario and Manitoba as part of the 2010 royal tour of Canada. Arriving in Ottawa 30 June 2010, she toured the Canadian Museum of Nature and met with Prime Minister Stephen Harper. The following day, the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh joined the festivities for Canada Day on Parliament Hill. The Royal Tour of Canada ended as the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh departed for New York on 6 July 2010, following visits to Toronto and Waterloo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/the-royal-visit-of-2010-1.892553|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]|title=The Royal Visit of 2010|date=25 June 2010|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Charles, Prince of Wales===\n[[File:Royal Tour 2014 (14040125577).jpg|thumb|left|[[Charles, Prince of Wales]] visiting [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]] during his 2014 royal tour of Canada.]]\nSince 2001, the Prince of Wales has conducted five official tours in Canada, in April 2001, November 2009, May 2012, May 2014, and June\u2013July 2017. He was accompanied by his spouse, [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] on the latter four tours.<ref name=pastt/>\n\nIn 2001 he toured through Ottawa, where his interactions with the crowds kept Prime Minister [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] waiting for twenty minutes. He also toured Regina, Moose Jaw, [[Assiniboia, Saskatchewan|Assiniboia]], Saskatoon, [[Whitehorse, Yukon|Whitehorse]], and [[Mayo, Yukon|Mayo]]. In Saskatchewan, he turned the sod for the Prince of Wales Cultural and Recreation Centre in Assiniboia and dedicated the Anniversary Arch outside Regina's YMCA.<ref name=Regina />\n\nOn 14 December, it was announced that Camilla and Charles would visit several provinces in Canada, including New Brunswick, Ontario, and Saskatchewan. This trip is in honour of the Queen's Diamond Jubilee in February 2012. In 2017, the Prince of Wales and Duchess of Cornwall were in Canada from 29 June to 1 July for [[Canada Day]] celebration and for the country's sesquicentennial celebrations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2017/04/18/prince-charles-camilla-to-visit-for-canada-150-celebration.html|title=Prince Charles, Camilla to visit for Canada 150 celebration|date=18 April 2017|accessdate=20 May 2017|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\n===William, Duke of Cambridge===\n[[File:Canada Ottawa William Kate 2011 (2).jpg|thumb|[[William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] and the [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Duchess of Cambridge]] at an inspection for the [[Governor General's Foot Guards]] during their [[2011 royal tour of Canada]].]]\n[[William, Duke of Cambridge]] has conducted two official tours in Canada in the 21st century. The [[2011 royal tour of Canada]] was the first time Prince William, and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]], visited Canada as the Duke and Duchess of Cambridge. The tour saw the newlywed couple tour Ottawa, Montreal, Quebec City, Charlottetown, [[Summerside, Prince Edward Island|Summerside]], [[Yellowknife]], Calgary, as well as the fire-ravaged community of [[Slave Lake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/services/past-royal-tours/2011-royal-tour-duke-duchess-cambridge.html|title=2011 Royal Tour of Canada by Their Royal Highnesses The Duke and Duchess of Cambridge|publisher=Government of Canada|date=4 August 2017|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref> It was the first such tour undertaken by the Duke and Duchess since their marriage two months prior.<ref>{{cite press release |title=HRH Prince William of Wales and Miss Catherine Middleton to undertake a Royal tour of Canada |url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/media/press-releases/hrh-prince-william-of-wales-and-miss-catherine-middleton-undertake-royal-tour |publisher=Clarence House |via=www.princeofwales.gov.uk |date=16 February 2011 |access-date=30 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=cbc-tour-it-an>{{cite news| last=Yelaja| first=Prithi| title=William and Kate's royal tour itinerary released| publisher=CBC| date=21 June 2011| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/williamandkate/story/2011/06/21/royal-tour.html| accessdate=2 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the Duke and Duchess of Cambridge, along with their children, [[Prince George of Cambridge]], and [[Princess Charlotte of Cambridge]], conducted an official tour of British Columbia and [[Yukon]], visiting Victoria, Vancouver, [[Bella Bella, British Columbia|Bella Bella]], [[Kelowna]], Whitehorse, [[Carcross]], and [[Haida Gwaii]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/services/past-royal-tours/2016-royal-tour-duke-duchess-cambridge.html|title=The 2016 Royal Tour of The Duke and Duchess of Cambridge|publisher=Government of Canada|date=24 October 2018|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Anne, Princess Royal===\nAnne, Princess Royal has conducted seven private working tours, and one official working tour of Canada since 2001. She conducted private working tours in August\u2013September 2003, June 2004, June 2007, February 2010, April 2010, October 2013, and February 2015; and one official tour in November 2014.<ref name=pastt/>\n\nThe Princess Royal's private tours to Canada are typically conducted in association with her honorary role as the colonel in chief of six units in the Canadian Forces. In April 2010, she visited St. John's to celebrate the anniversary of the [[Royal Newfoundland Regiment]], as well as Regina, to celebrate its centennial.<ref name=Regina /> The Princess Royal also a visit to Barrie on 22 October 2013 to commemorate the opening of park with military significance and to visit the [[Grey and Simcoe Foresters]], for which she their current colonel-in-chief.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.simcoe.com/news-story/4168372-princess-anne-s-royal-visit-commemorated-in-new-barrie-park/ |title=Princess Anne's royal visit commemorated in new Barrie park |work=simcoe.com |date=22 October 2013 |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Princess Royal and her husband [[Vice admiral (Royal Navy)|Vice-Admiral]] [[Tim Laurence]] arrived in Canada on 10 November 2014 in Ottawa for a two-day official tour, with focus on [[Remembrance Day]] ceremonies in Ottawa, such as the re-dedication of the [[National War Memorial (Canada)|National War Memorial]].<ref name=pastt/>\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/princess-anne-s-ottawa-tour-will-honour-everyday-heroes-1.2826736 |title=Princess Anne's Ottawa tour will honour 'everyday heroes' |work=CBC News |date=7 November 2014 |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Edward, Earl of Wessex===\n[[File:Wessex-MLC.jpg|thumb|[[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]] with members of the [[Monarchist League of Canada]] in Toronto, 2005.]]\nSince 2001, [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]] has conducted 17 private working tours in Canada. His first visit to Canada in the 21st century occurred in October 2001, with his latest tour occurring in October\u2013November 2015. Most of these visits were conducted for ceremonies relating to the [[Duke of Edinburgh Award]].<ref name=pastt/>\n\nIn 2003, Prince Edward opened two parks in Saskatchewan, the Prince Edward Park in Melfort and the Queen's Golden Jubilee Rose Garden in Moose Jaw.<ref name=Regina /> In 2005, the Earl and Countess of Wessex toured Ontario; the Earl visited Peterborough, [[Prince Edward County, Ontario|Prince Edward County]], and Toronto, while his spouse, [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex]], went to [[Welland, Ontario|Welland]] to be installed as Colonel-in-Chief of [[the Lincoln and Welland Regiment]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.heritagefdn.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/nts_1_8218_1.html| publisher=Ontario Heritage Trust| title=HRH The Earl of Wessex unveils provincial plaque celebrating the Toronto-Dominion Centre| date=14 August 2006| accessdate=15 September 2007| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927091304/http://www.heritagefdn.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/nts_1_8218_1.html| archivedate=27 September 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Countess has accompanied her husband, Prince Edward on a number of tours to Canada. Their tour of Canada in 2002 marked the Countess' first tour outside of the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite press release| title=Their Royal Highnesses The Earl and Countess of Wessex to Visit the Province| publisher=Queen's Printer for Prince Edward Island| date=4 May 2000| url=http://www.gov.pe.ca/news/getrelease.php3?number=1591| accessdate=11 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Burke |first=Scott |author2=Aimers, John |title=Wessexs' Tour a Triumph |journal=Canadian Monarchist News |publisher=Monarchist League of Canada |location=Toronto |year=2001 |url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2001/wessex.htm |accessdate=11 July 2009 |ref=harv |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708015252/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2001/wessex.htm |archivedate=8 July 2009 }}</ref> In 2009, Countess of Wessex opened the Air Force Museum of Alberta in Calgary, spending some hours visiting its displays.<ref>{{Cite book| last=Stepaniuk| first=Violette| title=New museum in Calgary tells story of Canada\u2019s Air Force| publisher=Skytech Dynamics Corporation| date=2 July 2009| url=http://www.aviation.ca/content/view/7566/117/| accessdate=3 July 2009}}</ref> The Countess of Wessex has also conducted private working tours of her own, as was the case in November 2015.<ref name=pastt/>\n\n===Other royal family members===\n[[File:Prince Philip as Colonel-in-Chief of the Royal Canadian Regiment.jpg|thumb|Prince Philip with members of [[The Royal Canadian Regiment]] in 2013.]]\nIn the 21st century, Prince Philip has conducted three official tours alongside Queen Elizabeth, in October 2002, May 2005, and June 2010. In addition to official tours, he has conducted three private working tours, in October 2001, April 2004, and April 2013.<ref name=pastt/> In 2001, he visited Toronto in order to present the Duke of Edinburgh Award to recipients, and participate in activities relating to the [[World Wildlife Foundation]].<ref name=pastt/> In April 2013, [[David Johnston]], the Governor General of Canada, presented Philip with the [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|Order of Military Merit]], and inducted him as a Companion of the [[Order of Canada]].<ref name=pastt/> On the 27 April 2013, Prince Philip, the Colonel-in-Chief of the Royal Canadian Regiment, visited Toronto in order to present the 3rd battalion its second colours.<ref name=PPDE/>\n\nThe Prince Andrew, Duke of York has conducted 17 of private working tours in Canada since 2001. His first tour in the 21st century was in January 2001, whereas his latest tour in Canada occurred in May 2019.<ref name=pastt/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thechronicleherald.ca/opinion/columnists/john-demont-prince-andrew-honours-halifaxs-princess-louise-fusiliers-315122/|title=Prince Andrew honours Halifax\u2019s Princess Louise Fusiliers|last=DeMont|first=Josh|publisher=SaltWire Network|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=24 May 2019|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> In 2003, he came twice, at one point going into the field in full [[CADPAT|combat uniform]] to observe tactical exercises and address the troops of the [[Queen's York Rangers (1st American Regiment) (RCAC)|Queen's York Rangers]], of which he is colonel-in-chief.<ref>{{cite journal| last=Roberts| first=Stephen| title=HRH Duke of York visits the Monarchist League| journal=Canadian Monarchist News| volume=7| issue=4| page=4| publisher=Monarchist League of Canada| location=Toronto| year=2003| url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmnews/CMN_summer_2003_Update-2.pdf| accessdate=4 July 2009| ref=harv|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071006170218/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmnews/CMN_summer_2003_Update-2.pdf| archivedate = 6 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nPrincess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy, has conducted two private working tours of Canada, in April 2010, and October 2012. During her 2010, she visited Toronto and Victoria to attend the 150th anniversary ceremonies for the establishment of [[The Queen's Own Rifles of Canada]], of which she is the colonel-in-chief.<ref name=pastt/> In 2012, she returned to Victoria to attend the 100th anniversary for [[The Canadian Scottish Regiment (Princess Mary's)]].<ref name=pastt/>\n\nSince 2001, Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex has visited Canada on two private working tours, on the 26 June 2007, and from September\u2013October 2008. Both visits were conducted for military exercises at [[CFB Suffield]] in Alberta.<ref name=pastt/> In addition to private working tours, Harry has made informal visits to the country, such as the opening for the [[2017 Invictus Games]] in Toronto. It was during these games that Prince Harry, and his future spouse, [[Meghan, Duchess of Sussex]] made their first public appearance together.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/invictus-games/2017/09/25/prince-harry-meghan-markle-make-first-public-appearance-together-at-invictus-games.html|title=Prince Harry, Meghan Markle make first public appearance together at Invictus Games|publisher=Torstar Corporation|work=The Toronto Star|last=Loriggio|first=Paolo|accessdate=23 January 2019|date=25 September 2017}}</ref> Prior to their first public appearance, reports had surfaced in 2016 that Harry visited Meghan at her home in Toronto; who was residing in the city from 2011 to 2017 in order to film the television series ''[[Suits (U.S. TV series)|Suits]]''.<ref name=Megh>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2017/11/27/how-meghan-markle-and-prince-harry-fell-in-love-in-toronto-the-timeline-of-a-royal-romance.html|title=How Meghan Markle and Prince Harry fell in love in Toronto: The timeline of a royal romance|publisher=Torstar Corporation|work=The Toronto Star|accessdate=23 January 2019|date=27 November 2017|last=Jones|first=Alexandra}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of royal tours of Canada (18th\u201320th centuries)]]\n*[[List of royal tours of Canada (21st century)]]\n*[[List of royal visits to Hamilton, Ontario]]\n*[[List of royal visits to London, Ontario]]\n*[[Royal visits to Saskatchewan]]\n*[[Royal and viceroyal transport in Canada]]\n**[[Royal Canadian Air Force VIP aircraft]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book| last=Bousfield| first=Arthur|author2=Toffoli, Garry|  title=Royal Spring: The Royal Tour of 1939 and the Queen Mother in Canada| publisher=Dundurn Press| year=1989| location=Toronto| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Go5p_CN8UQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_v2_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=&f=false| isbn=1-55002-065-X}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bousfuield|first1=Arthur|first2=Garry|last2=Toffoli|title=Royal Tours 1786-2010: Home to Canada|publisher=Dundurn Press|isbn=1-4597-1165-3 |year=2010|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last=Cartwright| first=Thelma|author2=Clay, John| author3=Hall, Edna|  title=The Silver Jubilee: Royal Visit to Canada| publisher=Deneau & Greenburg| year=1977| location=Ottawa| isbn=0-88879-002-3}}\n*{{Cite book| last=Fleming| first=Rae| title=The Royal Tour of Canada: The 1939 Visit of King George VI and Queen Elizabeth| publisher=Lynx Images| year=2002| isbn=1-894073-37-1| url=https://archive.org/details/royaltourofcanad0000flem}}\n*{{Cite book| last=Lanctot| first=Gustave| authorlink=Gustave Lanctot| title=The Royal Tour of King George VI and Queen Elizabeth in Canada and the United States of America 1939| publisher=E.P. Taylor Foundation| year=1964| location=Toronto}}\n*{{Cite book| last=MacDonnell| first=Tom| title=Daylight Upon Magic: The Royal Tour of Canada, 1939| publisher=Macmillan| year=1989| location=Toronto| isbn=0-7715-9229-9}}\n*{{Cite book| last=Radforth| first=Ian| title=Royal Spectacle: The 1860 Visit of the Prince of Wales to Canada and the United States| publisher=University of Toronto Press| year=2005| location=Toronto| isbn=0-8020-8699-3}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Royal visits by the Monarchy of the Commonwealth to Canada|Royal tours of Canada}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.canada.ca/en/services/culture/canadian-identity-society/monarchy-crown/royal-tours.html}} - Government of Canada\n* [https://www.nfb.ca/subjects/politics-and-government-canada/royal-family/ Royal Family] - National Film Board of Canada\n* [https://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/society/the-monarchy/ The Monarchy] - CBC Digital Archive\n\n{{Canadian monarchy}}\n{{Elizabeth II}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Royal Tours Of Canada}}\n[[Category:Elizabeth II]]\n[[Category:Monarchy in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal tours of Canada| ]]\n", "name_user": "Leventio", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrincess as the viceregal consort (1878\u20131883):ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_tours_of_Canada_by_the_Canadian_Royal_Family"}
{"title_page": "1862 Montgomeryshire by-election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\nThe 1862 Montgomery by-election was a parliamentary by-election held on 14 July 1862 for the British House of Commons constituency of Montgomeryshire, known at the time as Montgomery.\n\n== Cause ==\nThe seat had become vacant when the constituency's Member of Parliament (MP), Herbert Williams-Wynn died.\n\n== Candidates ==\nTwo candidates were nominated. \n\n- [[Charles Williams-Wynn (1822-1896)|Charles Williams-Wynn]] was the son of [[Charles Williams-Wynn (1775\u20131850)|Charles Wiliams-Wynn]], who was M.P. for Montgomeryshire 1796\u20131850, and was a [[Deputy Lieutenant]] and [[Justice of the Peace|J.P.]] for Montgomeryshire, and captain in the Montgomery Yeomanry Cavalry.<ref name=Debrett>[https://archive.org/stream/debrettshouseo1870londuoft#page/294/mode/2up Debretts House of Commons and the Judicial Bench 1870]</ref> He was the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] candidate.\n\n- [[Sudeley Hanbury-Tracy, 3rd Baron Sudeley|Sudeley Hanbury-Tracy]] was a British [[colliery]] owner. He succeeded his father as [[Baron Sudeley]] in February 1863, aged 25.<ref name=thepeerage.com>[http://thepeerage.com/p3092.htm#i30916 thepeerage.com Sudeley Charles George Hanbury-Tracy, 3rd Baron Sudeley]</ref> He also succeeded his father as [[Lord-Lieutenant of Montgomeryshire]], a post he held until his death aged 40. He was the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] candidate.\n\n==Result==\n{{Election box begin|title=Montgomery by-election, 1862<ref name=\"craig1832\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Craig|editor1-first=F. W. S.|editor-link=F. W. S. Craig|title=British Parliamentary Election Results 1832-1885|date=1977|publisher=Macmillan Press|location=London|isbn=978-1-349-02349-3|edition=1st|type=e-book}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Charles Williams-Wynn (1822-1896)|Charles Williams-Wynn]]\n  |votes      = 1,269\n  |percentage = 57.0\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Sudeley Hanbury-Tracy, 3rd Baron Sudeley|Sudeley Hanbury-Tracy]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Montgomeryshire|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000052/18620709/043/0008|accessdate=6 March 2018|work=[[Derby Mercury]]|date=9 July 1862|page=8|via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n  |votes      = 959\n  |percentage = 43.0\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 310\n  |percentage = 13.9\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      = 2,228\n  |percentage = 83.3\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box registered electors| \n  |reg. electors = 2,675\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n  |winner     = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |swing      =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Montgomeryshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Montgomeryshire constituency]]\n* [[List of United Kingdom by-elections (1857\u20131868)|List of United Kingdom by-elections]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results 1832-1885'' (2nd edition, Aldershot: Parliamentary Research Services, 1989)\n\n{{United Kingdom by-elections}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of United Kingdom by-elections (1857-1868)}}\n[[Category:1862 elections in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\nThe 1862 Montgomery by-election was a parliamentary by-election held on 14 July 1862 for the British House of Commons constituency of Montgomeryshire, known at the time as Montgomery.\n\n== Cause ==\nThe seat had become vacant when the constituency's Member of Parliament (MP), Herbert Williams-Wynn died.\n\n== Candidates ==\nTwo candidates were nominated. \n\n- [[Charles Williams-Wynn (1822-1896)|Charles Williams-Wynn]] was the son of [[Charles Williams-Wynn (1775\u20131850)|Charles Wiliams-Wynn]], who was M.P. for Montgomeryshire 1796\u20131850, and was a [[Deputy Lieutenant]] and [[Justice of the Peace|J.P.]] for Montgomeryshire, and captain in the Montgomery Yeomanry Cavalry.<ref name=Debrett>[https://archive.org/stream/debrettshouseo1870londuoft#page/294/mode/2up Debretts House of Commons and the Judicial Bench 1870]</ref> He was the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] candidate.\n\n- [[Sudeley Hanbury-Tracy, 3rd Baron Sudeley|Sudeley Hanbury-Tracy]] was a British [[colliery]] owner. He succeeded his father as [[Baron Sudeley]] in February 1863, aged 25.<ref name=thepeerage.com>[http://thepeerage.com/p3092.htm#i30916 thepeerage.com Sudeley Charles George Hanbury-Tracy, 3rd Baron Sudeley]</ref> He also succeeded his father as [[Lord-Lieutenant of Montgomeryshire]], a post he held until his death aged 40. He was the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] candidate.\n\n==Result==\n{{Election box begin|title=Montgomery by-election, 1862<ref name=\"craig1832\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Craig|editor1-first=F. W. S.|editor-link=F. W. S. Craig|title=British Parliamentary Election Results 1832-1885|date=1977|publisher=Macmillan Press|location=London|isbn=978-1-349-02349-3|edition=1st|type=e-book}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Charles Williams-Wynn (1822-1896)|Charles Williams-Wynn]]\n  |votes = 1,269\n  |percentage = 57.0\n  |change = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Sudeley Hanbury-Tracy, 3rd Baron Sudeley|Sudeley Hanbury-Tracy]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Montgomeryshire|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000052/18620709/043/0008|accessdate=6 March 2018|work=[[Derby Mercury]]|date=9 July 1862|page=8|via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n  |votes = 959\n  |percentage = 43.0\n  |change = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n |votes = 310\n |percentage = 13.9\n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n |votes = 2,228\n |percentage = 83.3\n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box registered electors| \n |reg. electors = 2,675\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n  |winner    = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |swing     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Montgomeryshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Montgomeryshire constituency]]\n* [[List of United Kingdom by-elections (1857\u20131868)|List of United Kingdom by-elections]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results 1832-1885'' (2nd edition, Aldershot: Parliamentary Research Services, 1989)\n\n{{United Kingdom by-elections}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of United Kingdom by-elections (1857-1868)}}\n[[Category:1862 elections in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Benawu2", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1862_Montgomeryshire_by-election"}
{"title_page": "Wild Thoughts", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 single by DJ Khaled}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Wild Thoughts\n| cover      = Wild Thoughts cover.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[DJ Khaled]] featuring [[Rihanna]] and [[Bryson Tiller]]\n| album      = [[Grateful (DJ Khaled album)|Grateful]]\n| released   = June 16, 2017\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Music download|digital download]]}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Latin pop]]|[[Hip Hop|Hip Hop]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=24}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[We the Best Music Group|We the Best]]|[[Epic Records|Epic]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[PartyNextDoor|Jahron Braithwaite]]|[[DJ Khaled|Khaled Khaled]]|[[Rihanna|Robyn Fenty]]|[[Bryson Tiller]]|[[Jerry Duplessis]]|[[Wyclef Jean]]|David McRae|Marvin Moore-Hough|[[Carlos Santana]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|DJ Khaled|DJ Nasty|PartyNextDoor|Carlos Santana}}\n| chronology = [[DJ Khaled]]\n| prev_title = [[I'm the One (DJ Khaled song)|I'm the One]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = [[Top Off]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Rihanna]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[Selfish (Future song)|Selfish]]\n | prev_year  = 2017\n | title      = Wild Thoughts\n | year       = 2017\n | next_title = [[Loyalty (Kendrick Lamar song)|Loyalty]]\n | next_year  = 2017\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Bryson Tiller]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[Somethin Tells Me]]\n | prev_year  = 2017\n | title      = Wild Thoughts\n | year       = 2017\n | next_title = [[Run Me Dry]]\n | next_year  = 2017\n}}{{External music video|{{YouTube|fyaI4-5849w|\"Wild Thoughts\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Wild Thoughts'''\" is a song by American musician [[DJ Khaled]] featuring Barbadian singer [[Rihanna]] and American singer [[Bryson Tiller]]. It was released on June 16, 2017, by [[We the Best Music Group|We the Best]] and [[Epic Records]] as the third single from Khaled's tenth studio album, ''[[Grateful (DJ Khaled album)|Grateful]]'' (2017).<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/music/2017/06/15/dj-khaled-rihanna-collaboration-wild-thoughts/|title=DJ Khaled reveals details of 'humongous' Rihanna collab, 'Wild Thoughts'|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Eric|last=Renner Brown|date=June 15, 2017|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> Canadian singer [[PartyNextDoor]] assisted the artists in writing the song, with production handled by Khaled. A mid-tempo pop song, \"Wild Thoughts\" consists of Latin percussion, [[acoustic guitar]] lines and riffs that interpolate the 1999 hit single \"[[Maria Maria]]\" by [[Santana (band)|Santana]]. Lyrically, the song praises a lover who inspires sexual thoughts.\n\nCommercially, the song reached number one in the United Kingdom, marking Khaled's second and Rihanna's ninth number one. The song also saw chart success in Australia and Canada, where it peaked at number two. The song peaked at number two on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming Rihanna's 31st top-ten song, Khaled's third, and Tiller's first.\n\nThe [[music video]] for the song was directed by [[Colin Tilley]] and was shot in the [[Little Haiti]] neighborhood of [[Miami, Florida]]. The music video was nominated in three categories at the [[MTV Video Music Award]]s for [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Collaboration|Best Collaboration]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]].\n\n==Background and composition==\nBryson Tiller and Khaled had first collaborated on the track \"Ima Be Alright\" for Khaled's ninth studio album ''[[Major Key (album)|Major Key]]'' (2016).<ref>{{cite web|title=DJ Khaled Details Major Key Tracklist Featuring Kanye, Jay Z, Drake, Future, Kendrick Lamar, More|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/66348-dj-khaled-details-new-album-major-key-featuring-kanye-jay-z-drake-future-kendrick-lamar-more/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=June 15, 2017|date=July 23, 2016}}</ref> During ''Grateful''{{'}}s recording, Khaled invited Tiller to his house for dinner. During dinner, Khaled played the initial demo of \"Wild Thoughts\" to Tiller and asked him if he could do something with the song. Tiller returned home and recorded his verse and sent it to Khaled who used it on the final recording.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/art-books-music/a10252969/bryson-tiller-interview/|title=Bryson Tiller on How His Collab with Rihanna and DJ Khaled Came to Life|date=3 July 2017|website=harpersbazaar.com}}</ref> While talking about collaborating with Rihanna for the first time in an interview with ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', Khaled said; \"Seven, eight years I've been trying to do this. I always put the kites out there that I wanted to work with her. But at the same time, while I was putting the kites out there, I was always getting the right record ready. You've gotta start with the right energy to see if something comes back that\u2019s possible.\"<ref name=\"ew\" />\n\n\"Wild Thoughts\" is a mid-tempo [[Pop rock]] song with Latin percussion and \"slinky acoustic guitar lines.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radio.com/2017/06/16/dj-khaled-wild-thoughts-rihanna-bryson-tiller/|title=DJ Khaled Drops 'Wild Thoughts' Video Featuring Rihanna & Bryson Tiller|website=radio.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616142027/http://radio.com/2017/06/16/dj-khaled-wild-thoughts-rihanna-bryson-tiller/|archivedate=June 16, 2017|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cirisano|first=Tatiana|title=Product G&B Talk 'Maria Maria' and 'Wild Thoughts': Interview|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7849262/product-gb-maria-maria-wild-thoughts-sample-interview|accessdate=May 8, 2018|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=June 29, 2017}}</ref> The song heavily samples the guitar riff from Santana's 1999 \"Maria Maria\", which features [[The Product G&B]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4820878/5-songs-you-need-to-listen-to-this-week-16/|title=5 Songs You Need to Listen to This Week|first=Raisa|last=Bruner|website=Time}}</ref> Written in the key of C minor, it has a [[tempo]] of 96-100 beats per minute in [[Duple and quadruple meter|simple quadruple ({{Time signature|4|4}}) time]]. The song follows a chord progression of Cm\u2013Fm\u2013Cm, and Rihanna's and Tiller's vocals spanning from C<sub>4</sub> to G<sub>5</sub>.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0175049|title=DJ Khaled Feat. Rihanna & Bryson Tiller \"Wild Thoughts\" Sheet Music in C Minor (transposable) \u2013 Download & Print|first=Khaled, Khaled|last=M|website=Musicnotes.com}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' editor Andrew Unterberger noted the \"Wild Thoughts\" featured the same groove and riff as \"Maria Maria\" and even featured Wyclef Jean's \"murmuring\" who supplied the original songs ad-libs.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7833809/santana-maria-maria-rob-thomas-smooth-dj-khaled-rihanna-wild-thoughts|title=It's Time for 'Maria Maria' to Replace 'Smooth' As the Santana Meme Song |work=Billboard |date=June 16, 2017|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref> Vanessa Okoth-Obbo of ''Pitchfork'' described the track as relying heavily on a \"Latin rock aesthetic\", with lyrics that hear Rihanna and Tiller croon praise lovers who inspire wild thoughts. Okoth-Obbo described the lyrics as straddling the line between \"innuendos and carnal statements\", whilst also noting the singers\u2019 vocal performances as being restrained and controlled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/dj-khaled-wild-thoughts/|title=\"Wild Thoughts\" Review \u2013 Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com}}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n[[File:Carlos Santana 2.jpg|thumb|right|\"Wild Thoughts\" heavily samples \"[[Maria Maria]]\" performed by Santana. Guitarist Carlos Santana praised the use of the song]]\nOn June 9, 2017, Khaled released the album's track listing, which also included \"Wild Thoughts\".<ref name=\"xxl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/06/dj-khaled-grateful-album-tracklist/|title=DJ Khaled Reveals Star-Studded \u2018Grateful\u2019 Album Tracklist|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|date=June 9, 2017|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref> The song's artwork, which features Khaled's son Asahd, was revealed via Rihanna's [[Instagram]] account on June 15, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7833688/dj-khaled-rihanna-bryson-tiller-wild-thoughts-grateful|title=DJ Khaled's 'Wild Thoughts' Collaboration With Rihanna and Bryson Tiller Will Drop Tomorrow|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=June 15, 2017|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref> \"Wild Thoughts\" was released on June 16, 2017, as the album's third single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/dj-khaled-rihanna-and-bryson-tillers-wild-thoughts-dropping-tomorrow-news.33810.html|title=DJ Khaled, Rihanna, & Bryson Tiller's \"Wild Thoughts\" Dropping Tomorrow|work=HotNewHipHop|date=June 15, 2017|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref> ''Grateful'' was released on June 23, 2017.<ref name=\"xxl\" />\n\nPeter A. Berry from ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' wrote; \"If all goes according to plan, it should go follow in the footsteps of \"[[I'm the One (DJ Khaled song)|I'm the One]]\" and reach platinum status in the very near future.\"<ref name=\"xxl2\" /> Janelle Okwode of ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' said that the song \"is an instant contender for song of the summer\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vogue.com/article/rihanna-dj-khaled-wild-thoughts-video-fashion-fantasy|title=Of Course DJ Khaled and Rihanna\u2019s New Video is a Wild Fashion Fantasy|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|date=June 16, 2017|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref> Raisa Bruner from ''Time'' magazine listed the song on her list of five songs that should be heard. Bruner praised the song calling it an \"irresistible, Latin-inflected summer jam with some smooth verses courtesy of the addition of Bryson Tiller.\" Bruner continued to state that the song was truly Rihanna's  \"but we all know this is Rihanna's show.\"<ref name=\"auto\" /> In a second and more in-depth review Burner stated:\n\n{{cquote|\"Wild Thoughts\" kicks off with a bang and that instantly-recognizable Santana guitar melody, before segueing into Rihanna's low, compelling vocals and Tiller's verses. It feels like a spiritual successor to last year's hits \"Work\" and \"One Dance\" \u2014 but swapping those songs' dancehall vibes for Santana's guitar. Either way, it's an intoxicating bop guaranteed to heat things up.}}\n\n[[Uproxx]]'s Corbin Reiff wrote that Rihanna \"brings some serious heat\", while Tiller \"rolls through in the middle to reprise his verse, and brings some serious R&B vibes with along him\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/realtalk/dj-khaled-and-rihanna-wild-thoughts/|title=DJ Khaled And Rihanna Keep Things Smooth In Their Spanish-Flavored \u2018Wild Thoughts\u2019 Video|work=[[Uproxx]]|date=June 16, 2017|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref>\nMatt Miller of ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' praised Rihanna's saying that she \"completely commands the song, the power of her voice, her presence takes the entire thing over.\" Miller was less favourable about Tiller and the Santana sample calling their inclusion forgettable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/music/news/a55683/dj-khaled-rihanna-wild-thoughts-video/|title=It Was Nice of Rihanna to Let DJ Khaled Put His Name on This Song|work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|date=June 16, 2017|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref>\n''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' editor Andrew Unterberger wrote that this is \"practically a cover with different lyrics\" of \"Maria Maria\", saying that it is \"not a perfect song, but it's a super-fun resurrection of the now 18-year-old single\".<ref name=\"auto1\" /> Elias Leight from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called it \"another warm-weather-friendly single\" by Khaled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-dj-khaled-rihanna-in-sultry-wild-thoughts-video-w488291|title=See DJ Khaled, Rihanna, Bryson Tiller in Sultry 'Wild Thoughts' Video|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=June 16, 2017|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Carlos Santana's response===\n[[Carlos Santana]] who originally wrote \"Maria Maria\", the song which is sampled on \"Wild Thoughts\", praised Khaled's, Rihanna's and Tiller's take on the song. Stating \"There is a reason that the infectious groove/theme that Wyclef and I created on 'Maria Maria' still resonates today. It speaks to the heart. DJ Khaled, Rihanna and Bryson take that vibe and bring it to a new dimension with 'Wild Thoughts,' but the groove and essence of the song is still intact.\" continuing to say, \"I am honored that DJ Khaled, Rihanna & Bryson felt the intense intentionality of 'Maria Maria' and have shared this summer vibe with the world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/carlos-santana-approves-of-dj-khaled-rihanna-and-bryson-tillers-wild-thoughts-news.34054.html?|title=DJ Khaled, Rihanna & Bryson Tiller's \"Wild Thoughts\" Approved by Carlos Santana|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[The Product G&B]] who originally sang \"Maria Maria\" had a mixed response to \"Wild Thoughts\". They stated they were grateful and called the song a \"blessing\" noting that when they hear \"Wild Thoughts\" \"you hear 'Maria,' it\u2019s bringing awareness all around.\" However they believed that \"Wild Thoughts\" had stripped the original of its meaning and \"its association with West Side Story, where the musical's character \"Maria\" stood to represent both the grim reality of gang violence and poverty and the hope for a better life.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7849262/product-gb-maria-maria-wild-thoughts-sample-interview|title=Product G&B Talk Recording 'Maria Maria' & Being Sampled on 'Wild Thoughts' 17 Years Later: 'It's A Blessing'|website=billboard.com}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nOn June 26, \"Wild Thoughts\" debuted at number four on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], with 89,000 digital copies sold and 36.3 million streams. The song marked Rihanna's 31st top-ten, Khaled's third and Tiller's first. The song's debut additionally marked the third-highest debut of Rihanna's 60 Hot 100 entries and made Rihanna the fourth woman to make at least 60 Hot 100 appearances, joining [[Nicki Minaj]] (78), [[Aretha Franklin]] (73) and [[Taylor Swift]] (70).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7842210/despacito-hot-100-number-one-7th-week-dj-khaled-rihanna-wild-thoughts|title='Despacito' Tops Hot 100 for 7th Week & DJ Khaled's 'Wild Thoughts,' Featuring Rihanna & Bryson Tiller, Debuts at No. 4|website=billboard.com}}</ref> In its second week the song rose to a new peak of three on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, becoming the first song to debut in the top five and rise in its second week since Eminem's \"The Monster\", also featuring Rihanna (2013).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7850288/luis-fonsi-daddy-yankee-justin-bieber-despacito-hot-100-imagine-dragons-top-10|title=Luis Fonsi & Daddy Yankee Rule Hot 100, Imagine Dragons Hit Top 10|website=billboard.com}}</ref> After slipping to number four on the Hot 100, \"Wild Thoughts\" rebounded to peak in the runner-up slot and remained there for seven consecutive weeks, but was blocked off the top spot only by [[Luis Fonsi]], [[Daddy Yankee]] and [[Justin Bieber]]'s \"[[Despacito]]\". It also earned Rihanna her record-extending 29th Radio Songs top 10, continuing her lead over [[Mariah Carey]] (23). \"Wild Thoughts\" additionally peaked at number one on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart, becoming Rihanna's seventh number one, Khaled's third and Tiller's first.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7866232/despacito-hot-100-ten-weeks-ed-sheeran-top-5-record|title='Despacito' Leads Hot 100 for 10th Week, Ed Sheeran Ties Record & Shawn Mendes Hits Top 10|website=billboard.com}}</ref>\n\n\"Wild Thoughts\" became Khaled's and Tiller's first number-one song on the [[Dance Club Songs]], and Rihanna's 31st.<ref name=\"Wild Thoughts Dance Club\">{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Gordon|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7933932/dj-khaled-dance-club-songs-wild-thoughts|title=DJ Khaled Crowns Dance Club Songs for First Time With 'Wild Thoughts'|work=Billboard|date=August 18, 2017|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref> It is Rihanna's fourth number-one on the chart in 2017, following \"[[Love on the Brain]]\", \"[[Sex with Me]]\" and \"[[Pose (Rihanna song)|Pose]]\", the most among all acts; she is one of only four acts to have achieved four number-ones in a calendar year, one of two to do so twice, and the only one to have done so five times.<ref name=\"Wild Thoughts Dance Club\"/> \"Wild Thoughts\" is also only one of four out of her 31 chart-toppers whereby Rihanna is not the lead artist.<ref name=\"Wild Thoughts Dance Club\"/>\n\nOn July 21, \"Wild Thoughts\" reached number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"UK\" /> It is Khaled's second number one in the UK following \"[[I'm the One (DJ Khaled song)|I'm the One]]\", Rihanna's ninth, and the first chart-topper for Tiller.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2017/07/21/dj-khaled-rihanna-bryson-tiller-hit-no-1-in-the-u-k-with-wild-thoughts/|title=DJ Khaled, Rihanna & Bryson Tiller Hit No. 1 In The U.K. With 'Wild Thoughts'|work=[[Forbes]]|last=McIntyre|first=Hugh|date=July 21, 2017|accessdate=July 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] for \"Wild Thoughts\", directed by [[Colin Tilley]], was shot in the [[Little Haiti]] neighborhood of Miami, Florida, in June 2017.<ref name=\"rapup\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2017/06/06/dj-khaled-rihanna-bryson-tiller-music-video-shoot/?image=1|title=DJ Khaled, Rihanna, & Bryson Tiller Shoot Video in Miami|work=[[Rap-Up]]|date=June 6, 2017|accessdate=June 15, 2017}}</ref> The first images from the shoot were released online on June 6, 2017.<ref name=\"rapup\" /> The video premiered via Khaled's [[Vevo]] channel on June 16, 2017.<ref name=\"ew\" /><ref name=\"xxl2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/video/2017/06/dj-khaled-rihanna-bryson-tiller-wild-thoughts-video/|title=DJ Khaled, Rihanna and Bryson Tiller Head to Little Haiti in \"Wild Thoughts\" Video|work=XXL|date=June 16, 2017|accessdate=June 16, 2017}}</ref>\nKatie Skinner from ''Billboard Magazine'' gave an in-depth review of Rihanna's fashion throughout the music video. Skinner stated that the video had an \"upbeat summer nightlife vibe in a tropical Miami setting\" which \"Rihanna and Khaled carry out that concept by dressing in bright-hued outfits, serving up some serious polychromatic summer looks straight off the runway.\"\nDuring a breakdown of the video Skinner stated that Rihanna's first look saw her wearing a \"psychedelic Balenciaga high-waisted floral-print leggings with matching \"Knife\" boots, a bright-pink vintage Betsey Johnson crop top and a pair of oversize crescent-shape Lynn Ban earrings.\" This was accompanied by a floral head scarf, green vintage Versace belt and a pair of pink Karen Walker sunglasses. In the following scene Rihanna wore a \"short turquoise off-the-shoulder silk chiffon dress by Alberta Ferretti\" along with a pair of gladiator sandals designed by Rihanna and Manolo Blahnik. During the last few seconds of the video, Rihanna stands beside Khaled and Tiller, wearing a bright nylon off-the-shoulder top and cargo pants designed by Matthew Adams Dolan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/lifestyle/7833840/rihanna-fashion-dj-khaled-wild-thoughts-video|title=Here Is Every Tropical Outfit Rihanna Wore in DJ Khaled's 'Wild Thoughts' Video|publisher=Billboard}}</ref>\n\n==Remixes==\nOn July 10, 2017, American rappers [[A Boogie wit da Hoodie]] and [[Fabolous]] released their remix of the song titled \"Wild Thots\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/new-music/2017/07/a-boogie-wit-da-hoodie-fabolous-wild-thots/|title=A Boogie Wit Da Hoodie and Fabolous Rap About \"Wild Thots\" on New Single|work=XXL|date=July 10, 2017|accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> Canadian singer and rapper [[Tory Lanez]] also released his remix of the track featuring American singer [[Trey Songz]] on July 21, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/tory-lanez-wild-thoughts-swave-session-feat-trey-songz-new-song.1975092.html|title=Tory Lanez - Wild Thoughts (Swave Session) Feat. Trey Songz|work=HotNewHipHop|date=July 21, 2017|accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Organization\n! Award\n! Result\n! R\n|-\n| rowspan=\"13\" | 2017\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[2017 MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Awards]]\n| [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" | <ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/mtv-vmas-nominations-2017-list-full-1023884 |title=VMAs: Kendrick Lamar Tops Nominations as MTV Continues to Eliminate Gendered Categories |date=July 25, 2017 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Collaboration|Best Collaboration]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Video Music Award for Song of Summer|Song of Summer]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[2017 BET Hip Hop Awards|BET Hip Hop Awards]]\n| Best Hip Hop Video\n| {{Nominated}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" | <ref>{{Cite news |url=http://